<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--SwanKilling     08-29 0166</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Swan Killing,0171</SECOND>
<HEAD>Football Player Gets 30-Day Suspended Sentence for Killing Swan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KALAMAZOO, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A college football player who admitted
ripping the head off a swan at Western Michigan University received
a 30-day suspended jail sentence Tuesday.
   Kalamazoo District Judge James Coyle also sentenced Paul Johnson,
20, of Rockford, Ill., to two years probation and ordered him to pay
$175 in restitution.
   Johnson pleaded guilty earlier this summer to killing the swan.
   Authorities believe Johnson and teammate Bradley Willis, 19, of
Rossville, Ill., were drunk when they killed the swan April 18.
   Willis pleaded innocent, and faces a jury trial next month.
   University officials banned the students from the football team
until Jan. 1 for destroying university property, and ordered them to
undergo alcohol counseling and to perform 100 hours of community
service at the Kellogg Bird Sanctuary.
   Killing a protected waterfowl is a misdemeanor punishable by up
to 90 days in jail and a $1,000 fine. Authorities estimated bird's
value at $350.
</TEXT>
