<DOCNO> AP890829-0007 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 2358EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-TwoForks 1stLd-Writethru a0630 08-29 0621</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Two Forks, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0630,0633</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Plans to Continue Veto Process for Dam, Officials Say</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with quotes and reaction from
EPA official, mayor, governor, Nebraska's senators; picks up 10th graf,
`Environmental groups....'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HILLIARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency will press on
with an effort to kill Denver's proposed $500 million Two Forks dam
because of the damage it would cause to the environment, an EPA
official said Tuesday.
   The 615-foot-high dam to be built near the confluence of the
South Platte River and its North Fork would flood 30 miles of scenic
river valley and canyon and the town of Deckers to provide drinking
water for up to 360,000 new Denver-area residents.
   Opponents, including several environmental groups, have called
the project ``the biggest ecological disaster'' in Colorado history.
   ``The Two Forks dam and reservoir project would result in the
loss of a major aquatic resource which provides irreplaceable stream
fishery habitat and recreational resources near the Denver
metropolitan area,'' said Lee DeHihns, the EPA deputy regional
administrator from Atlanta who reviewed the project for five months.
   DeHihns said he was recommending continuation of the veto process
started by EPA administrator William Reilly on March 24. The next
step in the process is two months of public hearings. The final
decision will be made at EPA headquarters in Washington, but DeHihns
said vetoes are rarely overturned.
   ``I caution that there are still powerful forces aligned against
us,'' Two Forks opponent Sen. Jim Exon, D-Neb., said in a statement
released by his Washington office.
   ``You simply can't leave us high and dry,'' Mayor Federico Pena
said at a news conference Tuesday. ``We have not been given a fair,
objective appraisal of this project.''
   DeHihns said in response to Pena's remarks: ``I'm not happy
they're upset. But I'm obliged to carry out my responsibilities
under the law.''
   Gov. Roy Romer, a onetime Two Forks supporter, was noncommittal
about DeHihns' decision. He said he hoped the cooperation forged
between Denver and its suburbs in their drive to build the project
would not deteriorate.
   EPA officials said DeHihns had two options besides continuing the
veto process _ letting the project proceed or attaching additional
environmental requirements that would have to be met before the
project could proceed.
   But after more than 160 hours of meetings with Two Forks backers
and foes, DeHihns' apparently remained unconvinced the project could
be built without inflicting serious environmental damage.
   The dam 25 miles southwest of Denver was proposed by the Denver
Water Board and 42 area water providers. They said the dam is needed
to meet Denver's future water needs.
   DeHihns said metropolitan Denver appears to have adequate water
supplies for now, and could put more water conservation measures in
place.
   ``This is not just a statement to the people of Denver,'' said
Sen. Bob Kerrey, D-Neb. ``We should hear this message too.''
   Environmental groups said the dam would flood a premier trout
stream and dry up wildlife habitat in Nebraska. Nebraska Gov. Kay
Orr opposes the project.
   Denver Water Board spokesman Ed Ruetz denied the downstream
habitat would dry up if the dam were built.
   Another board member, Monte Pascoe, said the agency would
challenge DeHihns' decision and demand more EPA involvement in
future Denver water decisions.
   Audubon Society President Peter A.A. Berle said DeHihns deserves
``the heartfelt praise and gratitude of all concerned Americans''
because of his decision.
   ``This recommendation brings us one step closer to a total
victory for common sense and for the environment,'' said Melinda
Kassen of the Environmental Defense Fund. ``There are less costly
and less destructive ways to supply the Denver metropolitan area
with water.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
