<FIRST>r w PM-TreasuryBills     08-29 0199</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Treasury Bills,180</SECOND>
<HEAD>Six-Month Bills Highest Since June</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest rates on short-term Treasury
securities are mixed, with rates on three-month bills declining
slightly while rates on six-month bills are at their highest level
since mid-June.
   The Treasury Department sold $7.2 billion in three-month bills
Monday at an average discount rate of 7.94 percent, down from 7.99
percent last week. Another $7.2 billion was sold in six-month bills
at an average discount rate of 7.88 percent, up from 7.85 percent
last week.
   The rates on three-month bills matched the rates Aug. 7 and were
the lowest since three-month bills sold for 7.65 percent on July 31.
The rates on six-month bills were the highest since June 19 when
they averaged 8.08 percent.
   The new discount rates understate the actual return to investors
_ 8.21 percent for three-month bills with a $10,000 bill selling for
$9,799.30 and 8.32 percent for a six-month bill selling for
$9,601.60.
   In a separate report, the Federal Reserve said Monday that the
average yield for one-year Treasury bills, the most popular index
for making changes in adjustable rate mortgages, rose to 8.36
percent last week, up from 8.30 percent the previous week.
</TEXT>
