<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0049EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Voyager-Neptune Bjt   08-29 0713</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Voyager-Neptune, Bjt,0735</SECOND>
<HEAD>Last-Minute Adjustments Saved Voyager's Photos of Icy Triton</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: News briefing 12:30 p.m. EDT; top prospects uncertain.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE SIEGEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PASADENA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voyager's pictures of Neptune's moon
Triton _ which revealed a unique world of icy volcanoes _ might have
been washed out if not for last-minute adjustments to the
spacecraft's cameras, NASA says.
   ``It wouldn't have wiped out the mission, but would have made a
lot of photographs embarrassingly overexposed,'' said Rich Terrile,
an astronomer at the National Aeronautics and Space Administration's
Jet Propulsion Laboratory. ``It would have been an incredible
disappointment.''
   ``They would have been white images,'' Voyager project scientist
Edward Stone said Monday.
   Meanwhile, scientists said the spacecraft found that Triton is
the coldest body ever measured in the solar system, and that Neptune
has something in common with Los Angeles: smog.
   Only days before Voyager made its closest approach to Neptune
last Thursday and zipped past Triton on Friday, scientists
recognized that the frosty surface of Neptune's largest moon
reflected much more light than originally expected, said Mary Beth
Murrill, a JPL spokeswoman.
   Engineers compensated by sending Voyager new computer commands
reducing the exposure time on its television cameras from 6.68
seconds to 3.84 seconds for the best close-ups of Triton, Murrill
said.
   Those photographs revealed that giant craters, called calderas,
once oozed an icy form of lava that flooded thousands of square
miles of lunar terrain. They also found what scientists believe are
active ice volcanoes that explosively propel frozen nitrogen
particles 20 miles skyward.
   During its Neptune encounter, Voyager's cameras discovered six
moons in addition to Triton and Nereid, which were discovered from
Earth. They also found three thin rings of debris and five broad
rings encircling the solar system's fourth-largest planet.
   NASA engineers are investigating the feasibility of reprogramming
Voyager to take a snapshot of the entire solar system sometime in
the coming months, said Lanny Miller, manager of the flight
engineering office.
   By 9 p.m. PDT tonight, Voyager will be 2.76 billion miles from
Earth and 4.55 million miles behind Neptune, speeding toward the
edge of the solar system at 37,568 mph.
   Voyager 2's ultraviolet detector determined Triton's surface
temperature is 400 degrees below zero Fahrenheit, making the moon
``the coldest body we have seen in the solar system,'' said Roger
Yelle of the University of Arizona.
   Scientists believe Pluto and its moon Charon are the
second-coldest bodies in the solar system.
   Voyager also found smog on Neptune.
   Sunlight hitting natural gas, or methane, high in the planet's
atmosphere converts it into a 90-mile-thick icy layer of
photochemical smog at the bottom of Neptune's stratosphere, said Jim
Pollock, an imaging team member from NASA's Ames Research Center in
Mountain View, Calif.
   ``Photochemical smog exists any place we've been that has an
atmosphere,'' imaging team leader Bradford Smith said of other
planets and moons.
   ``In Los Angeles, the problem is it's happening way down low
where we have to breathe it in amounts exceeding anything we've seen
except on Titan,'' he said, referring to Saturn's smoggy moon.
   In another finding, the best close-up shot of the Neptunian moon
1989 N1 showed it has a huge crater half the width of its
lumpy-looking, 240-mile-wide surface.
   That indicates that a big meteorite once smacked into 1989 N1,
one of the six moons discovered by Voyager since June, Smith said.
   Voyager found earlier that 1989 N1 really is Neptune's
second-largest moon after Triton. Scientists previously thought
Nereid was No. 2.
   Instruments aboard Voyager discovered Neptune is encircled by
electrically charged particles that form a giant doughnut shape,
called a torus.
   The torus is created by gases coming off of Triton, said Ralph
McNutt, of the Massachusetts Institute of Technology. Jupiter is
orbited by a similar torus of sulfur particles spewed by sulfur
volcanoes on the Jovian moon Io.
   The space probe also found Neptune and Triton have auroras
vaguely like Earth's northern and southern lights. They glow in
ultraviolet light wavelengths invisible to the human eye, however,
unlike Earth's visible auroras.
   Voyager's close encounter with Neptune last week capped its epic
tour of the four outer planets, including Jupiter, Saturn and
Uranus. The probe was launched in 1977 along with its twin, Voyager
1, which explored only Jupiter and Saturn.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0016 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0047EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-IranianArrest     08-29 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Iranian Arrest,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Iranian Opposition Figure Arrested on Visa Charge</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior Iranian opposition figure has been
arrested in Los Angeles on a visa fraud charge, authorities said
Monday.
   Aladdin Touran, a senior official of the People's Mojahedin
Organization of Iran, was arrested Aug. 21 at Los Angeles
International Airport by agents of the FBI, the State Department and
other federal agencies, FBI spokesman Fred Reagan said.
   Touran, a member of the Mojahedin's international relations
department, was wanted for allegedly entering the United States in
August 1988 with a fraudulent visa at Dulles International Airport
outside Washington, D.C., Reagan said.
   The charge was contained in a complaint issued by the Eastern
District U.S. Attorney's Office in Virginia.
   A spokesman for the Mojahedin condemned the arrest of a top
leader the organization says is under a death sentence issued in
absentia by the Iranian government. Ali Reza Jafarzadeh said the
arrest was an effort by the Bush administration to improve relations
with Iran in its attempts to win release of American hostages held
by pro-Iranian groups in Lebanon.
   The opposition group has engaged in combat with the Iranian
regime, even taking up arms in the Iran-Iraq war.
   Touran, 33, was being held without bail Monday at the federal
Metropolitan Detention Center in Los Angeles, U.S. Attorney's
spokeswoman Grace Denton said.
   U.S. Magistrate Ralph Geffen scheduled an identification hearing
for Touran for Sept. 6, Ms. Denton said. Touran probably would be
extradited to Virginia to face the charge if he doesn't enter a plea
in Los Angeles, she said.
   Touran was arrested as he stepped off a Scandinavian Airlines
flight from Copenhagen, Reagan said. Touran was carrying Swedish
travel documents issued in the name of Noori-Elika, said Claes
Jernaeus, press attache to the Swedish consulate in Los Angeles.
   Touran used the name Noori-Elika for security purposes, fearing
retribution from the Iranian regime, Jefarzadeh said. He also said
Touran's use of the other name when travelling was well-known by
European and American officials.
   Jefarzadeh said Touran had a Swedish politica refugee passport
and lived in Stockholm. He said Touran had come to Los Angeles to
meet with other members of the Mojahedin when he was arrested.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
