<DOCNO> AP890829-0023 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0224EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>x w PM-Trade     08-29 0528</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Trade,510</SECOND>
<HEAD>US Trade Deficit Cut With Industrialized Countries</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States cut its trade deficit with
Western Europe, Japan and industrialized countries of the Far East
in the first half of 1989, but increased its deficit with Third
World countries.
   That's the kind of development many economists have been urging,
saying the United States buys too much from advanced industrial
countries and sells them too little.
   Poorer nations want to expand their sales in the United States
and cut imports.
   If the second half of the year is like the first, the deficit
with Western Europe will be only $4.5 billion, compared with $15.8
billion last year, according to a Commerce Department report
released Monday. No breakdown was given for individual European
countries.
   With the four industrialized areas of the Far East known as the
``four tigers'' _ Hong Kong, South Korea, Singapore and Taiwan _ the
decrease in the deficit would be $6.5 billion, to $22.7 billion.
Those countries have allowed the value of their currencies to rise,
making their goods less attractive in the United States and
encouraging exports.
   The projected drop in the deficit with Japan, however, is only
$1.8 billion, leaving its deficit at $50.9 billion.
   Some economists think the trend won't continue.
   ``This is the end of the good news in trade,'' said Michael
Evans, head of a Washington forecasting company.
   David Wyss of DRI-McGraw Hill said the growth of exports had
slowed with the rise of the price of the dollar over the past 18
months. The increased cost of the dollar in terms of yen and marks,
for example, should make American goods less attractive to Japanese
and West Germans.
   The changes in the projected balance are due to exports,
increasing at a rate of 15 percent to Western Europe, 14 percent to
Japan and 7 percent to the four tigers.
   U.S. deficits were increasing at a rate of $7 billion with OPEC
countries, $1 billion with China and $200 million with Mexico.
   U.S. sales of farm goods were growing more rapidly _ 13 percent _
than minerals and manufactured products _ 12 percent. There was a 24
percent surge in imports of petroleum, which is coming in at the
fastest rate since 1985 and at higher prices.
   Other kinds of imports increased more slowly, though Mexican
sales showed a strong increase of 14 percent to a rate of $2.9
billion. From Japan, the increased rate was only 4 percent, and 6
percent from Hong Kong, South Korea, Singapore and Taiwan.
   In the second quarter, March through June, U.S. farm exports were
almost unchanged from the first quarter. Drops in sales of wheat to
the Soviet Union, soybeans to Western Europe and tobacco to Japan
were offset by increased sales of feed grains to South Korea and
Taiwan.
   Other kinds of exports increased by 4 percent, led by chemicals
and aircraft to Western Europe.
   Imports of passenger cars dropped sharply in the quarter _ 37
percent from West Germany and 9 percent from Japan. However, U.S.
manufacturers increased production in Mexico, which sent 31 percent
more vehicles across the border.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
