<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0248EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a BC-Mexico-Quake     08-29 0167</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Mexico-Quake,0173</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strong Quake Registered Off Mexican Coast</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GOLDEN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A strong earthquake struck off Mexico early
Tuesday, the U.S. Geological Survery reported. There were no
immediate reports of damage or injuries.
   The epicenter of the quake, measuring 6.5 on the Richter scale,
was in the Pacific about 250 miles southwest of Guadalajara off
Jalisco state, said Waverly Person of the survey's National
Earthquake Information Center in Golden.
   In Mexico, there were no immediate reports of damage or injuries.
   The earthquake struck at 12:16 a.m. EDT. It is not yet known if
there were any ships in the area or if there were any aftershocks
which may have caused trouble for boats.
   The Richter scale is a measure of ground motion as recorded on
seismographs. Every increase of one number means a tenfold increase
in magnitude. Thus a reading of 7.5 reflects an earthquake 10 times
stronger than one of 6.5.
   A quake of 6.5 on the Richter scale can cause widespread heavy
damage.
</TEXT>
