<FIRST>r a PM-Obit-Boatman     08-29 0214</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Obit-Boatman,0223</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hee-Haw Director Dead of Accidental Shooting</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LA11 of Aug. 28</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bob Boatman, director of the syndicated
television show ``Hee Haw'' for 17 years, accidentally shot himself
to death with a pistol, authorities say.
   Boatman, 59, was found Monday in the garage of his house in
Hendersonville, outside Nashville. He was pronounced dead at
Hendersonville Hospital a short time later.
   Police said Boatman accidentally shot himself in the stomach
after he pulled out a drawer that contained a .22-caliber revolver.
The gun hit the floor and discharged, they said.
   Boatman had been directing ``Hee Haw'' since 1972.
   Producer Sam Louvello said Boatman was a ``warm, honest upright
person and a very laid-back person.''
   ``He was a friend and a consummate professional. I loved him,''
said show regular George Lindsey, also known as ``Goober'' from his
role on The Andy Griffith Show.
   Cast member Lulu Roman called Boatman ``an incredibly gifted and
talented man with a genuine sweet and compassionate spirit.''
   ``He always encouraged me by telling me I was a million-dollar
baby. Bob will always hold a very special place in my heart,'' Roman
said.
   Boatman is survived by his wife, Anne, a manager for The
Nashville Network, the cable music network; seven children and two
grandchildren.
</TEXT>
