<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0312EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-USBases Bjt   08-29 0711</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-US Bases, Bjt,0728</SECOND>
<HEAD>Senate Seeks Closure of U.S. Bases, Challenges Mrs. Aquino</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate calls to close U.S. military
bases in two years have increased pressure on President Corazon
Aquino and set the stage for difficult talks with Washington on the
future of the strategically important installations.
   Mrs. Aquino has refused to say whether she favors keeping the six
U.S. bases, which employ more than 70,000 Filipinos. But opposition
Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, one of the co-sponsors of a resolution
seeking the base closures, said the proposal is aimed at forcing her
to take a stand.
   U.S. and Filipino officials are to begin talks later this year on
a new treaty to replace the Military Bases Agreement, which expires
in September 1991. Mrs. Aquino is expected to discuss the issue when
she visits Washington in November.
   ``That Senate resolution looks like the genie out of the
bottle,'' wrote former presidential spokesman Teodoro Benigno in the
Philippine Daily Star. ``And it will take a lot of political genius
on the part of the Aquino administration to put the genie back in
the bottle.''
   Twelve senators sponsored the resolution last Thursday. Under the
constitution, any agreement must be approved by two-thirds of the
23-member Senate, so the resolution shows the Aquino administration
lacks the votes for ratification.
   U.S. officials claim the installations, including Clark Air Base
and the Subic Bay naval base, are essential for maintaining the
military balance in the Far East and protecting sea lanes to
pro-Western nations such as Japan, Singapore and Thailand.
   About 40,000 U.S. troops, military dependents and civilian
employees are stationed at the bases, among the oldest and largest
U.S. garrisons abroad.
   Assuming Mrs. Aquino supports an extension, she has a number of
options for pressuring the Senate into ratification. Most political
surveys indicate a majority of Filipinos support the bases, which
pay more than $96 million in local salaries annually.
   But the Senate's view reflects that of the nationalistic urban
classes, which see the bases as a vestige of colonialism. Political
analysts say Mrs. Aquino could call for a referendum on the bases
and then pressure the Senate into accepting the national will.
   Mrs. Aquino could also use a discrepancy between U.S. and
Filipino interpretation of the expiration date.
   The constitution says the agreement expires in 1991. But U.S.
officials say the agreement actually says that after Sept. 16, 1991,
either side can terminate with one-year's notice. Without
notification, the agreement runs indefinitely, they say.
   U.S. Ambassador Nicholas Platt prefers to sidestep the ambiguity,
saying he would like a new agreement negotiated and ratified before
the 1991 cutoff.
   Faced with Senate rejection, the Aquino administration could
delay the ratification vote until after a new Congress is elected in
May 1992, four months before the end of the notification period.
   In any event, most analysts see long and difficult negotiations
before any new agreement can be forged. This is due in part to a
wide gap between U.S. and Filipino views of the bases.
   To Washington, the bases are America's contribution to the
defense of the Philippines, a commitment that transcends dollars and
cents. Because the bases are here, the United States would defend
the Philippines with American blood.
   As an island people hundreds of miles removed from the Asian
mainland, Filipinos do not perceive an external threat. To them, the
threat is internal _ Communist and Moslem insurgents. In those
conflicts, the bases are irrelevant.
   Therefore, Filipino officials view the bases as a business deal,
a means of luring U.S. economic aid.
   ``She is not pro-bases per se,'' wrote Benigno of Mrs. Aquino.
``Like many Filipinos, she is pro-bases only because she is
convinced she can use the bases for extracting the maximum
assistance or rental from the Americans.''
   Platt, however, says the United States is not prepared to pay
more. Last October, Washington agreed to pay $461 million a year to
keep the bases until 1991.
   ``I told them that if they are waiting for foreign aid to more
than double, they have a long wait coming,'' said Rep. Patricia
Schroeder, D-Colo., who visited the Philippines this month. ``Either
a base is necessary for mutual defense or it is not.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0315EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--China-FSMRelations     08-29 0163</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--China-FSM Relations,0166</SECOND>
<HEAD>China-Federated States of Micronesia Initiate Diplomatic Relations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KOLONIA, Federated States of Micronesia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   China and the
Federated States of Micronesia agreed today to establish full
diplomatic relations.
   Zai Zhang, China's ambassador to Australia, and Andon Amaraich,
the federated states' secretary for external affairs, signed a joint
communique making relations official.
   The federated states recognize the People's Republic of China as
the sole legal government of China, according to the document. Zhang
said China will assist the federated states in joining international
organizations such as the Asian Development Bank.
   The federate states extend across the 1,800-mile-long Caroline
Island archipelago and include the states of Pohnpei, Kosrae, Truk
and Yap, all formerly part of the U.S. Trust Territory of the
Pacific.
   The states, with a population of about 85,000 and located about
3,000 miles southwest of Hawaii, entered into a free association
with the United States in 1986, terminating the trust territory
control established by the United Nations in 1947.
</TEXT>
