<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0335EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-UndergroundAbortions     08-29 0502</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Underground Abortions,0518</SECOND>
<HEAD>1970s Underground Abortion Group Prepares to Pass the Torch</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHERI T. PRASSO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The threat of court and legislative action to
restrict or outlaw abortion is leading some women to consider
reviving an old underground movement that performed clandestine
abortions.
   The group _ called Jane after a pseudonym some of the women used
at the time _ performed as many as 13,000 abortions in the four
years before the U.S. Supreme Court legalized the procedure in 1973,
said former organizer Jody Howard.
   The high court's decision July 3 allowing states to place
restrictions on abortions and the threat of further court
restrictions may make it necessary to revive the group, said Ms.
Howard and Ruth Surgal, another key Jane member.
   ``It's time for new people to move in, a new generation,'' said
Ms. Howard, 48, now a freelance writer. ``I will do everything in my
power to teach them everything I know, but I would hope it wouldn't
be necessary.''
   Jane, believed to have been the only group of its kind in the
United States, involved about 120 Chicago-area women who were
trained, in some cases by sympathetic doctors, to perform abortions.
They worked clandestinely from 1969 to 1972 under constant threat of
arrest.
   ``Already (courts) are making it harder. The laws may make it
illegal, but women are going to keep it available. I'm convinced,''
Ms. Howard said.
   At a recent pro-choice march in Washington, she said, a number of
women from various states said they would establish similar
underground groups and take the movement nationwide if abortion were
outlawed again.
   ``It's easier if you have a role model somehow because it gives
people courage,'' said Ms. Surgal, 51.
   Andrew Scholberg, assistant director of the Chicago-based
Pro-Life Action League, said his group would battle any attempt to
revive an underground abortion network.
   ``We'll see to it that they're prosecuted to the fullest extent
of the law,'' he said. ``We'll have spies, we'll have to have people
claiming to be seeking out abortions ... to find out who the illegal
abortionists are so they can be punished.''
   In addition, he challenged the ability of Jane members to perform
abortions safely.
   ``I seriously doubt their safety record,'' he said. ``No abortion
is safe because it always kills the baby.''
   Women who were active in the group said 3 percent of treated
women developed complications, usually infections, but that no women
died.
   Statistics from The Alan Guttmacher Institute, the New York-based
research branch of Planned Parenthood, placed the complication rate
for abortions performed by doctors at about 1 percent.
   Seven Jane members were arrested in 1972 despite frequent changes
in locations where the abortions were performed. The charges were
dropped after the Roe vs. Wade ruling that legalized abortion.
   Ms. Howard said she would risk going to jail to give women the
freedom to choose abortion.
   ``What's more important, my staying out of jail or a woman having
to have an abortion?'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0031 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0326EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Japan-Markets     08-29 0376</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-Markets,0387</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Slumps, Share Prices Up</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar on Tuesday inched down against the
Japanese yen, while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange gained
moderately.
   The dollar closed at 144.15 yen, down 0.13 yen from Monday's
finish of 144.28 yen. It began trading at 144.58 yen, its high for
the day, and moved as low as 144.00 yen.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues gained 80.24 points, or 0.23 percent, closing at 34,687.65.
   Currency dealers said the dollar remained in a narrow range as
investors were cautious because of a possible intervention by the
central bank and profit-taking as the dollar moved on the upper side
of the 144-yen level.
   The Bank of Japan, which sold dollars Monday to stem the dollar's
rapid rise against the yen, did not intervene in Tokyo morning
dealing, traders said.
   ``I think (the central bank) will have no choice but to intervene
if the dollar reaches about 144.70 yen,'' said a trader of a major
Japanese bank, who spoke anonymously.
   Other dealers said the market was awaiting this week a series of
U.S. economic indicators, including the unemployment figures for
August, due out Friday.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei index rose moderately as
investors hunted incentive-backed issues at the start of trading but
later held back on profit-taking, dealers said.
   Michio Katsumata of Nomura Securities said morning trading was
thin and that there was no effect on overall trading from a planned
merger of two major Japanese banks.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange announced it suspended trading on Mitsui
Bank and Taiyo Kobe Bank for the day to avoid confusion in
connection with the announcement of a planned merger of the two
major Japanese banks next April. ``Tuesday's trading on both issues
was suspended from the start to get investors familar with
information on the merger,'' said Hiroshi Nakamura, an exchange
spokesman.
   Mitsui Bank, the country's seventh-largest bank, and Taiyo Kobe,
the eighth largest, will merge into a bank to be called Taiyo Kobe
Mitsui Bank, the second-largest bank in Japan after the Dai-Ichi
Kangyo Bank, ranked the largest in the world in terms of assets,
executives from the two banks told a news conference Tuesday morning.
</TEXT>
