<FIRST>r a PM-Governor-SecurityThreats     08-29 0280</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Governor-Security Threats,0287</SECOND>
<HEAD>Martinez Security Increased in Wake of Colombian Drug Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRENT KALLESTAD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TALLAHASSEE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Florida law enforcement agents have
increased security around Gov. Bob Martinez because of fears of a
backlash from Colombian drug lords under pressure.
   ``There has been a general warning, a general concern of
high-profile public officials on the subject of drugs,'' Martinez
said Monday. ``The Florida Department of Law Enforcement just feels
a little bit more comfortable, at least in these next few days,
being a little more cautious.''
   The bolstered protection began late Friday after state agents
were tipped by federal sources that Colombian drug lords had
threatened a political assassination in the United States if any of
the targeted drug dealers were extradited from Colombia, Martinez
said.
   The governor said his recent trip to South America to survey
drug-fighting efforts made him a prime target. He also serves as the
National Governors' Association's leader on substance abuse and drug
trafficking.
   Last Friday, Martinez asked Attorney General Richard Thornburgh
to extradite 25 Florida drug fugitives should they be arrested by
Colombian authorities.
   ``I recognize the importance of the United States doing all it
can to ensure that the drug merchants who threaten our society are
brought to justice,'' Martinez wrote.
   Martinez said he understood the threat against American officials
was tied to the scheduled extradition Wednesday of a Colombian drug
dealer.
   Brian Ballard, director of operations for Martinez, said the
governor's public schedule, which is normally published days in
advance for distribution to the press, will now be on a day-to-day
basis.
   Martinez said he had received death threats while Tampa mayor and
also as governor.
</TEXT>
