<FIRST>r a PM-PartyBloodbath     08-29 0318</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Party Bloodbath,0326</SECOND>
<HEAD>Spurned Husband Kills Four At Birthday Party</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An estranged husband burst into his wife's
birthday party and shot and killed her and three other people,
minutes after the woman had called authorities to say she feared an
attack.
   Authorities said Maria Delia Navarro called the sheriff's
department on Sunday night alarmed about a threat from Raymondo
Navarro Jr. About 15 minutes later Navarro crashed the party and
opened fire.
   Navarro, 26, was arrested Monday outside his father's East Los
Angeles apartment and booked for investigation of murder and
attempted murder.
   Mrs. Navarro had been celebrating her 27th birthday with about 20
family members. The other victims were her aunts, Maria Garcia, 65,
and Francisca Arizpe, 62, and a friend, Leticia M. Dipp, 46, said
coroner's spokesman Bob Dambacher.
   A third aunt, Berta Galvan, 47, was listed in critical condition
late Monday with a head wound. Another party guest, Richard
Covarrubias, was listed in serious condition with a wound to the
abdomen.
   The Navarro's three children were not hurt.
   Shortly before the attack, a man called and warned Mrs. Navarro,
``Your husband is coming to kill you.''
   Mrs. Navarro called the 911 emergency line, but a deputy told her
there was nothing police could do until the husband arrived at the
house, according to a transcript of the conversation.
   ``You have to make a judgment call over whether a threat is
emergent or immediate. If he was there with a gun, that would have
gotten a real immediate response,'' Sgt. Lynda Edmonds, a sheriff's
spokeswoman, said Monday. ``People get threatened all the time, but
that's a fact of life.''
   Mrs. Navarro had filed for divorce and custody of the children
about 17 months ago. She and Navarro had been high school
sweethearts. In court records, she contended he physically and
mentally abused her and the children during the past five years.
</TEXT>
