<HEAD>Dollar Down Slightly, Tokyo Stocks Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar inched down against the Japanese yen
today while share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange gained
moderately following a five-day decline.
   The dollar closed at 144.15 yen, down 0.13 yen from Monday's
finish of 144.28 yen, a nine-week high. It opened today at 144.58
yen, its high for the day, and ranged as low as 144.00 yen in the
day's trading.
   Currency dealers said dollars were being sold to take profits.
   A dealer at Daiichi Kangyo Bank added that when the dollar climbs
above 144.50 yen, ``players get nervous about intervention'' by the
central bank.
   Fear of intervention kept the dollar in a narrow range today,
said the dealer.
   Dealers also said the market was awaiting a series of U.S.
economic indicators, including unemployment figures for August, due
out Friday.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues rose 80.24 points, or 0.23 percent, closing at 34,687.65.
   The gain followed a total loss of 533.42 points, or 1.5 percent,
over the previous five trading days.
   Profit-taking late in the day checked the index's rise, dealers
said.
   They said high-priced issues, such as CSK and Daiei, were bought
actively.
   Michio Katsumata of Nomura Securities said morning trading was
``thin'' and there was no effect on overall trading from news of a
planned merger of two major Japanese banks.
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange announced it had suspended trading in
shares of the two banks _ Mitsui Bank and Taiyo Kobe Bank _ all day
today to avoid confusion in connection with the announcement of
their planned merger next April.
   ``Tuesday's trading in both issues was suspended from the start
so investors could become familar with information on the merger,''
said Hiroshi Nakamura, spokesman of the exchange.
   Mitsui Bank, the country's seventh largest bank, and Taiyo Kobe,
the eighth largest, will merge into a bank to be called Taiyo Kobe
Mitsui Bank, executives of the two banks said at a news conference
this morning.
   In terms of assets, it would be the world's second largest bank
after Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, also of Japan.
