<FIRST>r i PM-UN-Contras     08-29 0447</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-UN-Contras,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>UN Chief Tells Security Council he Needs Contras' Cooperation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar
says he plans to contact the U.S.-backed Nicaraguan rebels to obtain
their cooperation with a peace plan calling for their disarmament.
   Five Central American nations have asked the United Nations to
monitor the voluntary disbanding of up to 11,000 Contras camped in
Honduras, and the repatriation of as many as 12,000 of their
dependents.
   ``They are asking us to monitor operations to disarm the
opposition, and that is something that is very complicated and is
not very much in our practice,'' Perez de Cuellar said after
briefing the Security Council on Monday.
   ``That is why I need assurances that if we send people there,
there is cooperation from the resistance forces,'' he said.
   The presidents of Nicaragua, El Salvador, Honduras, Guatemala and
Costa Rica signed an accord Aug. 7 calling for the disbanding of the
Contras 90 days after a joint resettlement mission of U.N. and
Organization of American States representatives is formed.
   ``We'll be in contact with the resistance, to find ways and means
to be in touch with them in order to have assurances from them that
they will accept disarming, to give their arms to the United
Nations,'' the U.N. chief said.
   These contacts will take place ``as soon as possible,'' he added.
   The secretary-general of the OAS, Joao Clemente Baena Soares of
Brazil, and Perez de Cuellar announced Friday they will launch the
mission Sept. 6.
   By having the ``International Support and Verification
Commission'' begin its work on that date, the OAS and U.N. chiefs
set Dec. 5 as the target date for the voluntary repatriation.
   Numerous Contra field commanders and guerrillas have vowed they
will not give up their fight.
   A U.N. diplomat active in Central American affairs, however, said
preliminary talks with the Contras indicate they are quite willing
to go home or be resettled, and said little resistance is expected.
   The United States had lobbied the Central American nations to
allow the Contras to stay in their camps through the Feb. 25
national elections in Nicaragua, to maintain pressure on the leftist
Sandinista government to allow a fair campaign.
   Even Honduras, however, which has received lavish military and
foreign aid from Washington, agreed earlier this month there was no
justification to continue their mission.
   The United States gives the Contras $4.5 million a month in
non-lethal aid that may also be used for resettlement.
   Congress cut off funds for weapons last year, prompting the
Contras to arrange a truce with Nicaragua's government last year.
Since then they have launched only sporadic raids.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0036 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0500EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-ExxonValdez     08-29 0555</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Exxon Valdez,0572</SECOND>
<HEAD>Inspections of Exxon Valdez Begin</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS GEORGATOS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN DIEGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investigators looking into the nation's worst
oil spill and parties to litigation arising from it have started
inspecting the Exxon Valdez, the supertanker that caused the
disaster.
   Drucella Andersen, a Washington, D.C.-based spokeswoman for the
National Transportation Safety Board, said two of the agency's
investigators arrived Monday at a San Diego shipyard to begin their
anticipated five-day inspection.
   The Valdez is in a National Steel and Shipbuilding Co. dry dock
for a nine-month repair job estimated to cost $25 million.
   The ship's hull was shredded, causing about 11 million gallons of
crude to spill into Alaskan waters, when it struck a reef March 24
in Prince William Sound.
   Andersen said the inspection is the first look at the tanker's
hull outside of the water since the grounding. The inspectors
findings will be included in the NTSB report on the spill, which is
expected to be finished early next year, she said.
   Others in San Diego to examine the Valdez are an Alaskan state
investigator and representatives of Exxon Shipping Co. and the
Alyeska Pipeline Service Co., a consortium of seven oil companies
that includes Exxon, said Andersen.
   The state of Alaska is suing Exxon in connection with the spill,
which devastated hundreds of miles of pristine shoreline and killed
scores of waterfowl and marine wildlife. Alyeska also is a defendant
in the case.
   Les Rogers, an Exxon spokesman in Houston, said the inspections
are being conducted ``because the vessel itself is considered
evidence and they want a first-hand look at it.''
   He declined to elaborate because of the pending litigation.
   Shipyard workers will begin repairing the ship's damaged hull
after the inspections are complete.
   ``We can't start work (until then) because of certain court
orders that restrict any work that would cut or modify the ship,''
said Fred Hallett, NASSCO's vice president of finance and public
relations.
   ``Engineering, procurement and fabrication of steel outside the
ship are continuing, so we are still proceeding with the job. We
just can't proceed with the rip out of the damaged sections of the
hull.''
   The Valdez was towed from Alaska, arriving off the San Diego
coast July 10. It was kept from entering San Diego Bay for three
weeks, however, because of oily slicks sighted near the ship when it
reached Southern California.
   Huge steel plates that were peeled downward from the hull during
the 2,500-mile journey also had to be cut off by divers at sea so
they wouldn't drag bottom in the bay.
   The tanker docked at a NASSCO pier July 30 after the
environmental and navigational problems were fixed to the
satisfaction of state and federal officials.
   The Valdez floated into a dock for the repair work Aug. 15.
   Pumping operations to remove water trapped inside the enclosed
repair dock were completed Friday. The water was transferred to
another Exxon ship, which will take it to a processing facility at
an Exxon refinery in Northern California.
   During the weekend, shipyard workers washed down the dock to
remove sand, silt and marine growth. The debris was put into barrels
and trucked to a San Diego hazardous waste dump for disposal.
   ``The dock is now dry and clean so the appropriate individuals
can inspect the ship,'' Hallett said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
