<FIRST>r a PM-Lites     08-29 0432</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lites,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>On the Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GRAND RAPIDS, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kent County Sheriff's Deputy Jayson
Beute is ready to help deliver babies any time anywhere _ even at a
bait shop.
   Beute helped deliver a healthy baby girl Sunday at the Open
Season Bait Shop, where the baby's frantic parents stopped when they
realized they wouldn't get to a hospital on time.
   ``I put the gloves on and a catcher's mitt, and we did our thing
right in front of the cash register,'' said Beute, who has helped
deliver two other babies in his 15 years with the department.
   The parents, Rusty Parrish, 18, and Stacy Heminger, 19, were 20
minutes into their ride to the hospital at about 6:30 a.m. Sunday,
when Heminger realized they were running out of time.
   ``I told him to pull over and call somebody,'' she said.
   Parrish called police from a pay phone and carried the
mother-to-be to the bait shop.
   Heminger and the infant, Brittany Nicole, were in good condition
Monday at Metropolitan Hospital in Grand Rapids.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>TIFTON, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   No more sniffing and prodding to tell if a
melon is ripe _ government scientists have introduced a fail-safe
method: the melon meter.
   U.S. Department of Agriculture researchers have developed an
infrared device that measures the sugar content of watermelons,
cantaloupes and honeydews.
   Gerald Dull, a USDA chemist in Athens, said 16 years of research
yielded the melon meter, which shines infrared light into the top of
the fruit and then measures the amount of light that comes out the
side.
   The computerized device determines the amount of soluable solids,
based on how much light the fruit absorbs. Soluble solids are
predominantly sugars.
   ``The No. 1 parameter of quality is sweetness,'' Dull said in an
interview. ``If you haven't got sweetness, you haven't got a good
melon.''
   Growers and consumers currently have to rely on appearance in
judging ripeness and quality, Dull said, but similar-looking melons
can vary from 5 percent to 10 percent in sweetness.
   ``There's no one who can look at the outside and tell you whether
that melon is good,'' he said.
   Several companies have expressed an interesting in producing
melon meters, Dull said, and they probably will be installed
initially in packing sheds, where the fruit is graded, packed and
shipped.
   He believes they will appeal to suppliers who want to provide
consumers with the highest quality melons.
   ``I think we're just opening the door'' on analyzing fresh
produce, he said. ``With computers and high-speed equipment, we
might be able to get down to (measuring) the vitamins.''
</TEXT>
