<FIRST>r a PM-Rose     08-29 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Rose,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Giamatti, Rose Differ on Agreement</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Similar version on sports wires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CINCINNATI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Baseball Commissioner A. Bartlett Giamatti said
the agreement banning Pete Rose from baseball leaves Giamatti free
to express his opinion that the former Cincinnati Reds manager bet
on baseball.
   But Rose said he felt double-crossed by Giamatti's remarks, made
during the news conference last Thursday at New York in which the
commissioner announced Rose's lifetime banishment.
   ``Just 12 hours earlier, we signed that agreement in good faith,
and there he was saying he thinks I bet on baseball,'' Rose told The
Cincinnati Post in an interview published Monday.
   ``The only reason I signed that agreement was that it had no
finding that I bet on baseball. We got what we wanted, and we didn't
have to go another eight months and spend another three-quarters of
a million dollars,'' Rose said.
   On Monday, Giamatti said that Rose appeared to misunderstand the
agreement.
   ``I was very clear about the fact that I was not going to be
constrained from saying what I thought was the case,'' Giamatti told
The Associated Press by telephone from Cape Cod, Mass. ``I'm not
going to change anything I said.''
   Giamatti, asked at the news conference whether he thought Rose
had bet on baseball, replied, ``Based on the evidence and in the
absence of a hearing, I have concluded that, yes, he bet on
baseball.''
   Deputy commissioner Francis Vincent, Jr., and Rose's lawyer,
Reuven Katz, drafted the agreement, which includes a stipulation
that Rose neither admits nor denies betting on baseball.
   Katz acknowledged that Vincent had told him what Giamatti's
reponse would be to a question about whether Rose bet on baseball.
   ``That's true, he did,'' Katz said. ``Maybe I misunderstood.
Maybe I wasn't altogether clear on what Mr. Giamatti would say. I
think that I was surprised that (Giamatti's statement) was that
strong, that he put it that way and that it came so fast.''
   Giamatti said he based his opinion on the 225-page report by
baseball investigator John Dowd. The agreement noted that baseball
rules allow Rose to apply for reinstatement after a year but don't
guarantee that he can return.
   Rose said he's considering a television appearance to tell his
side of the story.
   ``We've got some good minds working on it,'' Rose said. ``The key
thing is, we'll tell the story and let the people decide. But I
don't know how I'm going to do it.''
   The Internal Revenue Service and a federal grand jury in
Cincinnati are reportedly investigating whether Rose illegally
concealed winnings from gambling or sales of memorabilia.
   The FBI has dropped an earlier reported investigation of Rose.
</TEXT>
