<HEAD>More Rain in Plains; Roads Flooded in Kansas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms continued in the central Plains this morning after
bringing torrential rain to parts of Kansas and Iowa.
   Several days of thundershowers have left the ground saturated,
especially in eastern Kansas and western Missouri. Flash flood
watches were in effect for northeast and east-central Kansas, part
of northwest Missouri and the southeast corner of Nebraska, where
storms were continuing early today.
   Water covered the highway north of Hanover, Kan., where 2{ inches
of rain fell Monday evening. More than 1} inches of rain fell in
Chase County, and some county roads were under water near Newton.
   Two to 3 inches of rain fell in parts of south-central and
southeast Kansas, and 1\ inches fell at Wichita in one hour. Lamoni,
Iowa, recorded 2.92 inches in the six hours ended at 2 a.m. EDT.
   Thunderstorms also produced three-quarter inch hail in Elk
County, Kan., and marble-size hail fell at Julian in southeast
Nebraska. Winds gusted to near 60 mph in eastern Nemaha County, Neb.
   Thunderstorms also dropped heavy rain on portions of the Middle
Atlantic states. Baltimore received 1.65 inches in one hour and a
total of 2.60 inches in the six hours ended at 2 a.m. EDT.
   Rain and scattered thunderstorms were over the lower Great Lakes
early today.
   Skies were mostly clear this morning from the Dakotas across the
Rockies to the West Coast states. Dense fog developed over northeast
Nebraska, with visibilities down to little more than 100 yards.
   Today's forecast called for widespread showers and thunderstorms
from much of New England across New York and Pennsylvania to the
Ohio Valley; scattered showers and thunderstorms from Michigan
across the middle Mississippi Valley and much of Kansas to the
southern Rockies; and widely scattered thunderstorms from southern
Texas across the Gulf Coast and the Tennessee Valley to the southern
Atlantic states.
   Highs were expected to be in the 70s over the northern Atlantic
coastal states, portions of the Great Lakes and along the Canadian
border from Minnesota to Montana; the 60s and 70s along the Pacific
coast; near 100 degrees in the southern Plains; and between 100 and
105 degrees in the Desert Southwest. Elsewhere, highs were expected
to be in the 80s and 90s.
   Temperatures at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 36 degrees at Yellowstone,
Wyo., to 88 degrees at Phoenix.
