<FIRST>r a PM-HelmsleyTrial     08-29 0340</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Helmsley Trial,0351</SECOND>
<HEAD>Helmsley Bodyguard Found at Jury's Hotel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Leona Helmsley's bodyguards was found in
the hotel where the jurors in her tax evasion trial were sequestered
and rode the elevator with one juror, according to a report today.
   But there was ``an innocent explanation and both the government
and court are satisfied,'' Assistant U.S. Attorney James DeVita told
the New York Post.
   The 12-member jury in Leona Helmsley's tax evasion and extortion
trial was heading into a fourth day of deliberations today.
   Mrs. Helmsley, 69, is charged with evading $1.2 million in
federal taxes by charging personal expenses, including renovations
at her Connecticut mansion, to her businesses.
   DeVita and defense attorney Gerald Feffer would not say why the
unnamed bodyguard was in the hotel Friday night.
   In court papers, U.S. District Court Judge John Walker told
Feffer to ``convey to his client to tell her people to stay out of
the hotel.''
   ``Needless to say, this is not a Helmsley hotel,'' Walker said.
Leona Helmsley and her husband Harry are among the biggest owners of
hotels and other real estate in New York.
   The judge said a federal marshal was escorting a juror back to
her hotel room after dinner Friday when one of Mrs. Helmsley's
security guards got on the same elevator.
   The marshal purposely pushed the elevator button for the wrong
floor so the guard would not know which floor the juror was staying
on, according to the judge in the transcript.
   The juror, misunderstanding the situation, pushed the correct
button. However, the juror and the guard got off the elevator on
different floors.
   ``If the Helmsley security people think they are doing their
client a favor by investigating where the jurors are, the rooms the
jurors are staying in or what floor the jurors are staying in or a
particular hotel, they are not,'' Walker said.
   Two Helmsley guards appeared before the judge, but the transcript
of the hearing, including the identity of the guard in question, was
sealed.
</TEXT>
