<FIRST>r i PM-Britain-Carnival     08-29 0346</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Britain-Carnival,0360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Youths Battle Police at Carnival; 37 Injured</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Thirty officers and seven civilians were injured
when rowdy youths ended an otherwise peaceful Afro-Caribbean
carnival by pelting police with cans and bottles, authorities said
today.
   Scotland Yard said 37 were injured and 250 arrested during the
two-day carnival in the Notting Hill district that ended Monday
night after drawing about 500,000 people.
   St. John Ambulance, however, said it treated 269 people _ 21 of
them policemen _ during the festival. Fifty people were
hospitalized, although there was ``nothing of a serious nature,'' a
spokesman said.
   One officer was stabbed but was not seriously hurt, said the
Yard, headquarters of the London police.
   The Yard said charges against those arrested included possession
of weapons and drugs, and disorderly behavior.
   It blamed groups of youths ``determined to provoke disorder'' for
violence in the carnival's closing hours when police were struck by
tossed cans and bottles.
   Police with riot shields tackled the rampaging youths. The Yard
said about 5,000 officers were on the streets, some on horseback,
and a police helicopter was overhead as the violence flared.
   The clashes took place at the close of what was earlier called
the most peaceful of the Afro-Caribbean festivals that have been
held for 24 years during the late August three-day bank holiday
weekend.
   Deputy assistant police commissioner Charles Rideout said the day
had been ``most successful'' until the clashes.
   Police estimated 200,000 people on Sunday and 300,000 on Monday
jammed the streets to see the spectacularly dressed paraders, street
performers and bands in what has become a cultural focal point for
London's black community.
   Riots, muggings and other violence marred previous festivals and
a man was fatally stabbed in 1987.
   Conservative lawmaker Terry Dicks said the carnival should be
banned because of the cost of policing it, which he estimated at
$1.56 million this year.
   ``There were probably more police on the streets monitoring the
carnival than there were throughout the rest of London. It is
outrageous that we should have to pay for this,'' Dicks said.
</TEXT>
