<FIRST>r a PM-Lutherans     08-29 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lutherans,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Compliance Questioned on Church Call for Divestment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Leaders of the Evangelical Lutheran Church
in America's pensions board say they may not be able to comply with
church's insistence on rapid divestment from companies operating in
South Africa.
   ``Whether the law will permit us to follow this churchwide
directive, I can't answer,'' said investment specialist John Kapanke
of Minneapolis, president of the board.
   The denomination's legislative assembly on Monday voted that by
September 1991 the Board of Pensions be completely rid of stocks in
companies with ``direct or indirect'' business dealings in South
Africa.
   An estimated 80 to 85 percent of the 1,041 delegates voted for
the deadline in a show-of-cards vote. At stake was the church's $1.6
billion pension fund, of which $84.9 million is invested in
companies doing business in South Africa.
   Kapanke and Mildred Berg of New York City, chair of the board,
pointed out the board was incorporated separately from the church
and thus was not legally bound by its instructions, although sharing
its purposes and principles.
   ``The board has a right not to accept it if we feel it is
violating our fiduciary responsibility,'' Ms. Berg said at a news
conference. ``But we take that mandate seriously in regard to
investments.''
   The vote by delegates of the newly merged 5.3 million-member
denomination is intended to put pressure on South Africa to end its
apartheid system of race separation.
   ``It puts teeth into our concern,'' the Rev. Joseph Ellwanger of
Milwaukee said of the deadline. He said if the church can't ``hear
the voices of blacks crying for justice above the call of profit
yield, then it doesn't mean anything to be called the body of
Christ.'
   Before the vote, Kapanke said a deadline threatened financial
responsibility.
   ``It puts us in an almost impossible situation to act in a
prudent way,'' Kapanke said. To ``introduce controls'' over
investing of funds, he said, ``jeopardizes them and increases risk.''
   Ms. Berg said the time limit imposed for the divestment process
was ``too short. We would have great difficulty accomplishing that
goal. We do recognize the frustration of the church about it.''
   Forty-four of the 65 regional synods had demanded total
divestment from South Africa, as had predecessor denominations of
the merged body, but none had fixed a deadline for it.
   The assembly, entering the next to last day of an eight-day
meeting, also approved a major, long-range program, called Mission
90, to strengthen Bible teaching, evangelism and work for the cause
of peace and justice.
   The meeting is the first since the 1988 merger of the Lutheran
Church in America, the American Lutheran Church and the Association
of Evangelical Lutheran Churches.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
