<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0601EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-NewtonFuneral 1stLd-Writethru a0442 08-29 0746</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newton Funeral, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0442,0760</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thousands Mourn Slain Black Panther At Funeral</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS grafs 4-5, `Newton, 47..., with 3 grafs to UPDATE with
Seale remarks, picks up 6th graf pvs, `While Hilliard...; INSERTS 3 grafs
after 15th graf pvs, `Tyrone Robinson..., to UPDATE with report Robinson
pistol-whipped Newton before shooting him, picks up 16th graf pvs, `Police
have...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto FX1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CATALINA ORTIZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   At a funeral for slain Black Panther
co-founder Huey Newton, friends called his death a ``clarion call''
to free black communities of drug-related violence and mourners
chanted ``Free Huey,'' a reminder of an earlier period of militancy.
   ``His problem with chemical dependency represents all our
weaknesses in America,'' said Newton's friend and fellow Panther
David Hilliard during the service Monday.
   Among the 1,200 people attending the service at the Allen Temple
Baptist Church were H. Rap Brown, leader of the Student Non-Violent
Coordinating Committee, and Panther co-founder Bobby Seale. Hundreds
of others milled around in the streets outside.
   Many in the congregation gave raised-fist salutes when Seale, 52,
donned a black beret and said ``all power to the people'' during his
turn at the pulpit.
   The mourners left the church chanting ``Free Huey,'' the refrain
that sounded during Newton's frequent imprisonments beginning in the
1960s.
   Newton, 47, was killed early Aug. 22 in the poor West Oakland
neighborhood where he began organizing blacks more than 20 years
ago. Police said Newton died in a dispute over crack cocaine.
   While Hilliard said Newton's violent death should be used as a
``clarion call'' to solve national problems with drugs and alcohol,
many of the mourners remembered Newton as a hero of the bold and
belligerent black pride movement.
   Members of Newton's family, friends and fellow radicals recalled
the days when the Black Panthers espoused the cause of black
liberation and ``the power of the gun'' against white authority.
   Johnny Spain, a former Black Panther who recently won a new trial
in the 1971 killings of two prison guards, spoke at the funeral
about problems still facing blacks.
   ``After the dust clears and next week, little kids say `Huey
who?' remember that in someone's community ... a human being was
gunned down and that should serve as a notice that there's a lot of
work to do,'' said Spain, 40, who joined the Panthers while serving
time at San Quentin Prison.
   Newton and Seale founded the Black Panther Party in Oakland in
1966. As the party's minister of defense and chief ideologue, Newton
became one of the most articulate leaders of the black militancy
movement.
   The Panthers embraced Maoist political theory and espoused the
use of arms for defense against police, whom they called racist. A
Black Panther poster distributed nationally during the orgnization's
heyday pictured Newton sitting on an African wicker throne, a spear
in one hand, a shotgun in the other.
   Many of Newton's admirers discounted police accounts and blamed
his death on authorities with whom Newton battled for decades.
   Newton had a long criminal history including a manslaughter
conviction in the 1967 shooting death of a police officer. He was
freed after 22 months when an appellate court sent the case back to
trial court.
   While in prison in March on a narcotics paraphernalia possession
charge, Newton received a suspended two-year sentence in connection
with the theft of $15,000 in state funds from community schools
operated by the Panthers.
   Tyrone Robinson, 25, who is accused of shooting Newton, appeared
in court briefly Monday and was ordered by Alameda County Municipal
Court Judge Horace Wheatley to return Sept. 5 to enter a plea.
   Robinson allegedly shot Newton with a companion's gun after
pistol-whipping the former Panther leader with his own gun, which
jammed, the San Francisco Examiner reported today.
   Being struck with the gun ``would explain the trauma to the right
side of Newton's face,'' the report said, quoting from a detailed
log of the investigation kept by Oakland Homicide Sgt. Dan Mercado.
   ``Then Robinson wrestled the witness' gun away from him because
Robinson's gun jammed,'' Mercado said. ``And Robinson fired three
times, striking Newton.''
   Police have said Robinson told them he shot Newton in
self-defense after Newton, who had battled drug and alcohol
addictions, pulled a gun and demanded crack cocaine.
   Police said they don't believe Robinson's account and think the
slaying was his bid to rise in the Black Guerrilla Family, a
drug-running prison-based gang that Newton allegedly had angered.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
