<FIRST>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     08-29 0279</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dollar-Gold,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower, Gold Steady</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. dollar fell in early European trading
today after Asian traders took profits ahead of the release of U.S.
gross national product figures, currency dealers said.
   Gold prices were little changed.
   Trading was still thin following Monday's closure of financial
markets in London and Hong Kong for national holidays.
   Dealers said revised second quarter GNP figures could give new
impetus to the market and lift the dollar out of its tight trading
range.
   GNP is expected to be revised to show growth at a 2.5-percent
annualized rate in the second quarter, up from the previously
reported growth rate of 1.7 percent.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.13 yen to a closing 144.15 yen. Later, in London,
it was quoted at 143.90 yen.
   Other dollar rates in London at midmorning compared with late
Monday's European rates:
   _1.9527 West German marks, down from 1.9650
   _1.6822 Swiss francs, down from 1.6940
   _6.5810 French francs, down from 6.6180
   _2.2068 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2130
   _1,401.50 Italian lire, down from 1,408.00
   _1.1715 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1753
   In London, the dollar fell against the British pound. It cost
$1.5741 to buy one pound, compared with $1.5635 elsewhere in Europe
late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at $359.75 a troy ounce, compared with late
Friday's $360.45. At midmorning, the city's five major bullion
dealers fixed a recommended price of $360.
   In Zurich, the bid was $360.25, up from $359.25 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.29 to close at $360.82.
   Silver was quoted in London at $5.12 a troy ounce, down from
Friday's $5.13.
</TEXT>
