<SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Plane,0161</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rescuers Search Glaciers for Missing Pakistani Airliner</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rescuers inched across the glaciers of
the Korakoram Mountains today in search of a Pakistani airliner
carrying 54 people that vanished four days ago.
   However, low clouds and rain continued to hamper an air search
over the rugged peaks where the twin-engine Fokker 27 Friendship was
presumed to have crashed Friday.
   ``The weather is a little better but still not good,'' said A.M.
Sarooqi, a spokesman for Pakistan International Airlines in
Islamabad, headquarters of the search. ``We have been able to get
some sorties up but visibility is a problem.''
   Two British trekkers reported seeing a low-flying plane Friday
near the 26,606-foot Nanga Parbat, or ``Naked Mountain.''
   The propeller-driven Fokker carrying 49 passengers and five crew
disappeared en route from Gilgit to Islamabad, 175 miles to the
south. The 45-minute trip offers a breathtaking view of the western
Himalayas and the eastern Korakorams.
