<FIRST>r i PM-Ireland-Bomb     08-29 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ireland-Bomb,0207</SECOND>
<HEAD>Irish Police Find Huge Bomb Near Border With Northern Ireland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DUBLIN, Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police today said they found a 1,500-pound
bomb less than two miles from the border with Northern Ireland and
believe it is the largest ever found in the Irish Republic.
   The bomb was primed when it was discovered Sunday in the back of
a van at Omeath, County Louth, and was probably destined for use by
the Irish Republican Army inthe British province, police said.
   Sunday was the 10th anniversary of the IRA's murder of Lord
Mountbatten, a cousin of Queen Elizabeth II, and of 18 British
soldiers.
   A police spokesman said the bomb was made of homemade explosives
packed into three steel drums that were wired together. Along with
the bomb, police found drogue bombs, devices that can penetrate
armor plating, as well as bomb timers and fuse wires.
   Houses in the area were evacuated and roads were closed until the
bomb could be dismantled.
   Police said they were questioning two men who had been arrested
under Ireland's anti-terrorist laws.
   The IRA wants to end Britain's rule of Northern Ireland and unite
the predominantly Protestant province with the Roman Catholic Irish
Republic.
</TEXT>
