<FIRST>r a PM-BangladeshiGirl     08-29 0644</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bangladeshi Girl,0663</SECOND>
<HEAD>State Says It Will Fight Deportation Of Girl From Bangladesh</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID AMMONS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OLYMPIA, Wash. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The state will fight the deportation of a
9-year-old Bangladeshi girl who was molested by the man who brought
her to America.
   More than 200 people marched to the state capitol on Monday to
express their opposition to deporting the youngster, known as Kushi,
and afterwards they were rewarded. State officials said they would
try to obtain an education visa for the girl, allowing her to stay
indefinitely.
   The girl was taken by state workers from a foster home last week
because it wasn't ``culturally relevant.'' The girl's foster parents
were among the marchers who demanded help for the youngster.
   The state Child Protective Services said it would review the case
and fight deportation. Spokeswoman Irene Hopman said an education
visa would be sought from the federal Immigration and Naturalization
Service. She faces deportation when her visa expires Sept. 5.
   The girl is one of several members of a Bangladeshi family that
Stefan Christopher, 52, brought to this country. A U.N. consultant,
he had married one of the girl's older sisters, separated from her
and married another sister, age 12. Over the years he brought family
members to work on his Oakville farm.
   Christopher is in jail awaiting sentencing after pleading guilty
to taking indecent liberties with the girl and two other children.
Sheriff's department officials said he subjected them to ``physical
and psychological torture.''
   At the rally, the foster parents _ chemical engineer Bob Martin
and his wife, English teacher Betsy Seidel _ wept when they were
surrounded by supporters. They had feared the state would allow
Kushi to be sent back to Bangladesh where she would be outcast
because of the sexual abuse.
   ``Kushi has a magic that touches everyone,'' Martin told the
rally. ``She certainly has touched us. She was taken away from not
only us but from the whole community.
   ``Betsy and I did everything we could within the system but it
wasn't enough. Removing Kushi was wrong, just wrong,'' Martin said.
   CPS workers took Khurshida ``Kushi'' Begum from the Martin-Seidel
home at Hoquiam last Friday, declaring it wasn't ``culturally
relevant.''
   Kushi has been placed at least temporarily with her 19-year-old
sister here, whose marriage gave the youngster entry to the United
States.
   Supporters say if she is returned to her remote village she faces
life as a social outcast because of her sexual abuse.
   Martin and Seidel, who have been her foster parents for a year,
had hoped to adopt the girl. But they have been told they cannot
keep her because they are not Moslem and because the natural parents
will not give her up for adoption.
   ``The girl's birth parents want her educated and raised in the
United States but their sect does not believe in adoption and they
have not relinquished their rights,'' Ms. Hopman said.
   ``I'm sure she is bonded to them after the year she has been with
them, but this has to do with family reunification and with cultural
relevancy,'' Ms. Hopman said.
   If the placement with her sister Morshida doesn't work out, three
Moslem families have volunteered their homes, Ms. Hopman said.
   Kushi and her sister did not attend the rally Monday, fearing it
would mean deportation of both, said Lee Terry, who sheltered the
family during the initial investigation. Ms. Terry said Morshida has
major problems of her own to deal with and that the foster parents
would be a better placement.
   Kushi's brother, Sultan, 21, who lives in Seattle, said in an
interview that Kushi's parents don't mind if their daughter stays
with Martin and Seidel.
   ``They say it's O.K. They don't know about this adoption. This
country is very hard. My parents can't understand,'' he said.
   ``They said it's OK if she happy,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
