<FIRST>r i PM-Korea     08-29 0469</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea,0482</SECOND>
<HEAD>Radical Students Clash with Police, Three Police Reported Beaten</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Radical students screaming
anti-government slogans today threw firebombs at police and captured
and beat three officers in the southern city of Kwangju, news
reports said.
   The three riot policemen were captured when 1,000 students
battled police at Chonnam University, said Yonhap, the South Korean
news agency.
   About 1,300 then stormed the campus, firing tear gas, Yonhap
said. It said the three policemen were released and taken to a
hospital, and about 10 students were arrested. No further details
were available.
   Rallies demanding the overthrow of the government and the release
of a student charged with illegally visiting Communist North Korea
were held at 17 schools in Seoul and 10 in provincial cities, the
state KBS television said.
   About 700 students in the capital fought riot police with clubs,
rocks and firebombs, news reports said.
   In the southeastern port of Pusan, about 1,000 students wielding
firebombs and rocks clashed with police firing tear gas at Donga
University in a battle that lasted 90 minutes, Yonhap said.
   ``Overthrow (President) Roh Tae-woo!'' yelled 200 students
hurling firebombs on rain-slick streets outside Seoul's Kyunghee
University. Riot police in combat fatigues fired tear gas to drive
students back inside the campus.
   ``Release Miss Im Su-kyong, flower of unification!'' students
shouted.
   Ms. Im was jailed for an illegal trip to North Korea to promote
national unification. She returned to the South in a much-publicized
border crossing at the Demilitarized Zone Aug. 15. Students at
Seoul's Polytechnic University and Sungkyunkwan University also
demonstrated for her release today, battling riot police.
   About 9,000 riot police surrounded Seoul campuses today to search
for Im Chong-suk, chairman of the National Council of Student
Representatives, who has eluded police for two months.
   Police issued an arrest warrant for Im in connection with the
trip to the North by Ms. Im. The two Ims are not related.
   Ms. Im is in the custody of the national security agency, charged
with violation of national security laws for making an unauthorized
trip to a hostile nation. Police say all those involved with her
trip face punishment.
   The Seoul government maintains that talks on unification of the
divided Korean peninsula must be carried out through official
channels, not by private citizens.
   Radical students and dissidents, a small but vocal minority,
claim the government is insincere in its efforts at dialogue with
North Korea. Radicals also demand the withdrawal of 43,000 U.S.
troops stationed in South Korea under a mutual defense pact, saying
their presence hinders unification.
   The Korean peninsula was divided into the Communist North and the
capitalist South at the end of World War II in 1945 and the two
nations, which fought a war in 1950-53, remain bitter enemies.
</TEXT>
