<FIRST>u i PM-Afghanistan-Rebels     08-29 0456</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Afghanistan-Rebels,0475</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dispute Grows Between Rival Afghan Guerrillas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clashes between the two largest groups
of U.S.-backed Afghan guerrillas have left 300 people dead, one of
the groups and some independent sources said today. A rival
guerrilla group disputed the claim.
   The battles reflect deteriorating relations among the
Pakistan-based guerrillas, who have yet to capture an Afghan city
since the Soviets withdrew their government-allied forces more than
six months ago.
   Hezb-i-Islami, a fundamentalist Moslem group, said 300 guerrillas
were killed in fighting in northern Afghanistan with the rival
Jamiat-i-Islami group.
   ``We don't have an updated figure, but we know that 100
Hezb-i-Islami mujahedeen (Islamic holy warriors) have died and 200
from Jamiat,'' said a Hezb spokesman identified only as Nasir.
   However, Jamiat, a more liberal Moslem party, called the claim
baseless.
   It said only that its men were holding five Hezb prisoners,
including an important commander.
   ``They were handed over by the local people because they are
criminals,'' said Jamiat spokesman Masoud Khalili.
   ``Something is going on; that's for sure,'' said Naim Majrooh, an
independent Afghan observer in Peshawar, Pakistan. ``Both sides are
involved. It's difficult to believe either one.''
   Fazle Akhbar, another prominent Afghan exile, said his
information indicated between 170 and 200 mujahedeen have died in
the fighting.
   Radio Kabul, the official broadcaster of Afghanistan's Marxist
leaders, has reported at least 556 mujahedeen killed in such clashes
in seven provinces since Aug. 18.
   However, the radio, monitored in Islamabad, is heavily slanted
against the mujahedeen.
   Deep-rooted antagonisms between the two leading guerrilla groups
broke out July 9 in northern Takhar province when Hezb guerrillas
under commander Syed Jamal ambushed and reportedly executed 32
Jamiat men, including several Jamiat commanders.
   Jamiat claims that local Afghans captured Jamal earlier this
month and turned him over to Jamiat's northern commander, Ahmad Shah
Masoud.
   Hezb claims Jamal was captured by pro-government militamen, who
then handed him over to Masoud because Masoud had made some kind of
deal with the Kabul government.
   Since the Takhar clash, the president of the mujahedeens'
self-declared government, Sibghatullah Mojaddidi, has publicly
called Hezb's leader, Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, a ``killer.'' Mojaddidi
is from the small, moderate Afghan National Liberation Front.
   The growing dispute has rocked the rebels' government, which is
composed of Hezb, Jamiat and five other Pakistan-based
anti-government groups.
   The mujahedeen, based mainly in Pakistan and Iran, are fighting
to topple the Kabul government and replace it with a Moslem regime.
   Hard-line parties, such as Hezb and Jamiat, favor fighting for a
military victory. Moderate mujahedeen groups have left the door open
for a negotiated settlement.
   The ruling People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan seized power
in a 1978 military coup, touching off the insurgency.
</TEXT>
