<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0922EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-BoatPeople     08-29 0377</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Boat People,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Vietnamese Reports Pirate Attack, Nearly 150 Believed Dead</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 17-year-old Vietnamese reported that
pirates raided a boat carrying her and about 150 other Vietnamese
refugees, and she believes nearly all the boat people died in the
attack two months ago, police said today.
   Lt. Col. Prakob Benjapong, deputy chief of the Songkhla marine
police, said the teen-ager told him the refugees left Vietnam June
15 in a boat headed for Malaysia.
   He said the teen-ager, whom he identified as Pham Hong Cuc, said
the boat was attacked two days later by two Thai fishing vessels.
   She said two fishermen armed with knives boarded the Vietnamese
boat and robbed its passengers, and then they took her, 10 women,
and three boys aboard their own boats.
   She said the pirates then rammed the Vietnamese boat six or seven
times and sank it. About half of those on board disappeared under
water as soon as the boat went down, she said, and she believes the
rest drowned later.
   The refugee said she and the 10 women were kept on one of the
fishing boats for about a week, raped by five of eight fishermen,
and later thrown overboard.
   She said someone on a passing boat threw her a buoy but refused
to take her aboard. A Thai fishing boat finally brought her ashore
on June 28.
   The police officer said Miss Cuc been living with the family of
one of the fishermen and only recently decided to tell police in the
southern town of Pattani about the attack.
   Prakob said there were no reports about the fate of the other
Vietnamese taken aboard the fishing boats.
   Pirates have been attacking boat people in the Gulf of Thailand
and the South China Sea since the refugees began fleeing their
homeland following the Communist takeover in 1975.
   Prakob said the latest attack was the 48th reported this year.
Police so far have arrested 14 suspects in connection with six other
cases, he said.
   Some officials say most of the pirates are not professional
criminals but fishermen who chance upon the refugee boats and see
them as easy targets.
   Officials say the pirates generally try to kill all refugees so
there will be no witnesses.
</TEXT>
