<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1053EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-GalaxyBirth 1stLd-Writethru a0440 08-29 0422</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Galaxy Birth, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0440,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>First Hydrogen Protogalaxy Found</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 3rd graf, The discovery, with Big Bang threory challenged</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Science Foundation says
astronomers believe they have stumbled across evidence that galaxies
may still be forming in the universe.
   The evidence is a massive cloud of hydrogen, 10 times larger than
the Milky Way galaxy, all by itself and close by astronomical
standards _ 65 million light-years away, the foundation said Monday.
   The discovery would appear to challenge the current belief that
all galaxies were formed within the first few hundred million years
after the ``Big Bang'' explosion dispersed hydrogen and matter in
the universe.
   The hydrogen cloud was found by Riccardo Giovanelli, adjunct
professor of astronomy at Cornell University and head of the radio
astronomy group at the foundation's National Astronomy and
Ionosphere Center in Arecibo, Puerto Rico, and co-worker, Martha
Haynes, associate professor of astronomy at Cornell.
   ``Before stumbling into this thing, neither I nor Martha were
great believers in the existence of such objects,'' Giovanelli said.
   ``But this cloud indicates that the discs of galaxies can form
slowly throughout the history of the universe and not just be
something that happened during some magic period in the distant
past.''
   Giovanelli and Haynes found the cloud while calibrating detectors
attached to the 1,000-foot dish radio telescope at Arecibo. For
calibration, they pointed the dish at a region of the sky thought to
be devoid of objects _ and found the characteristic radio signal of
hydrogen.
   Astronomers believe galaxies, massive groupings of millions to
billions of stars, must form from the condensation of hydrogen, the
simplest element _ a proton accompanied by an electron.
   Previous searches for cloud ``protogalaxies'' had failed to find
anything, though there is strong evidence for the existence of
clouds of hydrogen.
   Light from quasars, incredibly bright objects 10 billion or so
light years away from Earth, was missing frequencies characteristic
of what would be absorbed by hydrogen in its path.
   The cloud emits a strong radio signal, but there are no stars
associated with it, and it does not show up in optical surveys.
   Though 10 times larger than the Milky Way, it has only 10 percent
of the mass of that galaxy and it isn't clear whether the cloud will
evolve into a galaxy, the astronomers said.
   The cloud, south of the Virgo cluster, consists of two large
clumps of gas that may be merging, they said.
   A full report will appear in the Astrophysical Journal.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0065 </DOCNO>
