<FIRST>r a PM-DeputyCharged     08-29 0337</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Deputy Charged,0347</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deputy Charged In Fatal Shooting of Cookie Salesman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FORT MORGAN, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A sheriff's deputy has been charged
with criminally negligent homicide for shooting a cookie salesman
during a routine traffic stop in front of the salesman's home.
   Morgan County Sheriff's Deputy Dan Probasco, 29, was charged
Monday in Morgan County District Court in the July 15 death of Dan
E. Smith, 36, a salesman for Nabisco.
   Police say Probasco shot Smith in the back of the head after
pulling him over in front of Smith's Fort Morgan home for an
apparent drunken-driving check.
   ``Deputy Probasco's actions...grossly deviated from the standard
of care that a reasonable person in like circumstances and under a
like standard of care would exercise,'' District Attorney Jon Bailey
said at a news conference.
   Probasco has declined to discuss the shooting with investigators,
and has been on paid administrative leave.
   If convicted, the deputy could face one to four years in jail and
a fine ranging to $100,000. Bailey said the jail sentence could be
extended to eight years under exceptional circumstances.
   The shooting has prompted criticism of the sheriff's office by
some Fort Morgan residents, who said the episode epitomized the
sometimes overzealous law enforcement in the county.
   ``It seems to me if there was a shot in the back of the head, it
would be more than negligent,'' said attorney Roger Nixt, who is
representing Smith's estate.
   But Bailey said elements were lacking for the filing of murder
charges.
   Police reports say the shooting occurred after Probasco pulled
Smith's car over and radioed headquarters to verify Smith's license
number and driver's license.
   A transcript of radio transmissions the night of the slaying
showed the sheriff's dispatcher had just acknowledged Probasco's
call when Probasco yelled, ``I need backup.'' The dispatch center
then was unable to contact Probasco on the radio.
   A short time later, a neighbor of Smith's called police to say an
officer had asked her to call for assistance because there had been
a shooting.
</TEXT>
