<FIRST>u i PM-Iran 1stLd-Writethru   08-29 0391</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Iran, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0485,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parliament Approves Cabinet, Backs Rafsanjani's Removal of Hard-Liners</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with parliament approving entire
Cabinet; picks up 8th pvs, `Karrubi's support...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED BLANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Iran's parliament today approved all 22
nominations to President Hashemi Rafsanjani's new Cabinet, the
country's official news agency reported.
   The Islamic Republic News Agency, monitored in Nicosia, described
the vote of confidence by the 270-member Majlis as ``unprecedented''
since some members of all previous Cabinet slates had been rejected
in the past.
   The vote came after Rafsanjani got a last-minute boost for his
proposed Cabinet today from radical Parliament Speaker Mehdi Karrubi.
   ``I see Mr. Rafsanjani's Cabinet as a successful one and one that
supports the deprived ... and whose members have worked hard for the
revolution,'' Karrubi was quoted as saying by IRNA.
   He told Parliament, on the third day of a debate on Rafsanjani's
Cabinet: ``It is a Cabinet that has experience, proficiency,
competence and faith with full revolutionary credentials.''
   Earlier, Tehran newspapers had warned that as many as three of
the nominees could be rejected.
   Rafsanjani has come under fire from radicals for dumping their
leaders from his Cabinet. They included outgoing Interior Minister
Ali Akbar Mohtashemi, who has been closely linked with Shiite Moslem
militants holding most of the Western hostages in Lebanon.
   Karrubi's support was seen as critical for Rafsanjani, 55, who
was elected by a landslide vote July 28, after two days of debate in
which some of his nominees have incurred severe criticism from
radical deputies.
   Karrubi, a hard-line radical who has advocated the violent spread
of Iran's Islamic revolution, is allied to Rafsanjani's rivals.
   But he apparently has fallen in line with Ayatollah Ali Khamenei,
Iran's spiritual leader, who last week urged parliamentary deputies
to set aside their differences and approve Rafsanjani's Cabinet to
ensure a smooth transition from the outgoing government of Prime
Minister Hussein Musavi.
   Khamenei was elected to succeed Iran's revolutionary leader,
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, who died June 3. Karrubi succeeded
Rafsanjani, leader of Tehran's so-called pragmatists, as Speaker
last month.
   Rafsanjani's new-look Cabinet includes more technocrats, many of
them Western-educated, than revolutionary ideolgues. He has said his
main priority is to revitalize Iran's sagging economy, battered by
eight years of war with Iraq and a decade of mismanagement.
</TEXT>
