<FIRST>u i PM-India 2ndLd-Writethru a0515 08-29 0574</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-India, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0515,0589</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bus Blast Kills 12 A Day After Tribal Group Pledges to End Attacks</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 4 grafs with Sikh bomb attack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tribal militants today detonated a bomb
hidden in a bus in northeast India, killing at least 12 passengers a
day after tribal leaders agreed to suspend the campaign of
separatist violence, news reports said.
   The United News of India said the bomb exploded on a state-owned
bus in the state of Assam, where militants from the Bodo tribes have
been fighting for their own state.
   The news agency quoted unidentified officials as saying the bomb
was planted by Bodo militants and left at least 12 people and 35
injured.
   In New Delhi on Monday, Bodo leaders said they had agreed to
temporarily halt their separatist campaign as a result of talks with
federal government officials and the chief minister of Assam state.
   But Upendra Brama, one of the leaders, said the demand for a
separate Bodo state must be met by 1990 or the group would resume
violence.
   The Bodos have been demanding a separate homeland on the northern
bank of River Brahmaputrain in Assam, a remote and hilly state
bordering Bangladesh and Bhutan.
   The Bodos, mostly farmers of Mongol origin, were animists before
they converted earlier this century to Hinduism and Christianity.
They make up about 30 percent of Assam's 20 million people.
   The Bodos claim they suffer discrimination from the Assamese and
accuse them of mass migration to Bodo-dominated land.
   ``We will go to any extent to get our demand for a separate,
full-fledged Bodoland on the northern bank of Brahmaputra River,
implemented by 1990,'' Brahma told reporters in New Delhi after the
talks Monday.
   The violence has seriously affected the economy of the tea- and
timber-growing state.
   ``It is good news that both the sides have agreed to work for
peace and not to encourage violence,'' Assam government spokesman
J.K. Dass said today.
   Dass said that during the talks, the Bodos agreed to stop attacks
on government and in return, the Assam government would not to
invoke special police powers to detain suspects without trial for up
to one year.
   ``From our side, we will stop all actions against the Bodos with
the hope that they will abide by the agreement,'' Dass said. ``But
if they resume their violent campaign, we will use force against
them.''
   The Bodo problem has been simmering for more than 20 years, but
it turned violent earlier this year.
   Bodo leaders claim that 1,500 of their comrades have died in
police actions by the Assam government and that 15,000 houses have
been damaged by Assamese, leaving 100,000 people homeless.
   Dass, however, said only 395 people, including 41 policemen and
16 state officials, had been killed this year.
   In Punjab state, another hub of separatist violence, police said
today that Sikh militants set off a bomb at a railroad track and
closed down the rail line.
   A.K. Sharma, senior police superintendent at Majitha, said at
least six feet of nearby track were destroyed Monday by the bomb,
but no one was injured. He said seven empty train cars derailed when
they approached the damaged track. Sikh radicals have been fighting
for an independent nation in Punjab since 1982. They claim
discrimination by the Hindus, India's religious majority.
   On Sunday, masked Sikh gunmen raided a passenger train in Punjab
and massacred at least 22 Hindu passengers.
</TEXT>
