<FIRST>r a PM-CasinoFire 1stLd-Writethru a0467 08-29 0438</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Casino Fire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0467,0445</SECOND>
<HEAD>Witnesses Say Anti-Gamblers Burned Down Casino</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 3rd graf, `A Niagara ..., to UPDATE with power restored,
police investigating. Pick up 3rd graf pvs, `The Lucky ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOGANSBURG, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A casino under construction on an
American Indian reservation was set aflame by residents opposed to
gambling parlors on Indian territory, witnesses say.
   A power transformer was shot out near two other casinos on the
St. Regis Mohawk Reservation, where pro- and anti-gambling forces
have clashed since a gambling raid last month, state police said
today.
   Power was restored to the Bear's Den and Tony's Vegas
International by 5:30 a.m. today, said Niagara Mohawk Power Corp.
district manager David Werner. No homes were affected, he said.
   Troopers were investigating the incident, which occurred about 11
p.m. Monday, but no arrests had been made, according to a state
police spokesman who would not give his name.
   The Lucky Knight Casino, which was scheduled to open today, was
heavily damaged in the fire Sunday night after a confrontation
between a pro- and anti-gambling factions. A brief standoff between
the Warriors Society, a self-appointed reservation security force,
and state police followed the disturbance.
   Casino owner Victoria Adams said she had just left the building
when a mob stormed it and set the fire with Molotov cocktails. She
said the mob tried to burn other casinos but armed guards stopped
them.
   State police, in a statement, said the conflict at the casino
involved more than 500 people and lasted about six hours.
   While state troopers set up roadblocks to route traffic around
the reservation, Warriors Society members, expecting state police to
intervene, set up their own armed checkpoints just inside the
reservation.
   After several tense hours, both sides relinquished their
respective strongholds along the perimeter of the reservation, which
straddles the U.S.-Canadian border in northern New York.
   The reservation was the site of a 10-day standoff between
troopers and Indians after a gambling raid July 20 by state and
federal authorities. Mohawks voted this month to permit gambling on
the reservation, but some Indians claim the vote was invalid.
   State police and tribal leaders reached an agreement this month
to resume patrols on the reservation, but the Warriors Society has
said they would allow troopers on their land only with advance
notice and escorts.
   Although casino gambling is illegal in New York state, the
reservation's seven casinos offer slot machines and card games that
attract gamblers from both sides of the border. The Mohawks contend
they are not bound by state or federal gambling laws since they
consider their reservation a sovereign nation.
</TEXT>
