<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1214EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-FlagArtistry     08-29 0473</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Flag Artistry,0486</SECOND>
<HEAD>Art Show Protests Proposed Flag Desecration Laws</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERSEY CITY, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A group of artists says it wants to
enlighten, not offend, with a show on the U.S. flag that includes a
painting of the Statue of Liberty giving a Nazi salute against the
backdrop of an American banner.
   The 10 artists _ students and former students at Jersey City
State College _ are exhibiting their works in a month-long show
opening Sept. 12 called ``Flagging Our Freedom.'' The exhibit in a
campus gallery is funded by a campus literary magazine and has the
support of the chairman of the art department.
   The exhibit is motivated by proposed laws against flag
desecration and by the threat of the government withdrawing money
for art considered offensive.
   ``By no means are we trying to do shock art,'' organizer Orlando
R. Cuevas said. ``We're trying to do good art.''
   Oroc, an artist who goes by the one name, had a piece among those
previewed Monday.
   In his oil painting ``21st Century America,'' a grimacing Statue
of Liberty makes a Nazi salute. A swastika is painted on the tablet
on her arm, and pennies reading ``In Dog We Trust'' cover her
breasts. Behind her is a wrinkled, backwards American flag and the
corner of a dollar bill.
   Christ is crucified on the ``one'' of the bill.
   ``To me the Statue of Liberty is really a joke,'' said Oroc, a
24-year-old Union City resident. The work's message is that the
nation celebrates freedom but tolerates racism, homelessness,
exclusion of immigrants and worship of wealth, he said.
   Cuevas' contribution is a multi-media sculpture inside half a
cat-carrying box. What appears to be a row of toy soldiers marches
on top of a flag. A doll's head lies in back, its arm poking through
the row of soldiers.
   ``The Big Parade'' is an anti-war statement, and the flag
represents ``mainstream America,'' said Cuevas, 25, of Jersey City.
   The artists have a range of opinions over proper treatment of the
flag but agree their right to use it to express themselves should
not be limited, he said.
   They are reacting in part to a recent U.S. Supreme Court decision
protecting flag burning as free speech. The students also said they
were reacting to cuts of federal grants by the U.S. House to museums
that sponsored the controversial work of photographers Robert
Mapplethorpe and Andres Serrano.
   A spokesman for the state Veterans of Foreign Wars, which favors
a constitutional amendment against flag burning, said he would
reserve judgment on the show.
   ``It all depends on the works of art they're displayng,'' said
Willis Bird in Trenton.
   ``I absolutely do support the show,'' said art department
chairwoman Dorothy Dierks Harris. Of the students, she said, ``I
think they are rather exceptional.''
</TEXT>
