<SECOND>AM-BRF--Hungary-Intelligence,0143</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Communists Relinquish Control of Intelligence Service</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of Hungary's intelligence
service said in an interview published Tuesday that the Communist
Party no longer controls his organization.
   Police Brig. Gen. Jozsef Horvath told the Magyar Nemzet newspaper
that situation reports no longer are being given to leading members
of the party, and ``only state leaders are entitled to this right.''
   The formal transfer of control from the Communist Party to the
government has had little practial effect, however, because all
government leaders are also ranking Communists.
   After endorsing the concept of multiparty democracy in February,
the reform-minded communist leadership began transfering to the
government formal supervisory rights to organizations it had
traditionally controlled, including the armed forces and the police.
   The moves are in preparation for free parliamentary elections
next year.
