<HEAD>Helmsley Bodyguard Found at Jury's Hotel</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Retransmitting a0539 to indicate it is a 1st Ld-Writethru. Edits
throughout to UPDATE with judge's comments, deliberations resuming. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One of Leona Helmsley's bodyguards went to the
hotel where jurors in her tax evasion trial are sequestered and rode
an elevator with one juror, according to court papers.
   U.S. District Judge John Walker Jr., concerned by newspaper
reports on the incident, said today that there was an ``innocent
explanation'' for the incident that satisfied both the court and
government.
   Walker did not reveal why the unidentified bodyguard was in the
hotel in Manhattan on Friday night. The explanation is contained in
other court papers still under seal, he said.
   The incident was first reported in today's editions of The New
York Post and New York Newsday. Walker said the court transcripts
obtained by the newspapers were ``inadvertently'' unsealed.
   In the court papers from Saturday, Walker told Mrs. Helmsley's
lawyer, Gerald Feffer, to ``convey to his client to tell her people
to stay out of the hotel'' where the jury was staying.
   ``Needless to say, this is not a Helmsley hotel,'' Walker said.
   The jury began its fourth day of deliberations today in Mrs.
Helmsley's federal court trial. She is charged with 47 counts of tax
evasion and extortion for allegedly charging personal expenses to
her businesses.
