<FIRST>u a PM-IllinoisLotto     08-29 0219</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Illinois Lotto,0224</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple Claims Richest Lotto Prize to a Single Winner in Illinois</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A suburban couple came forward today to claim a
$42 million Lotto jackpot, the richest prize to a single-ticket
winner in Illinois State Lottery history.
   William and Kathleen Madigan, who formed the Madigan Partnership
to claim the prize, will receive 20 annual payments of $2.1 million,
officials said at a news conference.
   The Madigans, who live in Hometown, a southern suburb of Chicago,
bought their ticket for Saturday's Lotto drawing at a White Hen
Pantry in suburban Oak Lawn. The convenience store will receive
$420,000, 1 percent of their winnings, lottery officials said.
   Mike Wittkowski, a Chicago printer who was a 1984 Lotto winner,
held the previous state single-jackpot record of $40 million.
   The state's biggest jackpot ever was $69.9 million for the April
15 drawing this year, but the cash in that grand-prize pool was
divided four ways.
   The winner of the largest undivided lottery prize in the United
States was Sheelah Ryan of Winter Springs, Fla., who won $55.16
million in the Florida lottery on Sept. 3, 1988.
   Players in the Illinois Lottery select six numbers from 1 to 54.
A $1 ticket buys two plays. The winning numbers drawn Saturday night
were 6, 9, 33, 40, 51, 54.
