<FIRST>u i PM-Cambodia 1stLd-Writethru   08-29 0551</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cambodia, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0445,0565</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Makes Last-Ditch Effort to Find Cambodian Compromise</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with meeting canceled, predictions
that conference will fail; picks up xth pvs, `Fourteen foreign...' Minor
editing to TRIM.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Delegates to a peace conference canceled a formal
meeting planned for today, and a French official said warring
Cambodian groups might wait until next year before they negotiate
again.
   Representatives of the 19 nations spent the day working
informally in small groups, then planned a working dinner followed
by further consultations on the issues that have blocked a
settlement in the monthlong conference.
   The formal session was postponed several times before finally
being rescheduled for Wednesday.
   A Foreign Ministry spokesman, speaking anonymously in keeping
with department practice, said the conference would conclude
Wednesday with a short statement that probably would recommend a
reconvening the conference in Paris several months from now,
``perhaps in the spring.''
   The spokesman said there was ``no movement on the part of the
Cambodian parties'' on two essential points _ composition of a
proposed transitional government and an international mechanism for
monitoring withdrawal of Vietnamese troops this month.
   ``It's too early for a compromise,'' he said.
   A senior U.S. official predicted today that the conference would
be suspended, and a new round of fighting would follow.
   ``We see indications that we may be in for this period of
military testing,'' the official told reporters, speaking on
condition he not be further identified.
   The official suggested the conference could close, ``leaving
open-ended the prospect of reconvening ... some months down the road
when perhaps the realities on the ground have given people a clearer
sense of the real balance of forces at play here.''
   Fourteen foreign ministers present at the first session in late
July have returned to Paris, but China's Foreign Minister Qian
Quichen, Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze and U.S.
Secretary of State James A. Baker III did not return because no
resolution was in sight.
   Nineteen nations originally attended the conference with high
hopes of laying the foundations for a lasting peace in Cambodia,
which has suffered two decades of civil war and slaughter. But no
progress has been made in three weeks of working meetings.
   Some delegates said positions seem to have hardened among the
Cambodian parties _ the Vietnamese-installed government of Prime
Minister Hun Sen and the three-party resistance led by Prince
Norodom Sihanouk, Cambodia's ruler until 1970.
   Vietnam has said it will withdraw the last of its forces by Sept.
27 with or without a settlement.
   The greatest obstacle remains the role of the Khmer Rouge,
strongest of the resistance factions and responsible for the deaths
of an estimated 1 million civilians due to purges or starvation from
1975 until its ouster by Vietnamese forces in 1978.
   The Khmer Rouge regime came to power by defeating the U.S.-backed
Cambodian government.
   Sihanouk, Cambodia's heriditary ruler, says he would rather share
power with the Khmer Rouge than fight it in the jungles, while Hun
Sen says the group must be eliminated politically and militarily.
   ``There is a limit to which the rest of the world can impose a
solution on the Cambodians,'' a weary Australian Foreign Minister
Garth Evans said at the close of Monday's session.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
