<DOCNO> AP890829-0090 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1349EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Britain-Mail     08-29 0215</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Britain-Mail,0221</SECOND>
<HEAD>Midday Sun Upsets British Dogs; More Bite Mail Carriers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dog attacks on mail carriers are increasing, the
Post Office says, blaming the increase on warmer weather than usual
and on people keeping larger dogs.
   Hot weather makes dogs irritable and attacks on mailmen were up
by 40 percent in the first six months of this year, the Post Office
said.
   A survey of the problem in the current long hot summer by The
Times of London reported a mail carrier in Somerset was bitten on
the arm when a dog leaped through the window of his delivery van.
   In Bristol, a mail carrier had a narrow escape when a guard dog
inside a house crashed through the glass front door to try to get
him.
   There were 7,057 dog attacks on mail carriers in Britain last
year, nearly one-fifth more than in 1987. Dog attacks cost the Post
Office $515,000 a year.
   To stop them, the Post Office is testing a device that emits a
high-pitched sound inaudible to humans but intimidating to dogs.
   In the past, mail carriers facing a threatening dog were advised
to get down on all fours and look the beast straight in the eye. Few
were brave enough to try, the Post Office said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
