<FIRST>r a PM-BRF--Mayor-Drugs     08-29 0149</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-BRF--Mayor-Drugs,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Pleads Innocent To Cocaine Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LITTLE ROCK, Ark. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mayor of Parkin, Ark., pleaded
innocent today to federal cocaine charges.
   ``He didn't do it,'' defense attorney John Henry said of Mayor
Tommy Voyles, 43, who has remained in office and on the job in
Parkin, a town of 2,000 about 25 miles west of Memphis, Tenn.
   Voyles was arrested a week ago on an eight-count federal grand
jury indictment. The charges include one count of conspiring to
distribute cocaine and seven counts of distributing cocaine from
1987 through 1989. Voyles is serving his first term in the
$600-a-month mayor's post.
   U.S. District Judge Elsijane T. Roy set a trial date of Oct. 10.
Voyles remains free on $50,000 bond.
   The indictment alleges that Voyles conspired with William
Criswell, 50, a used-car dealer from Earle, to sell cocaine.
Criswell also faces a conspiracy charge.
</TEXT>
