<DOCNO> AP890829-0093 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1400EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Snakes     08-29 0234</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Snakes,0240</SECOND>
<HEAD>Snake Stunt Called Off After Public Outcry</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Live snakes sent to video rental shop owners to
promote a horror film will be retrieved and the stunt will be
canceled because of public outcry, the organizers said Tuesday.
   Cinema International Corp., which began sending out 700 Chinese
rat snakes to shops nationwide last week as part of a promotional
package, said it was worried about the reptiles.
   ``We were worried that all this unwarranted attention could get
the public overly interested in the snakes, and result in them
coming to harm,'' said Paul Brett, the company's marketing manager.
``We thought the best thing to do was to take them back.''
   The Royal Society for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals had a
different view on what might cause the snakes harm. It said last
week that directions accompanying the snakes had incorrectly said
they didn't need to be fed during what Cinema International planned
as the snakes' month-long stay in the shops.
   But an RSPCA spokeswoman said Tuesday it welcomed the end of the
promotion, saying ``obviously CIC has seen the error of their ways,
and we're very pleased about that.''
   The spokeswoman said it would prosecute the company if any of the
snakes suffered.
   The snakes, which were not poisonous, were sent out to promote
the release of the video of the film ``The Serpent and the Rainbow.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0094 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1414EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-BRF--GoldStreets     08-29 0121</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Gold Streets,0123</SECOND>
<HEAD>Norwegian Highway Accidently Becomes Street of Gold</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OSLO, Norway (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Norwegian streets may not be paved with gold
but one highway unwittingly was constructed right on top of $1.4
million worth of the precious metal, reports said Tuesday.
   A regional highway department used gold ore as landfill while
building a highway in the central Norway town of Grong, the news
agency NTB reported.
   State geologists said workers dug up a vein of gold that ran
through a department gravel pit, dumped it in the road bed, and
paved over it.
   Highway Superintendent Knut Andersen told state radio he hadn't
been aware of the lode but admitted that road construction was not
the best use for it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0095 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1418EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a People     08-29 0726</FIRST>
<SECOND>People,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>People in the News</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY44</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLAINS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The job of describing the buildings of former
President Jimmy Carter's hometown brought five people to Plains and
left them with a taste of Southern heritage and homemade pie.
   Four illustrators and an architecture historian came to Plains on
June 12 as part of the National Parks Service's Historic American
Building Survey.
   Their mission was to record with sketches and words the
architecture and history of buildings that figured in Carter's life.
   Team leader John Westberg said the artists' visit brought them in
contact with many of the 650 or so residents of Plains and with more
than a few fresh-baked pies.
   ``Everybody knows everybody and remembers everything,'' said
Elizabeth Barthold, an architectural history student at American
University in Washington. ``There's such a continuity here, such a
strong sense of history.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NORTH ADAMS, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oscar-winning actress Olympia Dukakis
has agreed to serve on the board of directors of The Mohawk Guild, a
non-profit organization that hopes to create a community-based
performance center.
   ``I will help the Mohawk anyway I can,'' said Dukakis, who runs
The Whole Theater in Montclair, N.J., with her husband, Louis
Zorich. The two visited this summer while performing ``Mother
Courage'' at the Williamstown Theater Festival.
   Dukakis, who won an Academy Award for her supporting role in
``Moonstruck,'' is a cousin of Gov. Michael S. Dukakis.
   ``She said she would help out when we need to meet somebody in
New York, or maybe attract a Broadway performer. She would also lend
her name to fund-raising letters and be as vocal as she can in her
support,'' said Maria Watson, manager of the Mohawk Theater, where
the group hopes to set up.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>OURAY, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   C.W. McCall says he's rolling his convoy
again, this time coming down the road with New Age music.
   The 60-year-old country singer known for the truckers' anthem
``Convoy,'' but better known in these parts as Ouray Mayor Bill
Fries, says he'll make his first recording in 15 years this fall.
   All his old hits will be on the album, but with a twist.
   ``It won't be your standard type of recording,'' Fries said.
``It's more like poetry and there will be a lot of natural sounds in
the background.''
   He will team up with the group Manheim Steamroller, one of the
best-selling groups in the jazzy, spacey, mostly instrumental music
that has become to be known as New Age.
   ``This album will give me one more shot of adrenaline,'' he said.
``Then I'm going to sit back and have some fun.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The closing credits to the movie ``Heart of
Dixie'' thank a variety of people for making the movie possible,
including Gov. Ray ``Maybus.'' Only it should be ``Mabus.''
   ``Heart of Dixie'' was filmed largely around Oxford and the
antebellum mansions of Holly Springs. It opened last week around the
country.
   In thanking the Mississippi Film Commission for its help, the
credits list Gov. Ray ``Maybus.''
   Orion Pictures and Los Angeles producer Steve Tisch referred
calls to a publicist who didn't answer his telephone.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   New York Mets pitcher Frank Viola's victory in
Los Angeles not only ended a losing streak but also put the bite on
a New York deli.
   Earlier this month, Abe Lebewohl, proprietor of the Second Avenue
Deli, said he'd give a one-pound salami to anyone who came into his
restaurant with a ticket stub from a Mets game won by Viola.
   Viola proceeded to lose his next three games.
   But Monday night he shut out the Dodgers, and the very next
morning New Yorker Stuart Baron walked into Lebewohl's restaurant
and handed over a stub for the game at Dodger Stadium, 3,000 miles
away.
   Baron didn't attend the game but had ordered a ticket by phone
Saturday.
   ``I wanted to see the look on their faces when I walked in at 9
o'clock with the stub from a road game on the West Coast that had
ended at 1 a.m.,'' said Baron. ``I did it for the effect, a joke.''
   The salami, 10 inches long and three inches thick, sells for $7.
Baron's stub was for a $4 upper-deck seat at Dodger Stadium, but
ticket agency commission and delivery by air express ran the total
to $14.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1418EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-CanyonPollution     08-29 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Canyon Pollution,390</SECOND>
<HEAD>EPA Says Arizona Plant Pollutes Grand Canyon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By H. JOSEF HEBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Environmental Protection Agency concluded
today that emissions from a massive coal-fired power plant in
Arizona cause up to 70 percent of the air pollution over the Grand
Canyon and must be curbed.
   In announcing its preliminary findings, the EPA said it expects a
final decision by next February on how pollution from the Navajo
Generating Station is to be curbed.
   Operators of the Page, Ariz., plant about 12 miles from the
northern rim of the canyon have argued that no additional pollution
curbs should be required because much of the canyon pollution comes
from other sources in the Los Angeles area and Mexico.
   But the EPA said the Park Service tests, using a chemical tracer
that was released through the power plant's 750-foot smokestacks,
demonstrated that on average about 40 percent of the pollution over
the Grand Canyon originates with the plant and during some periods
the percentage is as high as 70 percent.
   Officials said a solution may require the plant to install
expensive ``scrubber'' technology to reduce sulfur dioxide
emissions, which currently range as high as 12 to 13 tons an hour
during peak power periods.
   The 2,250-megawatt power plant, partially owned by the federal
government, has been under close scrutiny by the U.S. Park Service
to determine to what extent it contributes to the bright, white
layers of haze clearly visible over the canyon during much of the
year, especially in winter.
   ``We have substantial evidence that the Navajo Generating Station
is a significant contributor to the visiblity problem,'' said F.
Henry Habicht, the EPA's deputy administrator. ``Action must be
taken now to protect the Grand Canyon.''
   The plant is one of the largest coal-burning electric generating
facilities in the country, burning 24,000 tons of coal a day.
Because of the plant's size, sulfur dioxide emissions are a problem
even though it burns largely low-sulfur coal.
   The federal government could be required to pay for some of the
pollution control equipment because the Interior Department's Bureau
of Reclamation holds a 24 percent interest in the facility. The
government uses electricity from the plant to pump water from the
Colorado River for irrigation in central Arizona.
   The EPA action was prompted by a lawsuit filed by the
Environmental Defense Fund, a private group.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0097 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1423EDT</FILEID>
