<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1439EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-People--NancyReagan     08-29 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-People--Nancy Reagan,0280</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nancy Reagan In Flap Over Anti-Drug Grant</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former first lady Nancy Reagan is being
criticized for her plans to stay away from a junior high school in a
gang-plagued neighborhood and deliver an anti-drug grant at a
different school.
   Board of Education member Rita Walters charged Monday that Mrs.
Reagan is too afraid to enter the south-central Los Angeles
neighborhood that is intended to benefit from the grant.
   Ms. Walters made the accusations after learning that Mrs. Reagan,
the wife of former President Reagan, would not go to John Muir High
School on Sept. 14 to present the school with a $36,392 grant.
   Instead, Mrs. Reagan plans to make the presentation at Gates
Street School in the Lincoln Heights area north of downtown.
   ``The issue is the insult that is rendered when you're going to
give money for a program in one community but you're afraid to go
into the community,'' Ms. Walters said.
   However, Los Angeles Unified School District Superintendent
Leonard Britton said the Secret Service, not Mrs. Reagan, made the
arrangements for the presentation.
   City police and the Secret Service suggested the alternate
location because similar events had been held there, said Deputy
Superintendent Sid Thompson.
   Neither the Secret Service or representatives for Mrs. Reagan
could be reached for comment early today.
   Ms. Walters said that she would not attend the presentation if it
was held at Gates.
   ``This is an absolute slap in the face,'' she said.
   Britton said the district would discuss the issue with the Secret
Service before making a final decision about where the presentation
will be.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0099 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1439EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-TeenHijackers     08-29 0225</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teen Hijackers,0231</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Czechoslovak Teens Given Probation for Plane Hijacking</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FRANKFURT, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A juvenile court Tuesday sentenced
two Czechoslovak teen-agers to two years' probation for hijacking a
Hungarian jetliner.
   No one was injured in the March hijacking of the Malev Airlines
jet, but Frankfurt juvenile court judge Klaus Dirszoweit said the
teen-agers had put passengers' lives in danger.
   Stefan Macicko, 17, and Dusan Styck, 16, said they seized the
plane because they wanted asylum in the West.
   Armed with a sawed-off shotgun and a rifle, they grabbed a
hostage at Prague's Ruzyne airport on March 29 and forced their way
onto the Soviet-built Tupolev-154 plane, firing a single shot into
the air.
   After releasing 82 passengers, including all the women and
children, they forced the plane to fly to West Germany with 11
remaining passengers and a crew of four.
   They surrendered peacefully at Frankfurt airport, where the plane
had been scheduled to fly, three hours after the hijacking began.
They confessed to authorities, and there was no trial.
   The court said the teen-agers would be transferred to a youth
home in West Germany's Hesse state, where they will be allowed to
attend school while serving the probation.
   Shortly after the hijacking, Czechoslovak authorities requested
extradiction of the teen-agers, but West German officials decided to
prosecute them in Frankfurt instead.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
