<FIRST>u w PM-DeGreiff 3rdLd-Writethru a0589 08-29 0534</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-De Greiff, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0589,500</SECOND>
<HEAD>Colombian Official Vows to Continue Fight Against Drug Lords</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: CORRECTS word to ability sted abilities in 9th graf, He first</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Colombia's Justice Minister Monica de Greiff
today vowed to continue to fight her country's drug lords despite
death threats, and she appealed for more U.S. aid to protect judges.
   ``The law is under siege in Colombia and we must protect it every
way we can,'' she told a news conference at the Colombian embassy.
She disputed reports that she had considered resigning in the face
of death threats against her, her husband and the couple's
3-year-old son.
   ``I never considered resigning,'' she said. ``The threats are out
there, but I am satisfied with my protection right now.''
   Ms. de Greiff said she would remain in Washington through Sept. 6
to continue discussions with Bush administration officials about her
requests for additional aid to protect Colombian judges from
assassination.
   The 32-year-old justice minister said she was requesting $19
million to purchase armored cars, bulletproof vests, metal detectors
for court houses and other security devices to protect the jurists.
   The aid package being sought is in addition to the $5 million
that the Bush administration has approved over a two-year period to
improve security for judges.
   The president also has approved $65 million in U.S. military aid
to help the Colombian government fight the drug cartels.
   At his vacation home in Kennebunkport, Maine, where he met with
top aides on the anti-drug battle plan he will unveil Sept. 5, Bush
was noncommittal when asked about the requested $19 million in aid
to protect judges.
   He first declined comment, then said, ``It's being worked out
now, the details.'' And he said the United States ``will cooperate
with Colombia to the best of our ability.''
   Ms. de Greiff said she was anxious to continue her efforts to
preserve the Colombian legal system. She said her government faced a
fight with a foe that has ``no respect for the law or even the
minimal standards of decency.''
   But she expressed confidence that Colombia ``will survive this
crisis.''
   She said she was ``very pleased'' with the response of the Bush
administration, saying she still was hoping for more assistance.
   Meanwhile, David Runkel, a spokesman for Attorney General Dick
Thornburgh, backed away from the Justice Department's earlier
prediction that a Colombian drug trafficker wanted in this country
would be extradited this week.
   Runkel said Eduardo Martinez Romero may not be extradited for two
weeks under procedures set forth by the Colombian government. He
also raised the possibility that the Colombian Supreme Court, which
overturned the extradition procedures in 1987, may review the
emergency decrees for extradition that recently were promulgated by
Colombian President Virgilio Barco.
   ``Those extradition procedures are complicated, and I think there
is a possibility there may be a decision to have the Supreme Court
in Colombia rule on those new procedures,'' the spokesman said.
   Nevertheless, he said, ``we have every hope and expectation of
getting custody of Mr. Martinez.''
   Runkel said the Justice Department was in the process of drafting
extradition requests for 12 other Colombian drug traffickers under
federal indictment.
