<HEAD>With AM-US-Colombia</HEAD>
<HEAD>Aid to Colombia Awaits Agreed Upon List</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to correct to `routine' sted `daily' briefing.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Distribution of $65 million in U.S. military
aid for Colombia's war on drug traffickers awaits a detailed list of
needs from that government, the Pentagon said Tuesday.
   ``When the list is returned to the United States delivery will
begin,'' Pete Williams said at a routine Pentagon news briefing.
   President Bush last Friday granted the aid package of aircraft,
boats, arms and ammunition to work with Colombia to ``bring to
justice those responsible for the scourge of drug trafficking.''
   An unprecedented crackdown is underway in Colombia following the
recent murder of a presidential candidate. Drug traffickers declared
``total and absolute war'' on the government, and on Tuesday set off
seven bombs, according to police.
   Police also blamed traffickers Sunday for nine bombings of banks
in Medellin. There were no claims of responsibility.
   Williams said the United States sent Colombia a list of equipment
available for immediate transfer from Defense Department stocks
after Bush granted the aid. The Colombians, in turn, issued their
list of requests.
   ``Officials of both governments are now analyzing those needs,''
the spokeksman said, adding, ``The DOD is ready to provide immediate
airlift.''
   Williams declined to say what type of equipment would be
provided, noting in general terms it would be aircraft, weapons,
ammunition, personal gear, communications equipment and medical
supplies.
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater, in announcing the aid
package last Friday, said the United States would Huey helicopters
for transporting troops, equipment and ammunitions, Blackhawk
helicopters for medical evacuations, planes, trucks and assault
boats.
   The package also is to include American military advisers, which
Fitzwater said would be `relatively small.'' He said the soldiers
would not assume combat roles.
   Williams said the American personnel would be used to train the
Colombians in how to operate the equipment. He said the goods would
not be delivered until the entire list was received and approved,
which he added could be this week.
</TEXT>
