<FIRST>r a AM-WhaleFreed     08-29 0200</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Whale Freed,0208</SECOND>
<HEAD>Tuna Boat Catches, Frees Young Humpback Whale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A tuna boat lost practically its entire haul in
freeing an endangered humpback whale tangled in the vessel's nets
for more than two hours, the Coast Guard said Tuesday.
   The young whale, caught Monday by the 150-foot Eileen Marie,
appeared unharmed when it was freed, Coast Guard Chief Petty Officer
Jack Mason said.
   Environmentalists complain that marine mammals often become
tangled in tuna nets and drown.
   The incident occurred about 15 miles off Provincetown on
Stellwagen Bank, where humpbacks return to feed every summer.
Whale-watching boats often cruise the area. The 20-foot whale was
about half the size of mature humpbacks.
   The crew of the Eileen Marie freed the whale by manipulating the
nets until it spilled out but lost about 95 percent of the boat's
catch, Mason said.
   ``They were making all possible attempts to free the whale to the
extent of losing tuna,'' Mason said.
   Petty Officer 3rd Class Ellen Marie Harrington said she didn't
know how much tuna was caught and lost but that the vessel could
carry millions of pounds of tuna. The Eileen Marie did not answer
marine radio calls Tuesday.
</TEXT>
