<FIRST>u a AM-Nielsens     08-29 0467</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Nielsens,0479</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABC's `Roseanne' First in Television Ratings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JERRY BUCK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ABC's ``Roseanne'' was first in the Nielsen TV
ratings, but another working class housewife, Peg Bundy in ``Married
... With Children,'' gave Fox Broadcasting a big boost for the week
ended Aug. 27.
   ``Roseanne'' finished ahead of NBC's ``Cheers'' in their summer
seesaw battle for first.
   Fox's ``Married ... With Children'' jumped up in the ratings
again, this time for a tie for 17th place with NBC's ``Empty Nest.''
The show got a 13.4 rating, its highest ever, and was first in its
time period Sunday for the second time this summer.
   The Fox comedy was the only original show, other than ABC's
``20-20,'' in the 30 top shows for the week.
   Fox's fledging fourth network has made its first ratings
breakthrough in recent months with its shows rising out of the
ratings cellar for the first time. Shows such as ``Married ... With
Children,'' ``America's Most Wanted'' and ``Totally Hidden Video''
have all done well. ``Open House,'' a revamping of ``Duet,''
premiered this past week in 47th place, coming in ahead of the
second half of the ABC Sunday movie.
   Comedy continued its domination of the ratings. Eighteen of the
20 highest-rated shows were comedies. The movie pilot for NBC's
``Baywatch'' was tied for seventh with ABC's ``Who's the Boss?'' and
the CBS movie ``Tricks of the Trade'' was 12th.
   NBC was first in the A.C. Nielsen Co. survey for the 62nd
consecutive week with an average of 11.4. ABC was second with 9.7
and CBS was third with 9.6.
   For the season to date from Sept. 19, 1988, NBC was first with
14.5, ABC second with 11.7 and CBS third with 11.6. The rating is
the percentage of the estimated 90.4 million homes with television
in the United States. The share is the percentage of sets in use.
   Here are the Top 10: ABC's ``Roseanne,'' NBC's ``Cheers,'' NBC's
``A Different World,'' NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' and ``Dear John''
tied, ABC's ``The Wonder Years,'' NBC's ``Baywatch: Panic at
Malibu'' and ABC's ``Who's the Boss?'' tied, ABC's ``Mr.
Belvedere,'' NBC's ``Night Court.''
   CBS had only three shows in the first 20, the movie ``Tricks of
the Trade'' in 12th place, ``Designing Women'' 13th and ``Murphy
Brown'' 14th.
   The NBC summer comedy ``FM,'' which premiered in fifth place last
week, fell to 37th for a tie with CBS' ``Newhart.''
   ``The CBS Evening News'' was first among the news shows with a
rating of 9.7. ABC was second with 8.5 and NBC was third with 8.0.
   The lowest-rated show for the week was ABC's ``Incredible
Sunday.'' The five bottom network shows were: CBS' ``Beauty and the
Beast,'' CBS' ``Outpost,'' CBS' ``Tour of Duty,'' ABC's ``Student
Exchange'' and ABC's ``Incredible Sunday.''
