<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1715EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-HomeSales     08-29 0539</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Home Sales,530</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Home Sales Advance at Fast Clip in July</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sales of new homes, bolstered by falling
mortgage rates, surged 14.4 percent in July, the fastest pace in
nearly three years, the Commerce Department reported Tuesday.
   The department said that new single-family homes were sold at a
seasonally adjusted annual rate of 739,000 units last month,
compared with a revised rate of 646,000 units in June.
   The advance was led by a giant 55.8 percent jump in sales in the
Northeast, a region where sales have been especially sluggish
because of high prices. But every geographic area of the country
reported good gains during the month.
   Analysts credited the advance to a sharp decline in mortgage
rates. After hitting a peak of 11.2 percent in March, fixed-rate
mortgages had fallen to an average 9.81 percent nationwide by the
end of July.
   Rates have risen slightly in recent weeks, currently averaging
10.21 percent, according to a national survey by the Federal Home
Loan Mortgage Corp.
   Economists were split on whether this increase would continue or
whether mortgage rates would begin to drift down again in coming
months.
   David Berson, an economist with the Federal National Mortgage
Association, said he looked for mortgage rates to continue creeping
up, driven by reasonably strong economic growth and continued
worries about inflationary pressures.
   But Lyle Gramley, chief economist at the Mortgage Bankers
Association, predicted a resumption of modest rate declines and he
said this would act to spur further gains in sales.
   The July increase was the third in the past four months and put
sales at their highest level since December 1986, when homes were
sold at a seasonally adjusted rate of 784,000 units. The 14.4
percent rise was the biggest advance since a 22.9 percent jump in
September 1986.
   The report on new home sales followed a report last Friday that
sales of existing homes also improved in July, rising by 1.2 percent
to an annual rate of 3.40 million units, the second consecutive
month that existing home sales have increased.
   The price of a new home posted a modest decline in July. The
median new-home price fell 3.7 percent to $118,800. The median is
the point where half the homes sold for more and half for less.
   Some analysts said the price drop indicated that first-time
buyers, who buy less expensive homes, are re-entering the market.
But Gramley said he also believed that the decline reflected the
fact that sellers were being forced to cut their asking prices,
especially in such high-cost areas as the Northeast.
   The 55.8 percent jump in sales in the Northeast was the biggest
one-month advance for that region since February 1982. It put sales
at a seasonally adjusted annual rate of 120,000 units, 15.3 percent
above where they were a year ago.
   Sales climbed 23.8 percent in the Midwest to an annual rate of
125,000 units, the highest level of activity for this region since
February 1987.
   Sales in the West were up 8.9 percent to an annual rate of
232,000 units, while sales in the South rose by a more modest 2.4
percent to an annual rate of 261,000 units.
</TEXT>
