<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1717EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Cambodia     08-29 0646</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0667</SECOND>
<HEAD>Conference Fails in Peace Bid, New Fighting Threatened</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An international conference failed to formulate a
peace plan for Cambodia but will probably meet again next spring to
resume its work, a spokesman said Tuesday.
   Delegates predicted a full-scale resumption of the guerrilla war,
with the combatants also maintaining their political contacts.
   ``There is not at this stage the possibility for movement by any
of the Cambodian factions,'' said spokesman Jean Gueguinou.
   The 19 countries at the month-long conference were to issue a
brief declaration Wednesday at the closing ministerial session, he
said, adding the conference was likely to resume in Paris ``when
conditions are right.''
   Gueguinou said a likely time was next spring.
   The issues of national reconciliation among the warring factions
and setting up a control mechanism to monitor a standdown were the
biggest stumbling blocks, he said.
   A three-party resistance led by Prince Norodom Sihanouk has been
fighting the Vietnamese-installed government of Prime Minister Hun
Sen for a decade. Vietnam invaded Cambodia in December 1978,
toppling the Khmer Rouge from a nearly four-year reign of terror.
   The Chinese-backed Khmer Rouge, the strongest element in the
resistance, have been the central issue of contention.
   Hun Sen has rejected Sihanouk's efforts to include the Khmer
Rouge in an interim government composed of all Cambodian factions to
preside over the country before general elections. Sihanouk has
refused to exclude them from a share of power.
   The failure to reach a settlement at the conference means there
will be no international supervision of a withdrawal of Vietnamese
troops from Cambodia. Vietnam has pledged to pull out its 26,000
troops by Sept. 27 even without a peace agreement.
   Hun Sen has rejected any monitoring force under the United
Nations, which recognizes Sihanouk's coalition as legitimate
government of Cambodia.
   French Foreign Minister Roland Dumas and his Indonesian
counterpart, Ali Alatas, conference co-chairmen, decided that
compromise was impossible among the four Cambodian factions despite
``intensive consultations'' Tuesday, Gueguinou said.
   ``It was too early to reach a compromise but not too early to
work,'' he said. When the conference resumes, ``it will start with
considerable work behind it.''
   It had been widely speculated that the conference would fail in
its goal to reach a comprehensive settlement to the conflict in
Cambodia, which has endured two decades of bloodshed and turmoil.
   ``We are deadlocked here because the military situation is not
decisive,'' said a spokesman for Sihanouk's delegation, Ek
Saraywath. ``If there is no result on the battlefield, there is no
result at the negotiating table.''
   ``We may be moving into a period where ... things will go back to
the ground, to the battlefield,'' a senior U.S. official said,
demanding he not be further identified. ``There may be a period now
of some months of testing of the military balance on the ground.''
   Reports of battlefield action have increased over the past three
weeks. Western analysts attributed the renewed fighting to a
jockeying for power before the resumption in Paris of the final
ministerial session.
   ``Hun Sen thinks he can still win the war. That is why he has
made no concessions here,'' Ek said. ``When he sees that he is weak,
he will negotiate.''
   In three or four months, ``we'll see who has the advantage,'' he
said.
   The U.S. official said there was ``great uncertainty'' about the
real strength of the Khmer Rouge, and that a period of military
testing may determine who has the upper hand in any future
negotiations.
   The official refused to comment on whether the United States
could supply lethal aid to the resistance should fighting flare
again. President Bush had been pressing for aid to the two
non-communist elements of the resistance.
   ``We assume at the minimum there will be a very substantial
supply of armaments'' by Vietnam to Hun Sen's forces, he said.
</TEXT>
