<FIRST>r i AM-China     08-29 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China,0538</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Attacks on Ousted Party Chief; Possible Prelude to Trial</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The official press broadened accusations Tuesday
against ousted Communist Party chief Zhao Ziyang, saying the
reform-minded leader inspired attacks on government offices during
the spring democracy movement.
   The new attacks by two newspapers were a possible prelude to
prosecuting Zhao in what would be the first trial of a party leader
in nearly a decade.
   The newspapers said Zhao was directly responsible for massive
student marches, attacks on government offices and establishment of
illegal groups during the democracy movement through neglect of
political and ideological education.
   ``Zhao Ziyang ... proposed diluting the function of the party,''
said Economic Information. ``(He) denied the superior tradition of
the party (and) canceled the work of political education.''
   A commentary in the party newspaper, the People's Daily, said
Zhao bolstered flagging protests in Shanxi province when he told a
visiting delegation on May 4 that the government should open
dialogue with the students.
   His comments, the paper said, resulted in daily marches of tens
of thousands of people, the establishment of more than 60 illegal
organizations, attacks on provincial offices and the disruption of a
major international trade fair by thousands of students.
   Economic Information said students influenced by Zhao attacked
the socialist system at a discussion session last year with
education officials, and questioned the need for political
education. The students called ideological workers ``glib talkers
propagating dog philosophy,'' the paper said.
   Zhao was stripped of his party posts in late June after losing a
power struggle over handling of the seven-week democracy movement.
He was accused then of splitting the party and supporting the
protests.
   Since then, government officials have said the investigation into
Zhao is continuing but have refused to say if the party charges will
be turned into legal charges.
   Zhao has not been seen in public since late May, when he spoke
tearfully to students occupying Tiananmen Square. Some unofficial
reports say he is under house arrest, but government spokesman Yuan
Mu recently said Zhao was leading a normal life.
   The media have carried sporadic criticism of Zhao for weeks. But
the recent attacks have been notable for their length, detail and
specific references to damage Zhao allegedly caused by his erroneous
thinking and leadership, including leading ``vast numbers'' of
people astray.
   The commentaries may be an effort to prepare the public for the
first trial of a top party leader since the 1980 trial of the Gang
of Four, the leaders of the 1966-76 far leftist Cultural Revolution.
   Economic Information said Zhao neglected ideological work and
encouraged ``bourgeois-liberal,'' or Western, thought.
   A Worker's Daily commentary Saturday said Zhao elevated the role
of entrepreneurs while belittling workers, who should be considered
the force behind socialist modernization.
   Worker's Daily said Zhao missed the point of China's economic
reform policies of the past decade, which was to show the
superiority of socialism.
   ``Zhao Ziyang often told some people that capitalism actually was
better and our socialist system had problems,'' it said.
   A military assault on Beijing quashed the student demonstration,
killing hundreds and perhaps thousands of people.
</TEXT>
