<FIRST>r i AM-Czech-Rights     08-29 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czech-Rights,0305</SECOND>
<HEAD>Czechoslovak Dissident Convicted for Incitement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Czechoslovak court Tuesday convicted a
leading dissident of inciting rebellion and sentenced him to 20
months in prison, emigre and human rights sources said.
   The dissident, Stanislav Devaty, called the proceedings a
political trial that violated his freedom of speech, an emigre
source said on condition of anonymity.
   Defense attorney Jiri Machourek immediately appealed the
conviction, calling the proceedings unfair, according to the emigre
source, as well as Charter 77 human rights activist Dana Nemcova.
They said they were citing reports from friends of Devaty who
attended the trial.
   Devaty, 37, is a Charter 77 member who last year served as the
group's spokesman.
   The trial was held at Gottwaldov, about 125 miles east of Prague.
   Devaty was tried in connection with a petition signed by more
than 400 people calling for more religious and cultural freedom and
the release of all political prisoners. The petition was sent late
last year to the government, which made no response.
   One of the most active of Czechoslovakia's dissidents, Devaty has
been detained several times this year and released after hunger
strikes.
   Devaty initially was detained March 16 in a mass crackdown on
dissent that also put playwright Vaclav Havel and other leading
activists in jail. He was last detained Aug. 7.
   The emigre source said only five friends of Devaty were allowed
into the courtroom. Most of the 30 people attending were hired by
the government to keep out Devaty supporters, she said.
   Also present were representatives of the U.S. and Canadian
embassies, she said.
   Machourek said the evidence presented should have been
insufficent to reach a verdict, because none of the witnesses said
Devaty wrote the petition, according to the emigre source.
</TEXT>
