<FIRST>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     08-29 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Czechoslovakia,0379</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hungarian Activists Fined And Expelled From Czechoslovakia</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Hungarians were fined and
expelled from the country Tuesday for their part in an
anti-government demonstration on the anniversary of the 1968
Soviet-led invasion of Czechoslovakia.
   Gyorgy Kerenyi and Tamas Deutsch were found guilty of breach of
public order and fined $500 each, witnesses said. Western reporters
were not admitted into the proceedings at Prague District Court.
   Deutsch and Kerenyi had been in detention since they were
arrested by plainclothes police on Prague's central Wenceslas Square
Aug. 21. They had gathered a crowd of people around them and were
protesting the 1968 Soviet-led invasion.
   ``Bolsheviks came with tanks, we came with flowers,'' read their
banner rejecting Hungarian participation in the invasion. Kerenyi
delivered an emotional speech demanding liberal reforms in
Czechoslovakia similar to those underway in Hungary.
   The crowd applauded, shouted ``Long Live Hungary!'' and chanted
for freedom before uniformed police moved in to break up the protest.
   An estimated 3,000 to 4,000 Czechoslovaks then marched around
Prague for another two hours, calling for freedom and the withdrawal
of Soviet troops.
   Czechoslovak party leader Milos Jakes, echoing other party
officials, condemned the incident as ``interference in Czechoslovak
internal affairs by tourists in disguise.''
   Seven other Hungarians were among the 50 foreigners and 320
Czechoslovaks detained during the Aug. 21 demonstration. All the
others detained were released by last Thursday.
   ``I don't think we did anything wrong,'' Peter Molnar, a leading
official of the Hungarian youth group FIDESZ, said outside court
during the all-day trial, to which only Hungarian and Czechoslovak
journalists were admitted.
   ``If armies and tanks come to another country to change things,
that's interference, not if young people come with flowers and
express their views,'' he added.
   The fines were immediately paid by the Hungarian consul to
Prague, Lajos Taba, and both activists were driven to the airport.
   The charges against them carried a maximum penalty of six months
in jail and a fine of $2,000, or both.
   In Budapest, a group of Hungarians camped out in front of the
Czechoslovak Embassy ended a hunger strike they began last week to
protest the detention of the two activists in Prague.
</TEXT>
