<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--LicensePlates     08-29 0148</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--License Plates,0153</SECOND>
<HEAD>Texas Commission Rejects `Friendship State'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AUSTIN, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unfriendly reaction prompted the Highway
Commission on Tuesday to drop the idea of putting ``The Friendship
State'' on Texas license plates.
   The commission decided instead to add just the red, white and
blue state flag to the plate, which already carries a Texas map.
   On July 19, the three-member commission approved, with little
fanfare, what seemed an innocuous proposal to use ``The Friendship
State'' on the 27 million Texas license plates, hoping the cheery
message would attract tourists.
   The slogan became the topic of radio call-in shows, newspaper
surveys and coffee shop banter.
   ``It's wimpy,'' said Texas Treasurer Ann Richards, a candidate
for the Democratic nomination for governor.
   Many suggested ``The Lone Star State'' instead. A newspaper
survey came up with such suggestions as the ``Bank Failure State,''
``Don't Mess With Texas'' and ``Pinhead Legislature.''
</TEXT>
