<FIRST>r i AM-SriLanka     08-29 0453</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sri Lanka,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>59 More Killed in Sinhalese Violence in Sri Lanka</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEXTER CRUEZ</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attackers dragged 14 men from their
homes Tuesday and killed them, part of a new wave of Sinhalese
violence that left 59 people dead, officials and witnesses said.
   The reports came on the second day of a weeklong strike called by
the radicals to protest what they call genocide of their supporters
by the government.
   In Colombo, most shops, offices and businesses were open, but
only about 30 percent of government employees reported for work, an
official said.
   Residents of the village of Pandura, south of Colombo, said 14
Sinhalese men were pulled from of their homes before dawn and shot
by people wearing army-style uniforms.
   The Sinhalese-dominated government is fighting to put down a
violent campaign by Sinhalese radicals opposed to official peace
overtures toward ethnic Tamil rebels.
   The attack in Panadura followed another killing in the area
Sunday, when suspected Sinhalese radicals slayed a soldier and four
members of her family, residents reported.
   Military officials, who may not be identified under briefing
rules, confirmed 14 bodies were found near Panadura on Tuesday. But
they denied that army personnel were responsible for the deaths.
   The officials said at least 25 other bodies were found elsewhere
in the Sinhalese-dominated south and center of Sri Lanka.
   In addition, residents near the Kalu Ganga River, about 25 miles
south of Colombo, said 11 bodies had been thrown into the river.
Military officials did not mention those bodies.
   Scores of such unidentified bodies have been found in recent
weeks.
   Opposition politicians and human rights groups say such bodies
are of suspected radicals killed in revenge attacks by security
forces or pro-government vigilante groups.
   In other violence, the military officials said at least nine
people were killed in several attacks by the radicals during the 24
hours ending Tuesday evening.
   They said the victims included a former government lawmaker and
four of her bodyguards, two lawyers, and two policemen.
   At least 5,000 people have been killed in Sinhalese violence
since the radicals launched their anti-government campaign in July
1987.
   They say the government should be tougher in trying to end a
6-year-old Tamil insurgency in northeastern Sri Lanka. They also
claim that the presence of Indian peacekeeping troops, who have
tried unsuccessfully to end the Tamil uprising, compromises Sri
Lanka's sovereignty.
   In the Sinhalese general strike, radical groups had announced in
posters pasted on walls in the capital that employees could go to
their jobs but should refuse to work.
   Steel-helmeted policemen and soldiers in camouflage uniforms were
posted in Colombo and other major cities to ward off any attacks by
the radicals.
</TEXT>
