<FIRST>r i AM-Afghanistan-Clash     08-29 0421</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Afghanistan-Clash,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soldiers, Guerrillas fight in Several Cities</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Afghanistan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NEIL MacFARQUHAR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soldiers and Moslem guerrillas fought
in several provincial cities Tuesday and 10 rockets hit the capital,
the government said.
   Rival guerrilla groups were reported fighting each other in
northern and western Afghanistan.
   In a speech to the opening session of Parliament, President Najib
asked the United States, Pakistan and Saudi Arabia to stop
interfering in Afghanistan. The three nations are the guerrillas'
main backers.
   Government spokesman Mohammed Iqbal said one of the rockets
struck a house, wounding two people inside, and seven hit the
airport but caused no injuries.
   Employees and passengers fled the combined civilian-military
airport and passengers were told to return Wednesday for their
luggage, which was being unloaded when the rockets landed about 100
yards away.
   Iqbal said the level of fighting between the army and guerrillas
in three eastern cities had declined in recent days, and rocket
barrages had replaced close combat.
   Soldiers advanced east of Jalalabad, 75 miles east of Kabul, and
parried a guerrilla advance on Khost, about 100 miles to the
southeast, he said. Iqbal also claimed government troops won
victories around Kandahar in the southeast.
   He reported fighting between guerrilla factions around the
western city of Herat and in the northern provinces of Badakhshan,
Takhar and Konduz.
   The government spokesman and independent sources said the battles
were between two fundamentalist groups _ Hezb-i-Islami led by
Gulbuddin Hekmatyar and Jamiat-i-Islami fighters under field
commander Ahmad Shah Masood.
   At least 22 guerrillas were killed and an unknown number wounded
in the foothills and mountains 50 miles east of Herat, Iqbal said.
   He said he did not have statistics for the other areas. The
independent sources in Kabul said serious trouble appeared to be
developing between the rival groups.
   Jamiat leaders accused Hekmatyar last month of ordering the
killings of at least 30 of its guerrillas in the field, including
some commanders.
   Najib resumed his call for U.N.-supervised elections and said to
Parliament: ``The aggressive hand of the United States, Saudi Arabia
and Pakistan should be off Afghanistan.''
   In a weekend speech in Jalalabad, released in English on Tuesday,
Najib said the fighting had changed from a jihad, or holy war, to
fratricide.
   Moslem guerrillas began fighting after a communist coup in April
1978. Soviet military forces entered the war in December 1979 and
withdrew in February after more than nine years of involvement.
   The main guerrilla groups are based in Pakistan, Afghanistan's
eastern neighbor.
</TEXT>
