<FIRST>r i AM-Hostages     08-29 0392</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hostages,0405</SECOND>
<HEAD>Shiite Leader Calls on U.S. to Help End Lebanon War</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shiite Moslem chief Nabih Berri said
Tuesday that to solve the hostage crisis, the United States should
help end Lebanon's 14-year-old civil war.
   ``My advise to the Americans and everyone is to help resolve the
Lebanese problem,'' Berri told reporters representing foreign media
at his heavily fortified office in west Beirut.
   ``They have to go to the core of the problem in order to be able
to help resolve the hostage problem,'' Berri said.
   At least 802 people have been killed and 2,268 wounded, nearly
all of them civilians, since the latest outbreak in the civil war
began March 8 between Christian forces and a Moslem alliance led by
the 40,000 Syrian soldiers in Lebanon.
   Berri, leader of the moderate, Syrian-backed Amal movement, also
said the hostage issue was linked to the 1982 Israeli invasion of
Lebanon.
   The Israeli army withdrew from Lebanon in 1985 after a three-year
occupation but set up a self-designated security zone in the south,
six to 10 miles deep, as a buffer against cross-border guerrilla
attacks into northern Israel.
   ``Why was it before 1982 that we didn't hear of any kidnapping?''
Berri asked. ``Because before 1982 we didn't have the Israeli
invasion. All that happened to Lebanon came after that date.''
   Sixteen foreigners are missing in Lebanon. Most are believed held
by pro-Iranian, Shiite extremist groups. They include eight
Americans, four Britons, two West Germans, one Italian and one
Irishman.
   The longest held is Terry Anderson, chief Middle East
correspondent of The Associated Press, kidnapped on March 16, 1985.
   Amal is not involved in seizing hostages. The hostage-holding
groups are believed to come under the umbrella of Hezbollah, or
Party of God.
   Berri and Sheik Abbas Mousawi of Hezbollah on Thursday announced
the end of 16 months of intermittent clashes between their rival
factions for dominance of the 1.2 million Shiites, Lebanon's largest
sect.
   The feud killed nearly 575 people and wounded more than 1,550, by
police count.
   Mousawi said the ``mission for Amal and Hezbollah now is to
jointly confront the new Crusaders' invasion.''
   He referred to a French naval buildup in the eastern
Mediterranean, which the Shiites claim was designed to support
Christian army commander Gen. Michel Aoun in his confrontation with
Syria and its Moslem militia allies.
</TEXT>
