<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 2011EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-India-Strike     08-29 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-India-Strike,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Government Arrests Thousands in Sweep to Block Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAJU GOPALAKRISHNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government reportedly arrested 5,000
political workers Tuesday and asked others to stay in offices
overnight to prevent a nationwide strike to demand the resignation
of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi.
   Four major opposition parties set the general strike for
Wednesday in their latest attempt to focus attention on their
charges of government corruption.
   United News of India news agency said as many as 5,000 political
workers were arrested across the country Tuesday. There were no
details on any charges.
   The opposition has said that all businesses should be closed and
public transportation, except for essential services, should come to
a halt during the strike. The strike was intended as a show of
strength before parliamentry elections later this year.
   The government also asked thousands of its employees to stay in
their offices overnight so they could report for duty Wednesday.
   Officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said the
government was paying to provide food and bedrolls for the
employees. They were allowed to bring children into offices, the
officials said.
   Senior government executives were given rooms in luxury hotels
near their offices, they said.
   No official announcement was made about how many employees were
involved. Government employees in New Delhi said thousands of people
were being asked to stay on.
   United News of India quoted an unidentified government spokesman
as saying officials absent from work Wednesday would lose a day's
salary.
   The government planned to provide full security to all Indians
who wish to work, he was quoted as saying. Trains, state-owned
buses, and air services would function normally, he reportedly said.
   The opposition has repeatedly accused the government of
corruption in past weeks.
   Last month, 106 opposition members in Parliament demanded that
Gandhi resign, saying a July government audit of an arms deal showed
that senior officials received kickbacks.
   When Gandhi refused, the opposition members resigned in a rare
display of solidarity.
   The opposition charge relates to a $1.4 billion deal for purchase
of artillery guns from AB Bofors of Sweden. Opposition politicians
say the Swedish company paid kickbacks amounting to $50 million to
government officials and members of Gandhi's Congress Party.
   No proof has been offered, and the government has denied
wrongdoing.
   The new elections must be held sometime before the end of the
year. In the last general elections in 1985, the Congress Party won
415 of 544 seats in Parliament.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
