<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Karabakh     08-29 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Karabakh,0257</SECOND>
<HEAD>Karabakh Protest Leader Reported Acquitted</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Soviet-Ethnic, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A leader of the movement demanding the transfer of
the disputed territory of Nagorno-Karabakh from Azerbaijan to
Armenia has been acquitted of corruption charges, a documentary
filmmaker said Tuesday.
   Arkady Manucharov, chairman of the Karabakh Committee, was jailed
last autumn along with other committee leaders blamed for organizing
mass demonstrations in the Armenian capital, Yerevan.
   Filmmaker Arkady Ruderman, who is making a movie about
Nagorno-Karabakh, said Tuesday that a lower court had thrown out
corruption charges against Manucharov and the appeals court upheld
that decision Friday.
   Ruderman said Manucharov, a Yerevan glass factory manager, never
was accused of a crime connected to the protests.
   On Sunday, Manucharov was elected to a vacant seat in the
Armenian legislature with more than 90 percent of the vote, Ruderman
said. Authorities earlier refused to recognize his candidacy because
he was in jail.
   Ruderman said Manucharov apparently has not yet been released
from Moscow's Butirsky Prison.
   Meanwhile, Soviet Interior Minister Vadim Bakatin reported that
someone made ``an unconstitutional attempt to take power'' in
Nagorno-Karabakh last week, Tass said Tuesday.
   It quoted Bakatin as saying a person was killed, but did not say
when the incident occurred or give other details.
   The territory is in predominantly Moslem Azerbaijan. But it is
claimed by Armenia which, like Nagorno-Karabakh, is overwhelmingly
Christian.
   There have been frequent reports of violence in the area this
summer, some involving gunfire and explosives.
</TEXT>
