<FIRST>r p AM-LelandSeat     08-29 0252</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Leland Seat,0262</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mickey Leland's Widow Decides Not to Enter Race</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA TOLLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mickey Leland's widow announced Tuesday she will
not run for his U.S. House seat this fall.
   In a statement, Alison Leland, a 30-year-old investment banker,
cited her family responsibilities in deciding against seeking the
seat held by her husband for 10{ years before his death in a plane
crash in Ethiopia on Aug. 7.
   Mrs. Leland said she would support City Councilman Rodney Ellis
if he decides to run in the Nov. 7 special election.
   ``Mickey and I did discuss the future and the possibility that
someday he might pursue another career,'' she said. ``It is clear to
me that Mickey would have wanted to be succeeded by City Councilman
Rodney Ellis. He loved Rodney, he trusted Rodney, and considered him
to be among his closest friends.''
   Leland, a Democrat, and 15 others were killed when their plane
crashed while en route to an Ethiopian refugee camp on a hunger
relief mission.
   Ellis has said he would put off a decision about running until
Mrs. Leland announced her intentions.
   There was no immediate comment from Ellis; he did not return
calls to his office Tuesday.
   Since Leland's memorial service, state Sen. Craig Washington and
state Rep. Al Edwards have announced they will run. Several others
are considered possible candidates.
   Mrs. Leland, who has a 3-year-old son and is pregnant, said her
family responsibilities are too important to consider running for
Congress.
</TEXT>
