<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1942EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-SovietPrisoner     08-29 0367</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet Prisoner,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>Labor Camp Inmate Who Met With U.S. Lawmakers Gets Stiffer Sentence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet labor camp inmate who met recently
with two visiting U.S. congressmen is being moved to another
facility where conditions are worse, an advocacy group for Soviet
Jews said Tuesday.
   The Union of Councils for Soviet Jews said it believes Mikhail
Petrovich Kazachkov is being punished for his outspokenness with the
American visitors.
   Kazachkov was tried on Aug. 25 in Perm Camp 35 on charges of
``refusal to work'' and sentenced to be transferred to the Chistopol
prison, the union said.
   Kazachkov, a physicist who heads a human rights monitoring group
at the camp, went on strike with eight other inmates to demand safer
work conditions, the union said.
   Sergei Kovalev, a former political prisoner, told the
Washington-based group in a telephone call from Moscow that the food
and conditions at Chistopol are worse than at Perm 35, ``and there
is less opportunity for fresh air.''
   Kazachkov, 45, was arrested in 1975, one week after applying to
emigrate. He was convicted of treason and other offenses and
sentenced to 15 years in a labor camp. In 1981 he was given an
additional 3{ years after protesting prison conditions.
   In 1987, the authorities offered to free Kazachkov if he
confessed to his alleged crimes on television, but he refused, the
union said. He suffered a heart attack the same year.
   Last December, he was visited by New York Times columnist A.M.
Rosenthal, and last month he was allowed a visit by Rep. Christopher
Smith, R-N.J., and Frank Wolf, R-Va.
   In an interview, Wolf said Soviet authorities had promised him
there would not be any reprisals of the kind carried out against
some prisoners after Rosenthal's visit. Wolf said he had spoken with
23 of the 38 inmates at Perm 35, which is situated in the foothills
of the Ural Mountains.
   ``There's no doubt Kazachkov is a prisoner of conscience. He
ought to be released from prison,'' Wolf said. ``This is an
opportunity for the Soviets to review his and other cases and to
show that glasnost is coming to the prison system too.''
</TEXT>
