<FIRST>r a AM-MissingMan'sWill     08-29 0287</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Missing Man's Will,0296</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Who May Have Clues on Missing Industrialist to Split His Estate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVANSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man who may have the only clues to the
1980 disappearance of an industrialist is about to inherit nearly
half the businessman's $1.3 million estate.
   Donald Baggett, who was with industrialist Joseph F. Derr, then
73, on vacation in Mexico when Derr disappeared, has refused to talk
to police, and investigators have turned up no information on Derr's
whereabouts.
   Most of Derr's estate will be divided, according to his will,
between Baggett, 56, and a Pennsylvania school district once Probate
Judge Robert H. Lensing signs an order disbursing the money.
Lensing's action is considered a formality.
   Derr made his fortune in decorative plastics for appliances,
automobiles and business machines. His will, written in 1976, became
public in 1987 after the state asked that Derr be declared legally
dead.
   The court case dragged on while the state and other parties
challenged Lensing's decision to offer a $500,000 reward and spend
$100,000 from the estate on a renewed investigation into Derr's
disappearance. A state appeals court overturned Lensing's decision
last month.
   Derr went to Acapulco in December 1979 for his annual four-month
vacation, and Baggett soon joined him, court records show. Both men
were reported missing in January 1980.
   Baggett showed up the next month with a lawyer at the Evansville
Police Department. He refused to answer questions.
   Lensing ordered Baggett to appear at a hearing, but he refused to
answer questions, citing his Fifth Amendment right against
self-incrimination.
   Baggett and the school district in Benton, Pa., where Derr grew
up, each will receive $441,797. Baggett also will get the $129,000
Evansville duplex he shared with Derr.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
