<FIRST>r i AM-ChemicalArms     08-29 0274</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chemical Arms,0282</SECOND>
<HEAD>Japan Sees Chance to Ban Chemical Arms Slipping Away</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Japan told international negotiators ending their
latest talks Tuesday they may be letting chances fade for adopting a
global ban on chemical weapons.
   Chusei Yamada, Tokyo's chief envoy to the 40-nation Conference on
Disarmament, suggested the conference agree on a target date for
adopting a draft treaty.
   As the chemical weapons talks ended the 10-week session, Yamada
said progress was made this year mainly on technical issues. He said
the ``important political issues,'' such as provisions for
monitoring compliance, were unresolved.
   Yamada said a 149-nation conference on chemicals arms held in
Paris in January gave political impetus to the Geneva talks, but he
expressed ``a sense of uneasiness that the momentum might be
slipping out of our fingers.''
   The talks were entering a three-month recess.
   The United States has told Western allies it will not accept an
``artificial deadline'' at the conference, which has been debating a
global convention banning production, stockpiling and use of
chemical arms since 1968.
   French envoy Pierre Morel, who presides over the conference's
chemical arms negotiating committee, said the draft treaty was
``sharply improved'' this year.
   He said new provisions were added on protecting the
confidentiality of private chemical plants and progress was made in
working out an international inspection mechanism and classification
of toxic chemicals to be banned.
   Conference negotiators expect their next session to begin
incorporating U.S.-Soviet proposals on the destruction of stockpiles
and inspection procedures into the draft accord, Morel said.
   Talks on the treaty are to resume Nov. 28. The full conference is
expected to reconvene early next year.
</TEXT>
