<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1905EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Glemp     08-29 0761</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Glemp,0784</SECOND>
<HEAD>Primate's Comments on Jews Stir New Controversy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   World clamor set off by Cardinal John
Glemp's remarks grew louder Tuesday. One charge hurled at the head
of Poland's Roman Catholic Church was that he used Nazi-like
arguments against Jews.
   Glemp's Saturday comments were meant to calm international
criticism about his church's attitude toward Jews. Instead, his
speech set off a new round of controversy about alleged
anti-Semitism in the church.
   Glemp told pilgrims at Jasna Gora Monastery at Czestochowa,
Poland, that Polish anti-Semitism would disappear if Jews abandon
``anti-Polonism,'' or anti-Polish sentiments.
   He asked Jews to understand that it offended Poles' religious
sensibilities and feelings of sovereignty for Jews to insist on
removal of a Carmelite convent set up on the edge of the former Nazi
German death camp at Auschwitz in Poland.
   ``Dear Jews, do not talk to us from the position of a nation
elevated over all others and do not put to us conditions that are
impossible to meet,'' Glemp said.
   But some of his language _ invoking the image of Jews spreading
communism, mentioning that some Jews collaborated with Nazis during
World War II, that Jews as businessmen neglected or detested Poles,
and saying that Jews have easy access to mass media _ apparently
added fuel to charges of anti-Semitism.
   ``The expressions used by the primate, even contrary to his
intentions, pose a danger of deeply wounding the feelings of many of
those who are descendants and brothers of the Holocaust victims,''
said Catholic journalist Krzysztof Sliwinski in a rare published
criticism of Glemp.
   The commentary appeared Monday in the opposition's Gazeta
Wyborcza newspaper.
   Elsewhere the response was even more biting.
   Referring to Glemp's comment about easy Jewish access to mass
media, the International League against Racism and Anti-Semitism
said in Paris it regretted that Glemp ``made use of arguments used
against Jews by the Nazis yesterday and by the extreme right in
France today.''
   Yossi Sarid, a legislator from the left-wing Citizens Rights
Movement in Israel, said Tuesday in Jerusalem, ``Anti-Semitism has a
long history in Poland and I think it is ridiculous to talk about
`anti-Polonism.'
   Rome's Chief Rabbi Elio Toaff said in a newspaper interview the
question of anti-Semitism is something the church ``has to face.
...The analysis has to be deep enough to eradicate once and for all
the anti-Semitism that still exists in many countries, like Poland.''
   ``It is particularly serious that it was Glemp, one noted for
diplomacy and political gifts, who confused cause and effects,''
said Tullia Zevi, head of the Union of Italian Jewish Communities,
quoted in the same article Monday in Rome's I Messaggero.
   The Representative Council of Jewish Institutions of France
issued a statement Monday calling Glemp's comments ``malicious and
out of place.''
   They ``bring us back to a period we believed was forgotten: that
of 50 years ago, before the war, when comments of this type were
made and led to the tragedy that we know about.''
   Relations between the Polish church and Jewish organizations were
already strained by church refusal to relocate the community of
Carmelite nuns from Auschwitz. The convent site has been criticized
as offensive because most of the camp's victims were executed simply
for being Jews.
   An estimated 2.5 million of the 4 million victims of
Auschwitz-Birkenau were Jewish.
   Cardinal Franciszek Macharski of Krakow, whose diocese includes
the camp, announced Aug. 10 that the church was suspending a 1987
agreement to move the convent. He said it could not fulfill the
agreement in an atmosphere of ``aggressive demands.''
   The proposal to remove the convent, which was founded in 1984
just outside the Auschwitz fence, has found little sympathy in
Poland. Poles have commonly argued that thousands of the victims at
Auschwitz were Polish political prisoners, including many priests
and nuns.
   Cardinal Albert DeCourtray, archbishop of Lyon in France, said
Tuesday it was unlikely that Glemp's words were meant the way they
were received.
   He said the ``primate and bishops of Poland cannot be accused of
an anti-Semitism, which they denounce.''
   The issue of anti-Semitism remains much discussed in Poland even
though only several thousand Jews remain compared to a prewar Jewish
population of 3.5 million.
   Poles often feel wrongly accused of blanket anti-Semitism or of
playing an active role in the Holocaust, carried out by Nazi German
occupiers of Poland.
   Few Poles deny that anti-Semitism exists here, but they often
argue that it is exaggerated and note that many Poles risked their
own lives to protect Jews during the war.
</TEXT>
