<FIRST>r i AM-Poland-Lithuania     08-29 0190</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Lithuania,0197</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lithuanian National Movement Congratulates Mazowiecki</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The grass-roots independence movement in
the Soviet republic of Lithuania has congratulated Prime Minister
Tadeusz Mazowiecki on becoming the East bloc's first non-communist
leader, PAP reported Tuesday.
   ``Your victory is also our victory,'' the state news agency
quoted a telegram sent by the Lithuanian Movement for
Reconstruction, Sajudis, as saying.
   ``We have no doubt that the experience of heroic struggle of
Solidarity makes the strivings for freedom and independence by your
closest neighbors understandable to you.''
   Mazowiecki, a longtime Solidarity journalist, was elected prime
minister by the Sejm, or lower house of Parliament, on Thursday.
   Soviet President Mikhail S. Gorbachev recently complained that
Lithuanian activists are pressing too hard for independence from the
Soviet Union, Sajudis members have reported.
   The histories of neighboring Lithuania and Poland long have been
intertwined. The countries were linked from 1386 to 1795, first
through a family dynasty and later as a joint commonwealth.
   The Lithuanian capital of Vilnius was captured by Poland in 1920
and held until 1939. Today, Lithuania retains a significant Polish
minority, and Poland has a small Lithuanian minority.
</TEXT>
