<DOCNO> AP890829-0154 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 2043EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Waldheim     08-29 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Waldheim,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Britain Publishing Inquiry Into Austrian President</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain said Tuesday it will publish in full the
findings of its inquiry into whether Austrian President Kurt
Waldheim is linked to the Nazi executions of six British commandos
in World War II.
   A Defense Ministry spokesman, speaking on condition of anonymity,
said the report ordered by Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher in
February 1988 will be published within a few weeks, but no date was
fixed.
   He would not elaborate, and made no comment on a British
newspaper report Tuesday that the findings are likely to be
inconclusive.
   The Daily Telegraph, quoting defense sources, said the report
would shed ``fresh light'' on the war record of Waldheim, a former
U.N. secretary-general who was an intelligence officer in the German
army. But it added ``no major revelations are likely.''
   Speculation has arisen that some evidence may be suppressed
because of possible postwar links between Waldheim and British and
U.S. intelligence services.
   The six commandos were in a raiding party captured in the
German-occupied Balkans in April 1944. They were handed over for
interrogation to Waldheim's unit in Army Group E, refused to talk,
and were executed. It is a crime under the Geneva Convention to kill
prisoners of war.
   An international commission of historians that investigated
Waldheim's army career reported in February 1988 that the initial
``W'' was on transcripts of interrogations of the six men.
   The commission said it could not prove a connection between
Waldheim and the commandos, but suggested he knew they were shot by
the Gestapo under a general order by Adolf Hitler to execute
commandos.
   The Britons' fate was part of the commission's inquiry into
charges that Waldheim took part in or facilitated atrocities,
including massacres of 60,000 Yugoslav partisans and civilians and
rounding up Jews for death camps.
   The commission concluded Waldheim lied about his war record, knew
about atrocities and did nothing to stop them, but left open the
question of guilt.
   Waldheim says he did nothing wrong after being drafted into the
German army.
   For the British inquiry, the United States sent to London copies
of German army war records relating to the commandos' capture. The
original files were among documents captured by American forces as
the war ended in 1945.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
