<FIRST>r i AM-Germany-Refugees     08-29 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Germany-Refugees,0439</SECOND>
<HEAD>Newspaper Says Hungary Will Pass Thousands of East Germans</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRENCE PETTY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BONN, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four new refugee camps will be built to
handle an expected increase in what already is a flood of East
Germans fleeing their strict communist homeland through Hungary,
officials said Tuesday.
   The Munich newspaper Abendzeitung said huge tent cities for
refugees were planned in Bavaria and thousands of East Germans
visiting Hungary would be allowed to go directly to the West.
   Anton Haussmann, spokesman for Bavaria's Social Ministry, said
four new camps with a total capacity of 5,000 people will be built
in the southern state as temporary homes for new East German
refugees. Two other camps already exist, in Hesse and North
Rhine-Westphalia states.
   Haussmann denied the Abendzeitung report that 15,000 East Germans
would arrive in West Germany from Hungary by the weekend.
   The newspaper sent telexes of its report to other news
organizations in advance of Wednesday's publication.
   Rudolf Seiters, Chancellor Helmut Kohl's chief of staff,
confirmed that West Germany was preparing for a greater influx of
East German refugees.
   ``It is the federal government's responsibility to make
preparations for all possible eventualities,'' he said during an
evening newscast on the ZDF television network.
   East Germans are given automatic citizenship by West Germany and
receive assistance in starting new lives.
   Hungary already has said it would not return East Germans against
their will. West German and Hungarian government officials have held
talks about the East German refugees.
   Discontented East Germans have left by the tens of thousands in
the past few months, by both legal and illegal means. At least
100,000 are expected to reach West Germany by the end of the year.
   More than 5,000 East Germans have escaped through Hungary since
the liberal communist regime began in May to dismantle the barbed
wire and other barriers along its border with Austria.
   Scores of East Germans have taken refuge in West German
diplomatic missions in East Berlin and Prague, the Czechoslovak
capital.
   The situation has caused tension between East and West Germany.
Bonn demands that East Germany undertake reforms that would remove
the reasons for large numbers of people to leave. East Germany
claims West Germany incited the exodus.
   Junge Welt, or Youth World, the East German Communist Party youth
paper, published a letter Tuesday that called the refugees traitors.
   Czechoslovakia's ambassador in Bonn, Dusan Spacil, said harboring
East Germans in West German diplomatic missions was a ``misuse'' of
the function of such facilities, the Badische Zeitung of Freiburg
reported.
</TEXT>
