<FIRST>u a AM-NJDisturbance     08-29 0541</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-NJ Disturbance,0563</SECOND>
<HEAD>Police Shooting Sparks Looting, Rioting</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MELANIE BURNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VINELAND, N.J., (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Merchants boarded up storefronts and swept
up broken glass Tuesday after a night of vandalism and looting
sparked by the fatal police shooting of a black man.
   Leaders of this city of 54,000 people about 40 miles southeast of
Philadelphia moved to prevent another night of violence.
   Samuel Clark, president of the local chapter of the National
Association for the Advancement of Colored People, met with Mayor
Harry Curley to try to defuse racial tensions that escalated into
rioting Monday night by nearly 200 people on the city's main street
and the arrest of 23 people.
   In New York City, religious and community leaders met with
reporters, and called for continued efforts to root out racism in
the wake of the fatal shooting of a black teen-ager by white youths
last week.
   In a separate statement, New York Gov. Mario Cuomo called on New
Yorkers to pray ``that we will make this moment of shame a time for
honesty and renewal.''
   Police said the gang in the borough of Brooklyn attacked four
black youths because they believed the four were going to visit a
young woman who had spurned one of the gang members. Yusef Hawkins,
16, was killed.
   The New Jersey violence followed Sunday's shooting of Samuel
Williams, 26.
   About 40 businesses and 20 cars were damaged by rocks and
bottles, most of them along a mile-long stretch, police said. Four
people were injured.
   Damage was estimated at $75,000 to $100,000 for broken windows,
and officials were still trying to gauge losses from looting, city
spokesman Lee Tofanelli said at an afternoon news conference.
   Eight of those arrested were charged with burglary, assault and
theft. police said. The remaining 15 were charged with disorderly
persons offenses. All were released.
   Tofanelli said city patrols were beefed up Tuesday night and
officers had orders to arrest any disorderly persons.
   Williams was shot after he apparently threatened officer Paul
Letizia with a steel rod, said Police Chief Joseph Cassisi.
Williams, who was wanted on drug and weapon charges, was spotted by
officers after police received an anonymous call about a man on a
bicycle carrying drugs, Cassisi said.
   After being told he was under arrest, Williams picked up the rod
and approached Letizia, swinging, Cassisi said. Letizia, who is
white, fired two shots at Williams, hitting him both times.
   Police found no drugs on Williams. The state attorney general's
office has taken over the investigation of the shooting.
   At the city's news conference, the victim's sister, Velma Doyle,
called for an end to the violence.
   ``I really would hope everyone would calm down and wait to see
what really happened,'' she said.
   Before Tuesday's meeting, Clark of the NAACP called for
Cassissi's resignation, saying he had mishandled the matter.
   He said that many in the community became angry over newspaper
reports in which the police chief called the shooting a
``justifiable homicide.''
   ``That was the catalyst,'' Clark said. ``That sparked the anger.''
   Cassisi, in a statement read Tuesday by city spokesman Tofanelli,
said, ``in the absence of a complete investigation, it appears to me
that proper police procedures were followed in the shooting
incident.''
</TEXT>
