<FIRST>r a AM-ReactorShutdown     08-29 0452</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Reactor Shutdown,0463</SECOND>
<HEAD>Nuclear Reactor Closed Earlier Than Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLATTEVILLE, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The troubled Fort St. Vrain nuclear
power plant, the nation's only helium-cooled reactor, was shut down
nearly a year earlier than planned because of cracks in steam tubes,
utility officials said Tuesday.
   The hairline cracks found Aug. 18 in tubes that supply steam to
drive the the plant's turbine generator pose no threat to the
public, but fixing them would have required a lengthy shutdown
anyway, officials said.
   The 330-megawatt reactor 35 miles north of Denver has repeatedly
experienced equipment problems and unplanned shutdowns since opening
in 1976. In December, Public Service Co. of Colorado said it planned
to end nuclear operations at the plant in June 1990.
   ``Although we had hoped the plant would perform through the first
half of 1990, our board and executive management feel this is the
most prudent action to take in light of the new difficulties at the
plant,'' said utility Chairman Delwin Hock.
   Utility officials, however, would not rule out resuming nuclear
operations at Fort St. Vrain, even though they had ruled it out in
December.
   Public Service spokeswoman Peggy Morton said the utility could
permanently close the plant, convert it to fossil fuel or resume
nuclear operations with financial help. The Nuclear Regulatory
Commission has licensed the plant to run through 2008.
   However, Morton said plant workers have begun removing nuclear
fuel from the reactor and are preparing to decommission it.
   Hock said layoffs are expected, but not for at least a month.
   He said the shutdown would not hurt the utility financially
because it already has written off the estimated costs.
   Fort St. Vrain never has operated for any length of time at 100
percent capacity. In 1984, a series of equipment problems closed the
plant for 22 months. In 1986, the NRC identified it as one of the 10
worst-run nuclear power plants in the United States. The agency took
it off the list last year.
   The latest shutdown came after a routine test Aug. 18 indicated a
problem with a control rod in the reactor's fuel core. While
replacing the faulty rod, crews discovered the cracks.
   Gas-cooled reactors have been widely used in Europe, but Fort St.
Vrain is the only one of its kind in the United States. Public
Service officials have blamed the choice of a water-lubricated
bearing for its turbine-like helium circulators for many of the
plant's problems, saying the bearing proved more sensitive than
anticipated.
   Fort St. Vrain also is the only U.S. commercial reactor with a
graphite fuel core. The Soviet reactor at Chernobyl, which exploded
and burned in 1986, had a graphite core, which was cooled by water
rather than helium.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
