<FIRST>r a AM-TropicalWeather     08-29 0171</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tropical Weather,0175</SECOND>
<HEAD>Weakened Tropical Storm Felix Remains Out to Sea</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A weakening Tropical Storm Felix remained far out in
the Atlantic Ocean on Tuesday, its 40-mph winds causing problems
only for ships, forecasters said.
   At 6 p.m. EDT, Felix's center was near 21.8 degrees north
latitude and 28.2 degrees west longitude, or about 380 miles
north-northwest of the Cape Verde Islands.
   The system, barely strong enough to remain a named storm, was
heading west- northwest at about 7 mph, with some increase in speed
likely, forecaster Hal Gerrish said at the National Hurricane Center
in Coral Gables, Fla.
   Felix's winds, which were at 50 mph on Monday, showed no sign of
picking up again, forecasters said.
   Felix is the sixth named storm of the Atlantic hurricane season,
which runs from June 1 through Nov. 30.
   A tropical depression becomes a named storm when sustained winds
reach 39 mph and a hurricane if winds climb to 74 mph. There have
been three hurricanes so far this season.
</TEXT>
