<FIRST>u w AM-GalaxyBirth 1stLd-Writethru a0617 08-29 0747</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Galaxy Birth, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0617,730</SECOND>
<HEAD>Cloud Of Hydrogen May Be Forming Galaxy, Astronomers Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: SUBS word ``huge'' for ``massive'' in lede and 14th graf,
Most astronomers ...; DELETES word ``massive'' from overline. ^By PAUL
RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A huge disk of hydrogen gas discovered 65
million light years away suggests that galaxies are still being
formed in the universe, a finding that could modify the current
theory that star systems formed within a relatively short time after
the ``big bang.''
   Riccardo Giovanelli, head of the Radio Astronomy Group at the
National Astronomy and Ionosphere Center in Arecibo, Puerto Rico,
and Martha Haynes, associate professor of astronomy at Cornell
University, found the gas cloud earlier this year using the
1,000-foot radiotelescope dish at Arecibo.
   Others astronomers said Tuesday that the findings were
``exciting'' and ``important'' and could reshape the current view of
the history of the universe.
   The cloud of hydrogen gas is 10 times larger in diameter than the
Milky Way Galaxy, which includes the sun, and appears to be in the
shape of a disk that is rotating slowly, the National Science
Foundation announced.
   Carl Heiles, a professor of astronomy at the University of
California, Berkeley, said the gas cloud ``is a very important
discovery.''
   ``It shows that there are clouds of gas out there that have not
yet turned into galaxies,'' he said. Further study, said Heiles,
could lead to modifications of the basic ``big bang'' concept of the
universe.
   The ``big bang'' theory postulates that the universe began with a
cataclysmic explosion 10 billion to 20 billion years ago and that
galaxies of stars formed within a few hundred million years after
that. Astronomers have earlier reported findings that suggested star
formation within existing galaxies, and studies that indicated that
some galaxies may have formed billions of years later than others.
   But there have been no earlier reported findings of true
``proto-galaxies,'' or star systems at the very beginning of
formation. The general belief has been that such formation halted
billions of years ago.
   Giovanelli and Haynes said they made the discovery through luck.
They were attempting to calibrate the radiotelescope by aiming it at
a part of the sky they thought was empty.
   ``Before stumbling into this thing, neither I nor Martha were
great believers in the existence of such objects,'' Giovanelli said
in a statement. ``But this cloud indicates that the disks of
galaxies can form slowly throughout the history of the universe and
not just be something that happened during some magic period of the
distant past.''
   Gas clouds have been discovered in the heavens, but those were
associated with existing galaxies.
   ``This cloud seems to have formed independently, in a pocket of
space isolated from other galaxies,'' said Giovanelli.
   No stars were found in the gas cloud.
   Most astronomers believe that galaxies form when hydrogen atoms
collect in
   huge clouds that are collapsed by gravity and that form clumps
that further gravitational collapse turn into stars.
   Giovanelli and Haynes estimated the mass of the cloud at about a
tenth of the Milky Way, which contains billions of stars.
   Heiles said the relatively small mass of the cloud presents no
problems to the theory that it is a proto-galaxy.
   ``There are lots of small galaxies out there, lots that are about
10 percent the size of our Milky Way,'' he said.
   James Rose, an associate professor of astromony at the University
of North Carolina who has studied young galaxies, called the new
finding ``very exciting.''
   ``This would be the first time that we could see a mass of gas
changing itself into a galaxy,'' he said. ``It offers the
opportunity to study the process in great detail.''
   Rose said that fact that the cloud is close to Earth by
astronomical standards, just 65 million light years away, will help
astronomers study it. A light year is a measure of distance used by
astronomers. It is the distance that light travels through a vacuum
in one year, about 5.7 trillion miles.
   Heiles said the next step now is to conduct a careful search for
other such clouds in the universe. He said astronomers may find that
there are many other such clouds, or forming galaxies.
   Presently, said Heiles, it is believed that vast areas of the
heavens are devoid of any matter. He said a survey might find that
many of those voids are not empty at all, but filled with hydrogen
clouds, or proto-galaxies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0164 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 2051EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i AM-Argentina     08-29 0547</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Argentina,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Showdown Looms Between Government, Labor as Teachers Plan Strike</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ED McCULLOUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A showdown between the new
government and organized labor shaped up on Tuesday as bus drivers
in the capital refused to work and teachers prepared a nationwide
strike.
   The bus drivers and teachers, along with doctors in municipal
hospitals and public employees in the provinces, are demanding
salary increases that exceed guidelines set by the economy and labor
ministries.
   ``We insist on a pay floor of 75,000 australs (about $114) for
the month of August,'' said Maria Sanchez, secretary-general of the
200,000-member Confederation of Argentine Educators.
   The monthly base now is about $46. The 48-hour strike was to
begin Wednesday.
   Menem belongs to the Peronist Party, whose traditional base is
organized labor, but government and labor have been heading for a
clash since he was sworn in as president on July 8.
   Faced with a huge budget deficit and hyperinflation, the new
government raised public utility rates by several hundred percent,
pledged to sell off money-losing state companies, and implemented
``voluntary'' wage and price controls.
   The Labor Ministry threatened to revoke collective bargaining
pacts that exceeded 175 percent for the July-September period. Most
fell within that limit, though the cost of living soared by 197
percent in July alone.
   Labor leaders complained that workers cannot pay the higher
utility rates, face firings or reduced wages in any privatization
plan, and that the guidelines allowed prices to rise higher than
wages.
   ``My main obligation is to defend the interests of workers,''
Saul Ubaldini, leader of the 3 million-member General Labor
Confederation, said. ``I'm Peronist, but I'm not servile to
anybody.''
   To restart an economy in recession, Menem is willing to make
concessions to business that organized labor is not inclined to
accept.
   On Tuesday, Economy Minister Nestor Rapanelli proposed that as a
temporary measure, businesses be allowed to hire employees for up to
three years with no commitments to job security or unemployment
insurance.
   On Tuesday, bus drivers demanding a raise of 36 percent over the
recently negotiated monthly pay floor of about $95 refused to charge
passengers. Many owners pulled their buses off the streets.
   Coffins piled up in cemeteries in La Matanza, the most densely
populated district of metropolitan Buenos Aires, as municipal
workers, including grave diggers, refused to work.
   Public employees in Mar del Plata and San Miguel de Tucuman
struck for higher pay. Butchers in Rosario, Argentina's
third-biggest city, refused to pay electricity bills that are up to
2,500 percent higher than the previous month.
   The Menem government, conscious of the food riots that shook the
country last May, has tried to ease the way for its program of
economic restructuring.
   Private and public sector workers have received clothing
allowances, one-time bonuses and advances on monthly salaries. Soup
kitchens feed hundreds of thousands of hungry Argentines in the
countryside.
   Some progress has been reported under the new government.
Inflation is projected to increase by 35 percent in August, and by
10 percent or less in September.
   Real wages in July were about 30 percent higher than in June.
   The austral currency has stabilized against the dollar and
interest rates have plunged. Prices in supermarkets and department
stores have come down slightly.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
