<HEAD>Bush's Only Daughter Separates from Husband</HEAD>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine, (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush's only daughter,
Dorothy, has separated from her husband, William LeBlond, sources
told The Associated Press.
   The White House officially issued no comment on the separation,
which was confirmed by sources close to the family. First Lady
Barbara Bush's press secretary, Anna Perez, said only, ``It's her
private affair.'' She said there would be no other comment.
   Bush spokesman Steve Hart also declined comment.
   One source said the White House was ``taking a firm position''
not to talk about the matter.
   Mrs. LeBlond, 30, has been with her parents during much of the
president's vacation at his seaside home that began Aug. 16. She
frequently jogs with her father in the morning.
   She lives in nearby Cape Elizabeth and works as head of the Maine
tourism bureau.
   She celebrated her birthday on Aug. 18 at the family vacation
home on Walker's Point, with many relatives present. White House
sources said her husband, a construction contractor, was absent.
   The Bush family apparently has decided not to publicly discuss
the separation, which is the only one that has occurred among the
president's five children.
   ``They're not thrilled but what can they do?'' said one source,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   The LeBlonds have two young children, Sam and Ellie.
