<FIRST>r a AM-Lutherans 1stLd-Writethru a0689 08-29 0426</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lutherans, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0689,0434</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lutherans, in Tangle, Approve Measure Seen as Pro-Choice on Abortion</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 11 grafs to UPDATE with delegates rejecting original
abortion statement, adopting neutral one; picks up 9th graf, `But in...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Evangelical Lutheran Church in America
adopted but later rejected a measure on abortion Tuesday that some
interpreted as pro-choice. A neutral version was later approved.
   In drawn-out, emotional sessions of the denomination's assembly,
delegates voted down an initially approved statement after several
said it upheld access to abortion.
   ``Some felt it supported abortion on demand, others that it did
not,'' said the Rev. Herbert Knutsen of Rice Lake, Wis., urging
reconsideration of the statement. The original was tossed out, then
revived in changed form.
   ``It was not intended to be divisive,'' said Louise Shoemaker of
Philadelphia who sponsored the original resolution.
   She proposed the amended version, eliminating an earlier phrase
calling for ``free acess to services'' and substituting ``personal
care, information, counseling and competent Christian guidance.''
   A nurse, Betty Jane Reisner of Whitehall, Pa., pleaded against
the substitute, saying, ``Pro-choice allows pro-life. The reverse is
not true. This is taking away our freedom.''
   Robert Vargas of Woodville, Wis., and others urged retention of
the original statement because of the the church's diversity and to
give ``opportunity for ministry to one and all.''
   The question had been simmering several days among delegates of
the newly merged 5.3-million-member denomination, which had taken no
stand on the issue.
   ``We must begin to lead or be led,'' said Guy Erwin of New Haven,
Conn. Calling the issue ``urgent, excruciating and personal,'' he
urged prompt post-assembly study and action by the church's interim
policy-making counsel.
   ``We must risk deep disagreement for the sake of the church,''
Erwin said.
   Favoring the original measure, Anne Cuba, a Binghamton, N.Y.,
nurse, appealed for Christians to ``trust women'' and give them the
``freedom to make their best choices in God's world.''
   But in a pained voice, the Rev. Paul Hinlicky of Delhi, N.Y.,
exclaimed, ``I will not obey this call for free access to abortion
on demand!''
   The three denominations that merged into the new body had taken
differing positions on abortion, from accepting it in limited
circumstances and defining human life as beginning at conception to
stressing the right to personal choice.
   The eight-day assembly, which ends Wednesday, is the first since
the 1988 merger of the Lutheran Church in America, the American
Lutheran Church and the Association of Evangelical Lutheran Churches.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
