<HEAD>Three Stroessner Generals Offer Restitution</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ASUNCION, Paraguay (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three generals offered Tuesday to
return millions of dollars in cash and property if officials drop
charges that they illegally enriched themselves under the 34-year
Stroessner regime, their attorneys said.
   The offers come as auditors reportedly are uncovering massive
irregularities at state companies and agencies following the
February overthrow of Gen. Alfredo Stroessner.
   President Gen. Andres Rodriguez, who toppled Stroessner and then
was overwhelmingly elected president on May 1, has pledged to
recover and redistribute property and goods stolen from the
government and people of Paraguay.
   Gen. Roberto Knopfelmacher, who after the coup was ousted from
his position running the national steel company, offered to return
$4 million to the government, his lawyer said on condition of
anonymity.
   Hugo de Jesus Araujo, the general who used to direct the
Institute of Social Planning, offered several mansions, a 2,470-acre
ranch and cash, his attorney said, also on condition of anonymity.
   Former police chief Alcibiades Britez, another general, said
through his atorney he would make 20,470 acres of land available to
landless peasants.
   The new director of Paraguayan Steel Inc. accepted
Knopfelmacher's offer, but said the audit will continue and the
retired general may have to return more assets.
   The Institute of Social Planning did not accept or reject the
offer of Araujo, whose arrest pending trial has been ordered by a
judge.
