<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 2236EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Brazil-AmazonPlagues     08-29 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brazil-Amazon Plagues,0485</SECOND>
<HEAD>Brazil Fighting Hepatitis and Malaria in Amazon</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JORGE MEDEROS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Health Ministry said Tuesday it is
starting a multimillion-dollar campaign to stop the spread of
hepatitis and malaria _ the centuries-old scourges that kill
thousands each year in the Amazon jungle.
   The campaign is to include spraying huts and lean-tos in the
Amazon rain forest with $198-million worth of DDT, the cheap but
powerful insecticide banned in many countries.
   Health Minister Seigo Tsuzuki said the World Bank will help pay
for the DDT-spraying campaign.
   In an interview, he said Brazil begins a $4.4 million vaccination
campaign Thursday against hepatitis ``B'' in Lambrea, a backwoods
town in Amazonas state known for its high incidence of the illness.
   Some 93,000 children under nine years old will be given Belgian
vaccines in what Tsuzuki claimed is the world's first mass
immunization against the disease that inflames the liver.
   Some 10,000 workers will be involved in the campaign, which will
be monitored by scientists from Cuba, France, Belgium and the World
Health Organization, Tsuzuki said in an interview.
   In Brazil, hepatitis afflicts 7.4 percent of the population and
malaria 3.3 percent, according to government statistics. The
ministry says four of every 1,000 Amazon residents die each year
from hepatitis.
   Tsuzuki said the government plans to use the vaccine nationwide,
in hopes of bringing the disease under control within three years.
   To contain malaria, they plan a five-year campaign involving
$198-million worth of DDT, he said.
   Last year, the ministry registered 560,000 cases of malaria in
Brazil, up from 500,000 a year earlier. The number is expected to
rise again this year.
   Malaria is almost exclusively a problem of Amazonia, a 2 million-
square-mile wilderness sprawled across northern and western Brazil.
   The government plans to send 70,000 army troops to the region to
begin spraying now that the four-month rainy season has ended,
Tsuzuki said.
   He said DDT is cheap and effective against the anopheles
mosquito, which carries malaria.
   The insecticide will not be used indiscriminately, but only to
spray inside the huts and lean-tos used by miners and settlers, he
said.
   He said World Bank loans will help pay for the DDT campaign.
   During the 1964-1985 military regime, the generals in power urged
poor Brazilians to settle in the undeveloped Amazon and offered
numerous tax incentives and state subsidies to ranchers and
developers.
   Since the drive began in the 1970s, the incidence of malaria has
risen more than 500 percent, the ministry says.
   Malaria causes fever and chills and a gradual weakening of the
body. It can be fatal if not treated. In Brazil, between 1 and 2
percent of those who get the disease die from it, Dr. Agostinho Cruz
Marquez of the ministry's Malaria Institute told the AP.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0179 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 2257EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-BigPrime    08-29 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Big Prime, </SECOND>
<HEAD>Researchers at Computer Manufacturer Say They've Got It</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Billion-Digit Pi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SUNNYVALE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers spent evenings and weekends
to find the world's largest known prime number, even though it has
no practical use, the company said Tuesday.
   ``It's like going to the moon, in a sense; there's not a lot
there, but it's important scientifically to do it because the
technology proves so useful,'' said Bodo Parady, one of six
researchers for Sunnyvale-based computer maker Amdahl Corp. who came
up with the number.
   There's no simple way to express the largest prime number. But it
equals 391,581 multiplied by 2 to the 216,193rd power, minus one.
   The number has 65,087 digits, 600 times as many as the number of
atoms in the known universe, according to Sergio E. Zarantonello,
another of the researchers.
   A prime number is any whole number greater than 1 that can only
be evenly divided by 1 or by itself. For example, 3, 5, 7, 11 and 17
are prime numbers.
   The new biggest known prime number, determined Aug. 6, beats the
record set in 1985 by David Slowinski of Cray Research Inc., the
U.S. supercomputer maker. The new number has 37 more digits and is a
trillion, trillion, trillion times larger.
   ``Searching for a largest known prime number is like looking for
a needle in a haystack, since only about one in 150,000 numbers is
prime in the region where the new record was found,'' Zarantonello
wrote in a company memo.
   The discovery was also announced at a meeting this week of the
American Mathematical Society.
   Although the number has no known practical application, the
standard advanced multiplication programs that were honed by Amdahl
scientists during the search already are being used by scientists
searching for pulsars, the company said.
   The process has other applications, particularly in cryptology
and in bank transaction coding. Both systems can depend on using
large prime numbers.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0180 </DOCNO>
