<FIRST>r a AM-TeacherStrikes     08-29 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Teacher Strikes,0213</SECOND>
<HEAD>Teachers Strike in Four States, Idle 37,000 Pupils</HEAD>
<HEAD>By The Associated Press</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Teachers strikes Tuesday idled more than 37,000 pupils in
Illinois, Michigan, Ohio and Pennsylvania, and one small district
that tried to hold classes was stymied by picket line violence.
   Three pickets in Indian Creek, Ohio, told police they were hit by
cars or a bus, and one teacher was arrested on charges of blocking a
bus and breaking a window. No serious injuries were reported, but
the school board voted to suspend classes until Tuesday because of
``the intensity of picket line activities'' said Superintendent
Charles Aguiar.
   Pay and benefits were the major strike issues for about 2,200
teachers who walked out in nine small districts in the four states.
   In northeast Ohio's Warren County, a district $6 million in debt,
550 teachers accepted a proposed two-year wage freeze but struck to
demand a 10 percent pay raise in the third year and an elementary
class size limit of 30 instead of 36.
   The strikes so far have spared any large school systems. But the
leadership of unions representing 4,700 teachers in two Sacramento,
Calif., area districts have voted to strike over pay on Sept. 5, the
first day of school for 94,000 pupils.
</TEXT>
