<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 2309EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-HazardousWasteBan     08-29 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Hazardous Waste Ban,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Alabama Bans Hazardous Wastes From 22 States, D.C.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PHILLIP RAWLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTGOMERY, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Alabama, one of the nation's biggest
dumping grounds for toxic waste, announced a ban Tuesday on
hazardous waste shipments from 22 states and the District of
Columbia.
   Gov. Guy Hunt said the ban _ the second in the nation _ was
necessary to prevent ``Alabama from becoming the waste dump of the
nation.''
   Alabama's ban mirrors one enacted earlier this year in South
Carolina. The Alabama ban takes effect Sept. 14, but may wind up in
court.
   Richard Fortuna, executive director of the Hazardous Waste
Treatment Council in Washington, said the lobbying group is
determined to overturn Alabama and South Carolina's laws. He said
the state laws violate federal interstate commerce statutes and will
produce a shortage of sites nationally to handle hazardous waste.
   ``It is virually certain we will challenge one,'' Fortuna said.
``The only question is whether we will challenge both.''
   According to figures compiled by state environmental officials,
Alabama is fourth in the amount of hazardous waste it gets from
other states. When the amount of waste shipped out of each state is
compared to the amount brought in, Alabama jumps to No. 2 in net
intake. Indiana is listed first in amount received as well as net
intake.
   Alabama's ban comes from a new state law that says states can't
ship hazardous wastes to Alabama if they don't allow for disposal of
hazardous wastes within their own borders or don't have a
cooperative agreement with Alabama. Alabama has signed no
cooperative agreements.
   The law was approved by the Legislature and the governor in May,
but the lawmakers left it up to the state Department of
Environmental Management to determine which states would be
affected. A list was released Tuesday.
   Sue Robertson, chief of the department's land division, said the
ban only affects a landfill at Emelle, which is the nation's largest
hazardous waste landfill. The law leaves it up to the landfill
operator, Chemical Waste Management, to deny shipments from the
banned states.
   Chemical Waste spokesman Chris Grimshawe said the company is
still studying the list and will decide whether to take legal action.
   A violation of the ban is punishable by up to 10 years in prison
and a $10,000 fine. The state could also go to court to seek civil
penalties of up to $25,000 per day per violation.
   Among the banned states, 18 and the District of Columbia have no
disposal facilities. They are Alaska, Arizona, Delaware, Florida,
Iowa, Kansas, Maine, Mississippi, Missouri, New Hampshire, New
Mexico, North Carolina, North Dakota, South Dakota, Vermont,
Virginia, West Virginia, and Wyoming.
   Idaho, Montana, Oregon and Washington state were banned because
they did not respond to the state's request for information about
hazardous waste disposal within their borders.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0184 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 2311EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Korea-Survey     08-29 0315</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea-Survey,0324</SECOND>
<HEAD>Survey Shows Most Koreans Believe U.S. Troops Should Stay</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Most South Koreans believe U.S. troops
should remain here to help defend their country, and 64 percent
worry North Korea may invade again, according to a survey published
Wednesday.
   The poll, conducted by independent Korea Research for the
Ministry of Culture and Information, said 94.07 percent of those
interviewed believe the 43,00 U.S. troops stationed in South Korea
under a mutual defense pact should stay.
   Radical students and dissidents, a small but vocal minority,
daily stage violent protests demanding the withdrawal of U.S. troops
whose presence they believe hinders unification with North Korea.
   Some U.S. politicians have said plans should be made for a
gradual phasing out of American troops because they consider South
Korea able to defend itself.
   According to the poll, only 5.93 percent of those questioned
support demands for immediate withdrawal of U.S. troops. And 81
percent feel conditions will change in 10 years and South Korea will
be able to defend itself.
   The Ministry of Culture and Information said the survey was
conducted among 1,500 South Koreans aged over 20 and randomly
selected from around the country between July 28 and Aug. 16.
   Details on polling techniques were not available and pollsters
did not figure a margin of error.
   North Korea invaded the South in 1950 to start a bloody
three-year war, and the poll said 84.2 percent of those polled feel
their country would have become communist if U.S. troops had not
helped. A cease-fire ended the war. But a peace treaty was never
signed and the two Koreas remain enemies.
   The survey said 64 percent of those questioned fear North Korea
may invade again, and 23 percent do not. It said 60.4 percent
believe North Korea has the capability to invade and 66.2 percent
think the North Koreans have better combat capability.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
