<FIRST>u a AM-UndergroundExplosions     08-29 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Underground Explosions,0407</SECOND>
<HEAD>Federal Agency Won't Use Ranch for Explosives Tests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLEY SHANNON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEL RIO, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A government agency is no longer
considering a ranch near this border city for underground explosives
tests, but agency officials said it's looking at another site in the
area.
   The Defense Nuclear Agency had been looking at a site on the Buck
King Ranch 25 miles northwest of Del Rio.
   ``I'm convinced that they are out _ out of Del Rio, out of Val
Verde County,'' Del Rio Mayor Alfredo Gutierrez Jr. said Monday
evening after the agency's announcement. ``I think we're through
with the DNA.''
   Gutierrez and other local leaders staged a rally against the
underground explosion testing, which some residents fear could
damage the city's sole source of drinking water, the San Felipe
Springs. Del Rio, with 40,000 residents, is in southwestern Texas,
on the U.S.-Mexico border.
   The series of blasts, known as ``DUGHEST'' for ``Deep Underground
High Explosive Simulation Test,'' are designed to simulate the
impact of nuclear explosions on subterranean missile silos. They
would start in 1990 with a 1,000-pound charge and culminate in
November 1992 with a 470-ton blast using conventional explosives,
federal officials have said.
   In a letter to congressional leaders, Vice Adm. John T. Parker
Jr. of the Defense Nuclear Agency said the Buck King Ranch was no
longer under consideration. He said the agency's preliminary
analysis of rock core from the ranch indicated it ``was less useful
for the experiment than we anticipated.''
   But he added, ``We are interested in investigating other Texas
sites, one of which is in western Val Verde County much farther from
Del Rio than the Buck King ranch.''
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who opposed the ranch site, said he
would try to block funding for the project if other sites in the
county are considered.
   ``If you do choose to proceed with an investigation of other test
sites in Val Verde County, however, you should know that I will
introduce an amendment to the Defense Department appropriations bill
to deny DNA the funding necessary to pursue this project,'' Gramm
wrote Parker.
   Potential damage to drinking water was the top concern among the
approximately 1,000 people attending Monday's demonstration.
   Sylvia Urby, a former city councilwoman, said ``We certainly
don't want this to happen to Del Rio _ our spring water is our life
here.''
</TEXT>
