<FIRST>r a AM-HUDIndictment     08-29 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD Indictment,0342</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former HUD Accountant Indicted in Alleged $1 Million Embezzlement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JULIA RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury on Tuesday indicted a former
Department of Housing and Urban Development accountant on charges he
embezzled more than $1 million in public funds intended for
low-income housing projects.
   Douglas R. Turner is accused of depositing into his private
account money from a program that gives developers subsidies to
build housing for low-income people, U.S. Attorney Mike Norton said
at a news conference.
   ``I believe it will be the first in a series of criminal
prosecutions in this HUD area,'' said Norton, referring to the
Colorado regional office.
   Colorado FBI chief Bob Pence said the Turner case, discovered
during a routine HUD audit, ``lifted the lid off what is beginning
to look ... like a mess.''
   HUD has been beset with allegations of fraud, embezzlemet and
influence peddling nationally during the Reagan administration.
Secretary Jack Kemp has promised reforms. He also has refused to
blame his predecessor, Samuel Pierce, who faces questioning before
Congress next month.
   Turner was arrested Tuesday and pleaded innocent before U.S.
Magistrate Donald Abram. He was released on $100,000 bond.
   The case is scheduled to be heard by Nov. 7 by U.S. District
Judge Jim R. Carrigan, who also is presiding over a civil case
against Turner.
   The civil lawsuit was filed by Norton's office Aug. 8, and seeks
to recover the allegedly embezzled funds. Turner, who was suspended
without pay June 4, and fired Aug. 8, was expected to respond to the
civil lawsuit by Sept. 5.
   Turner is accused of embezzling $1,006,130 from Dec. 1 through
May 22. Norton said federal agents recovered more than $480,000 in
money, securities and property. Turner, whose annual salary was
$28,000, had been building a suburban home valued at $450,000 or
more, the prosecutor said.
   If convicted, Turner could face a maximum penalty of 10 years in
prison and a $250,000 fine on each of six counts.
</TEXT>
