<FIRST>a a PM-BusinessMirror Adv30   08-29 0610</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Mirror, Adv 30,0627</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release PMs Wednesday, Aug. 30</HEAD>
<HEAD>Food, Glorious Food</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: John Cunniff is on vacation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If you would like a grand tour of some of the
most treasured assets of American industry, just take a stroll
through the aisles of your local supermarket.
   The soups, cereals, pet foods and frozen entrees come in packages
of many colors. But to the businesses that produce them, many are
solid gold.
   To get a financial slant on the modern food-processing industry,
consider how it has fared on Wall Street in the 1980s.
   The Value Line Investment Survey, the nation's largest investment
advisory service, notes that stocks of food manufacturers, which
have soared this year even faster than the market as a whole, are on
the way to their ninth straight year of ``outperforming'' the market
averages.
   ``In the 1980s, an investor could not have found a much more
fertile investment field,'' Value Line observed.
   That message hasn't gone unnoticed by the takeover artists and
speculators of Wall Street, who have made the food stocks one of
their most regular haunts. What attracts them is not only abundant
sales and profits, but the perception of precious assets waiting to
be mined.
   ``The most valuable asset of the typical leading food processor
can't even be found on its balance sheet,'' Value Line says.
   ``That asset is the portfolio of brand-name franchises. The buyer
is willing to pay a premium price for these names. That translates
into premium profits.''
   For a time during the 1960s and '70s, it looked as though the Big
Brand Name was a diminishing species in food and other
consumer-products businesses.
   The increasingly sophisticated shopper was discovering that a lot
of money could be saved by opting for a store's private label
merchandise or for ``generic'' goods in austere packages.
   But in the 1980s, hurried consumers looking for convenience and
reliability have evidently gone back to the names they know best.
   As a result, says Value Line, there is an unprecedented array
these days of powerful brand names in the nation's stores.
Food-processing companies are spending more and more of each sales
dollar on advertising and expanding old brand names and trying to
develop new ones.
   All this can have a self-reinforcing effect. When a brand attains
high status, the large sales volume that results often allows the
product to be made, packaged and sold at a lower cost per unit.
   At the same time, supermarkets and other retailers tend to give
more coveted shelf space to big-name brands. More shelf space, in
turn, contributes to still-higher sales.
   That is not to say, by any means, that this process happens
automatically. Armies of people are employed to nurture, protect and
promote packaged-food products and their names.
   Just imagine, for example, all the work that has gone n the past
few years into ``positioning'' existing food products and creating
new ones to meet changing consumer health concerns.
   When any business has been prospering for a long time, people
naturally begin to wonder if some lean years aren't due pretty soon.
But the way analysts see things now, prospects for food producers
and their big brands still look bright.
   The recession scare of the past few months has eased of late.
Even if a downturn comes, the food industry is historically
recession-resistant.
   At the investment firm of Merrill Lynch, which is projecting a
``mild, short-lived recession'' that might drag down profits
somewhat in more cyclical industries, analysts say, ``the earnings
reports of many food companies should sparkle against that dull
background.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv PMs Wednesday Aug 30</NOTE>
</DOC>
