<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1628EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-Wilderness-NewJersey Adv03   08-29 0504</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Wilderness-New Jersey, Adv 03,0521</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>A Green Oasis Just Miles From New York City</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-American Wilderness</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARDING TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Just 25 miles from the flashing
lights and honking horns of New York City's Times Square is a large,
green oasis filled with the lovely sounds of silence.
   The Great Swamp National Wildlife Refuge, situated in the heart
of congested northern New Jersey, was officially declared a
protected area in 1968 under the federal Wilderness Act.
   Since then, it has attracted urban and suburban residents looking
for a secluded escape. David Franz, a biology professor at Brooklyn
College, sometimes brings his students across the Hudson River to
study ``forest communities'' and analyze vegetation at the refuge.
   On his own time, he visits Great Swamp ``just for the beauty of
it all. Especially in the fall, when the foliage changes. On a
Sunday afternoon, I often see families stopping at the refuge after
church just to spend a few hours outside together.''
   The refuge is open from dawn to dusk seven days a week, said
Thomas McFadden, a recreation planner at Great Swamp. It might never
have opened at all.
   In the late 1950s, the Port Authority of New York and New Jersey
proposed building a jetport at the site.
   But local residents quickly formed a grassroots organization to
buy as much land as possible. Several years later, the newly formed
New Jersey Conservation Foundation gave the federal government the
deed to about 3,000 acres of prime, undeveloped land which formed
the heart of Great Swamp, McFadden said.
   The refuge's acreage keeps growing, with almost 7,000 acres now
protected and the acquisition of 2,000 more acres expected soon.
   About 3,660 acres of the refuge is untouched, with only seven
miles of trails for nature lovers to walk on, McFadden said. The
rest is a federal management area, where grass is mowed, ponds dug
and trees cut to encourage the breeding of certain animals and
plants, he said.
   ``It's unusual to find a fairly large tract of uninhabited
natural vegetation,'' Franz said appreciatively.
   Even though planes pass overhead and neighboring towns edge
closer, he said, ``You have the feeling you are a long distance from
mankind.''
   More than 160,000 people _ most from the New York metropolitan
area _ visit the Great Swamp each year, McFadden said.
   Unfortunately, unwanted visitors also come, said Douglas Spencer,
the refuge's assistant property manager. By day, passing vehicles
litter roads leading into the refuge, he said, and at night, illegal
dumpers have left even worse.
   Nearby development also has an impact. ``It causes non-point
pollution _ runoff from septic systems and the streets,'' Spencer
said.
   With each rainfall, pollutants such as roadway oils and treated
sewage effluent wash into the Passaic River watershed area, which
eventually passes through the refuge, Spencer said.
   ``Great Swamp acts as a giant filter,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 3</NOTE>
</DOC>
