<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0133EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessFailures     08-29 0294</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Failures,0303</SECOND>
<HEAD>First-Half Business Failures Down Sharply, Supporting `Soft Landing'
Theory</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Business failures fell by 14.5 percent in the
first half of 1989, the biggest drop in more than 10 years, Dun &amp;
Bradstreet Corp. said in a report that suggested the economy is not
tumbling into recession.
   ``The steady decline in business failures across the country
underscores the overall stability of the U.S. economy and offers
further support for the `soft-landing' scenario,'' said Joseph W.
Duncan, corporate economist and chief statistician for the
business-information company.
   A total of 26,234 companies failed in the first six months of
1989, vs. 30,697 in the first six months of 1988, D&amp;B said Monday in
its twice-yearly report on business failures. The figures reflect a
continuation of a trend that began in 1987 and showed a sharp
improvement in the weak farming and oil regions.
   Failures declined everywhere except in South Atlantic states, one
of the areas that has led an economic expansion now almost seven
years old. The number of failures in that region rose 10.2 percent
to 4.024 from 3,651.
   The area of greatest decrease was in the agricultural belt of the
western and north central states, where failures declined 31.3
percent, to 1,582 from 2,304.
   By industry, failures in the agriculture-forestry-fishing sector
fell 23.5 percent, failures in the mining sector fell 25.4 percent,
wholesale trade fell 23 percent, and services fell 23.8 percent.
   The only industry to report an increase in failures was the
finance, insurance and real-estate sector, where they rose 11.7
percent. D&amp;B attributed the rise to the thrift industry crisis and
scattered problems in the property business.
   Dun &amp; Bradstreet is the largest marketer of business information,
with wordwide revenue of $4.3 billion last year.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0206 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0134EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Soybeans-FarmGroups Bjt   08-29 0615</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soybeans-Farm Groups, Bjt,0634</SECOND>
<HEAD>Farm Groups Split Over Soybean Emergency Order</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ``Darl'' in 7th graf is cq.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The debate continues over whether the Chicago
Board of Trade should have ordered the emergency liquidation of July
soybean futures contracts.
   ``It's becoming more and more evident that the cost of this
liquidation was all put on the back of the producers,'' said John
White Jr. of the American Farm Bureau Federation.
   But Donald M. Mennel, an Ohio representative of the Millers'
National Federation, said he thought the BOT ``did a magnificent job
of moving very rapidly to stop something that could have gone
horribly wrong.''
   Mennel and White were among more than a score of farmers,
ranchers, exporters, grain dealers and elevator operators who
debated the soybean emergency action Monday at a meeting of the
Commodity Futures Trading Commission's agricultural advisory
committee.
   Last month, the Board of Trade issued an emergency order
requiring traders to reduce their holdings in soybean futures
contracts. The move brought howls of protest from farmers and
traders, who saw the value of their futures holdings plummet after
the order caused wild swings in soybean prices.
   The CBOT's action was taken after a U.S. affiliate of the Italian
grain conglomerate Ferruzzi Finanziaria SPA refused to liquidate its
dominant position in July soybeans. The action was seen as a move to
prevent Ferruzzi from cornering the soybean market, a plan which
Ferruzzi has denied.
   ``To decide what we decided was sort of like going against apple
pie,'' said Darl Kleinbach, a wheat farmer who also sits as a public
director on the CBOT and voted for the emergency action. But she
defended her vote as ``best for the farmer.''
   The American Agriculture Movement's Larry Mitchell told CFTC
officials, ``Farmers want to know, who did you protect with that
action?''
   ``The answer is the market,'' said John Mielke, CFTC director of
market surveillance, explaining that the agency's mission was to
preserve orderly markets. ``We have to be price neutral.''
   The CFTC, which oversees the futures industry, released its
preliminary findings Friday on the CBOT action. The CFTC found that
there was a ``reasonable basis for the emergency'' and that the
Board of Trade took appropriate action.
   The CFTC also said it found no evidence of self-dealing by CBOT
officials who might have profited by selling off their holdings
after voting to issue the emergency order.
   But farm group leaders remained skeptical.
   ``Their (farmers') perception now is that the market's been
manipulated by those internal forces and CFTC is part of that for
allowing the emergency action,'' said White of the American Farm
Bureau Federation.
   Roy Smith, a Nebraska soybean farmer and representative of the
American Soybean Association, told the CFTC's Mielke: ``To be honest
with you, the farmers are tired of hearing you guys say everything
is all right, of hearing the Board of Trade say it's all right.
We're getting a different perception out there.''
   The St. Louis-based American Soybean Association has formed its
own task force to probe the results of the emergency order.
   None of the CBOT directors who voted personally controlled a
position in July soybean futures, according to the CFTC.
   When several agricultural groups said they wanted more evidence
proving that there had been no inside trading by CBOT executives
either for their firm or their firm's customers, Mielke said he
doubted it would defuse conspiracy theories.
   ``I'm not sure the facts, even if they were laid out, would put
the questions to rest,'' said Mielke. ``I think people with theories
don't need facts.''
   ``I think you're underestimating the ability of farmers to
understand the facts,'' countered Smith.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890829-0207 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0134EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-Soviets-Agriculture     08-29 0359</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Soviets-Agriculture,0372</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Urges Increased U.S. Purchases From Soviet Union</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIANE DUSTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   House Agriculture Committee Chairman Kika de la
Garza, just back from a trip to the Soviet Union, says the United
States should import more Soviet goods in exchange for the
commodities the it sells that country.
   De la Garza, D-Texas, said Monday that his five-day visit made it
clear to him that the Soviet Union is a long way from becoming
self-sufficient in grain production and will continue to turn to the
United States for that commodity.
   He said the Soviet Union also could use other U.S. items but has
a hard time getting them because Soviet currency is not accepted and
the United States has shown little interest in Soviet products other
than vodka.
   ``Everything they need for the comfort of the creature, we could
sell them,'' said de la Garza. ``But they have no hard currency.''
   Agriculture Department officials say the Soviets buy American
grain with dollars that they can get by drawing upon their gold
reserves.
   De la Garza said that a better understanding is developing
between the United States and U.S.S.R.
   ``We need to look at how we can reshape our relations so we can
buy and sell,'' he said. ``We need to remove the feeling that all we
want to do is sell, sell, sell.''
   He said the first imports may be ``symbolic'' but would go a long
way toward achieving an arrangement that shows trade ``is a two-way
street.''
   The Soviets have an agreement with the United States that they
will buy at least 9 million tons of grain before Sept. 30. They have
already purchased 21.7 million tons of grain and corn and another 1
million tons of sorghum, says the Agriculture Department.
   Agriculture Committee members Reps. Dan Glickman, D-Kan., Jerry
Huckaby, D-La., Robin Tallon, D-S.C., Claude Harris, D-Ala. and
David Dreier, R-Calif., accompanied de la Garza on the trip.
   They did not see Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev but met with
other top officials to discuss agricultural reform and enhanced
trade between the two countries. They also visited cooperative farms
and markets.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
