<HEAD>Boeing Unit To Eliminate Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Boeing Aerospace and Electronics, a unit of Boeing
Co., said it will eliminate about 800 secretaries, engineers and
managers from its space and missile programs.
   Spokesman Dave Suffia said the company ``will make every effort''
to reassign affected employees to other jobs at Boeing. The cuts
will take effect over the next month, Boeing said.
   The reductions reflect the company's desire for greater
efficiency in the 22,000-person division in the face of defense
spending cuts and projections that Boeing will lose money on
government contracts this year.
   Employees at the Kent-based division were notified of the cuts on
Friday.
   The aerospace and electronics unit works on National Aeronautics
and Space Administration programs such as the space shuttle and the
space station.
   It also has military contracts, including a missile system for
the U.S. Navy, the Airborne Advanced Warning and Control System
(AWACS) and Strategic Defense Initiative programs.
   About 18,000 of the division's employees work in Washington state.
