<FIRST>r f PM-UnisysPresident     08-29 0387</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Unisys President,0400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Unisys Names Unruh President, Putting Him In Line For Top Job</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BLUE BELL, Pa. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Unisys Corp. officials hope a new president
can turn around the company's recent drop in earnings by focusing on
network computer systems and software.
   Unisys' board of directors Monday promoted James Unruh to
president and chief operating officer, putting him in line to
succeed the 63-year-old chairman and chief executive, Michael
Blumenthal.
   Before Unruh's promotion, the company had no president and chief
operating officer.
   ``His top priority will be to strengthen the company's financial
position by improving profitability and cash flow and to continue
the company's thrust into the faster-growing markets of distributed
network computing systems and software and services,'' Blumenthal
said in a news release.
   Unruh will handle all computer business except defense sales.
   Unruh, 48, beat out Curtis Hessler, 45, for the No. 2 job at the
computer giant. Hessler, who worked with Blumenthal when he was
Treasury secretary in the Carter administration, and Unruh, a former
Burroughs executive, were viewed as the two candidates to take over
when Blumenthal retires.
   Blumenthal, who engineered Burrough's takeover of Sperry to form
Unisys, has indicated he may step down in two years.
   Hessler was promoted from executive vice president to vice
chairman. Hessler's duties still include chief financial officer and
head of the Defense Systems Group.
   ``Curt Hessler is a key member of the management team and this
promotion recognizes the substantial contributions he has made and
the broad expertise he brings to the corporation,'' Blumenthal said.
   Unisys reported a 67 percent drop in earnings for the second
quarter. Blumenthal attributed the decrease to the expense of
cutting inventories, pricing pressures from competitors and the
temporary suspension of Unisys' defense business by the Pentagon.
The strong dollar also decreased the value of sales made in foreign
currencies, he said.
   For the second quarter, Unisys reported net income of $53.6
million, or 17 cents per share, on revenue of $2.57 billion. In the
second three months of 1988, net income totaled $162.3 million.
   The Unisys board also promoted Reto Braun to senior vice
president and named him president of the Americas-Pacific Division.
The new division combines the former Pacific-Asia Division and the
Americas Division. G. Graham Murphy, president of the Europe-Africa
division, was promoted to senior vice president.
</TEXT>
