<DOCNO> AP890829-0218 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 0918EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-Britain-Economy     08-29 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Britain-Economy,0413</SECOND>
<HEAD>British Economy Slows</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain is entering a period of slow investment
growth, modest increases in manufacturing output and subdued
consumer spending, the Confederation of British Industry said
Tuesday.
   The organization representing big business said manufacturers'
order books this month were below normal for the fourth consecutive
month while their output growth continued at rates much lower than a
year ago.
   David Wigglesworth, who heads the confederation's industrial
trends survey, said companies would trim spending to protect profit
margins.
   ``There is clearly a danger that in this process, investment will
be cut back, with a damaging effect on the nation's ability to
compete in international markets,'' he said.
   Analysts blame Britain's high 14 percent base bank lending rates
for most of the industrial and consumer spending slowdown.
   The Financial Times business daily said Tuesday that most
forecasting groups it surveyed expect the interest rates to remain
at about 14 percent for the rest of this year.
   ``Even in the last three months of 1990, interest rates of about
12 percent are expected,'' it said. ``Consumer spending is also
expected to slow dramatically ... After growing by about 3 percent
this year, the survey points to growth of only 1.7 percent in 1990,
the lowest annual growth rate since 1982.''
   The daily said inflation was expected to fall from a little below
7 percent in the last quarter of this year to just above 5 percent
in a year's time.
   However, it predicted exports would grow, reflecting expectations
of stronger economic growth in other countries.
   Britain had its second worst monthly trade deficit in July of 2.1
billion pounds, or $3.2 billion, suggesting the deficit for the year
will be around 20 billion pounds against the Treasury's official
forecasts of 14.5 billion pounds.
   The high interest rate, which is fixed by the government, is a
means of keeping the British pound strong in world currency markets
at a time of slow industrial growth.
   Anne Segall, a financial commentator, wrote Tuesday in the
conservative Daily Telegraph: ``While we were nearly 10 billion
pounds in deficit in the first six months of this year, West Germany
was 20 billion pounds in surplus ... Britain's deficit is eight
times as big as France's ... We are now overspending the equivalent
of 4 percent of gross domestic product ... We are in an even bigger
mess than the Americans.''
</TEXT>
