<FIRST>u f PM-NewspaperWar 1stLd-Writethru f0031 08-29 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Newspaper War, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0031,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dallas Times Herald Wins Restraining Order Against Rival Morning
News</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS 7th graf, `At the ..., to fix typo in spelling of hearing.
Pick up 8th graf, `The smaller ...</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dallas Times Herald won a temporary
restraining order barring its rival, The Dallas Morning News, from
publishing two dozen syndicated columns and comic strips beginning
next week.
   The question of who has publication rights to the features also
is under the scrutiny of a federal judge in Kansas City, where a
hearing was scheduled today.
   The features, including such items as ``Dear Abby'' and ``Tank
McNamara,'' would have disappeared from the Times Herald beginning
Sept. 3, had a contract obtained by the Morning News not been
challenged.
   Universal Press Syndicate, the Kansas City-based firm which
distributes the features, has sued the Times Herald under federal
copyright laws. A hearing on that suit is set for Friday.
   State District Judge David West in Houston said his restraining
order Monday could mean no Dallas newspaper will be carrying the
features and comics. ``Until the logjam is broken, that's what the
result is,'' he said.
   Last week, West declined to grant a similar temporary restraining
order sought by the Times Herald, citing an order by U.S. District
Judge D. Brook Bartlett that nothing be done to infringe the federal
judge's jurisdiction.
   At the Kansas City hearing today, attorneys for the Times Herald
were to seek to have Bartlett's order vacated, according to Times
Herald officials.
   The smaller Times Herald wants to prevent Morning News owner A.H.
Belo Corp. from acquiring exclusive Dallas-area rights to the 26
comics and features.
   Belo announced early this month it had formed a joint venture
with Universal Press to explore television programming possibilities
for some of the syndicate's features. As part of the agreement, Belo
_ which also owns Dallas' top-rated television station WFAA _
acquired exclusive rights to the syndicate's features.
   That prompted the suit from the Times Herald, which accused Belo
of unfairly increasing its influence in the Dallas market.
   Morning News attorney Paul Watler insisted the federal court's
jurisdiction should not be disturbed, but West said he felt he
needed to do something.
   ``I'm interested in the public rather than the parties,'' West
said. ``The public has a right to competing newspapers and has a
right to read these columns.''
   The legal actions are not the first involving the intense rivals.
Last year, the two newspapers settled a dispute over circulation
figures.
   According to Editor &amp; Publisher, the Morning News has a daily
circulation of 354,000 issues, to 224,000 for the Times Herald.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
