<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prices dipped in early trading on Wall Street
today after the government revised upward its estimate of economic
growth in the second quarter.
   The Dow Jones industrial average was off 6.66 to 2,736.70 as of
10 a.m.
   Declining issues were ahead of advancers by a margin of about 5
to 4, with 368 stocks rising, 462 falling and 502 unchanged on the
New York Stock Exchange.
   Volume after the first half-hour of trading came to 19.26 million
shares.
   The Commerce Department said the gross national product, the
broadest measure of the economy's performance, grew by 2.7 percent
from April through July, a significant change from the 1.7 percent
growth rate originally reported last month. The news eased fears
that the economy was slipping into a recession.
   The report also contained good inflation news. A closely-watched
gauge tied to the GNP indicated inflation did not worsen during the
second quarter despite the strength in the economy.
   But on Wall Street, the news ``was a non-event,'' said market
analyst Michael Metz of Oppenheimer &amp; Co.
   Traders were pleased that the GNP figures indicated there was no
real pressure on inflation or interest rates, but the report
``happens at a moment when we've had a generous markup in stocks and
we're due for a correction,'' Metz said.
   However, he said, this report was not likely to spark a decline.
   The most actively-traded issue on the NYSE in the early going was
Ford Motor, which fell { to 52{.
   Among other blue chip issues, AT&amp;T was unchanged at 40[ and Exxon
was down [ to 43~.
   The NYSE's composite index of all its listed stocks was down 0.10
to 195.35. On the American Stock Exchange, the market value index
slipped 0.27 to 381.40.
   On Monday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 11 to a record
2,743.36.
   Volume on the Big Board totaled 131.18 million shares compared to
165.93 million shares on Friday.
   Advancing issues outnumbered declined in nationwide trading of
NYSE-listed issues, with 760 up, 692 down and 537 unchanged.
   The NYSE composite index gained 0.66 to 195.45.
