<FIRST>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   08-29 0314</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0327</SECOND>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Little Changed In Early Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures prices were little
changed in early trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade with
corn and soybeans up slightly and wheat futures a bit lower.
   The early gains in the corn and soybean markets reflected
followthrough buying from Monday's late comeback.
   Growing fears of an early frost in the Midwest also supported the
corn and soybean markets, said Jon Horton of Research Department
Inc., a Chicago-based market-analysis firm.
   The summer's unusually cool temperatures have prompted some
private meteorologists to declare a better-than-average chance of a
crop-damaging early frost in the Grain Belt.
   ``It could happen, and if it does, it will definitely affect the
beans and corn,'' Horton said. ``A lot of corn was late-planted this
year.''
   Wheat futures were weaker on expectations that a large number of
delivery notices will be posted Thursday against the soon-to-expire
September wheat contract.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1 cent lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.87{ a bushel; corn was \
cent to 2 cents higher with September at $2.33 a bushel; oats were {
cent to 1} cents higher with September at $1.35{ a bushel; soybeans
were { cent to 2{ cents higher with September at $5.78{ a bushel.
   Livestock and meat futures were mixed in early trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .12 cent lower to .48 cent higher with September
at 73.50 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .07 cent lower to .23
cent higher with August at 83.45 cents a pound; hogs were .02 cent
lower to .08 cent higher with October at 40.60 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .25 cent to .80 cent higher with February at 41.35
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled mostly lower on Monday.
</TEXT>
