<FIRST>u f BC-BritishStocks 1stLd-Writethru f0027 08-29 0220</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-British Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0027,0225</SECOND>
<HEAD>London Shares Decline in Thin Trading</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: RECASTS throughout to UPDATE with later activity, closing indices;
No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Share prices declined Tuesday in thin trading on
the London Stock Exchange.
   Dealers said the downturn was set in motion when market players
trimmed prices in a bid to shake out sellers.
   Market sentiment also was hurt by a weak opening on Wall Street,
traders said. Several attempts to start a rally during the London
afternoon failed to gather momentum, they noted.
   ``There was very little corporate or economic news out today, and
I think the market's lackluster tone is likely to continue all
week,'' said one dealer.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-share index ended 16.6
points, or 0.6 percent, lower at 2,380.8, down from the day's high
of 2,394.4. At its lowest, the index touched 2,378.5, a fall of 18.9
points.
   Volume was a slim 383.1 million shares, down from 431.2 million
traded on Friday. The London financial markets were closed Monday
for a bank holiday.
   At the close of trading, the narrower Financial Times 30-share
index was down 8.3 points at 1,972.7. The Financial Times-500 index
was 1,329.63, down 8.12.
   At the London close, the Dow Jones average of 30 industrials in
New York was 7.23 points lower at 2,736.13.
</TEXT>
