<FIRST>u f BC-BoardofTrade Close   08-29 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0254</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soybean Futures Rise; Wheat Drops</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed moderately higher in
light trading Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade, boosted by a
government report showing less improvement in the U.S. soybean crop
than traders had expected.
   Wheat futures closed lower amid expectations that a large number
of delivery notices will be posted Thursday against the
soon-to-expire September contract, and corn futures finished nearly
unchanged.
   The Agriculture Department's weekly crop condition report,
released late Monday, showed less improvement in the soybean crop
last week than traders had expected, given the amount of rain that
fell in the Midwest during the period.
   The government said the portion of soybeans in fair condition
rose to 52 percent from 46 percent but the change in the ``good''
and ``excellent'' categories was negligible.
   ``The market thought it would be a little better than it came
out; that's what you got most of your buying off of today,'' said
Jon Horton of Research Department Inc., a market analysis firm based
in Chicago.
   At the close of trading, wheat was 4\ cents lower to 2 cents
higher with the contract for delivery in September at $3.84\ a
bushel; corn was \ cent lower to 1\ cents higher with September at
$2.32\ a bushel; oats were { cent lower to { cent higher with
September at $1.34\ a bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents to 7{ cents
higher with September at $5.80{ a bushel.
</TEXT>
