<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1941EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-ToyRecall     08-29 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Toy Recall,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Consumers to Get Refunds for Recalled Toy Gun</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A manufacturer has agreed to give refunds to
people who bought a pistol-shaped juice container for children that
has been recalled, the state attorney general's office said Tuesday.
   Mackie International Inc., based in Santa Fe Springs, Calif.,
reached an agreement with the U.S. Consumer Product Safety
Commission early this month to recall the toy, called Chilly Bang
Bang. It had sold 578,688 of them in New York between April and June.
   The federal and state agreements were based on a plastic piece on
the toy that could choke young children. However, the company agreed
to discontinue sales on June 2 because of complaints about teaching
children to put guns in their mouths.
   The agreement released by the attorney general's office said the
product's wrapper pictures a boy with the barrel of the Chilly Bang
Bang in his mouth, and the directions, ``Twist Tip of Barrel.
Squeeze and Drink!''
   A three-eighths of an inch, plastic piece must be removed from
the barrel before drinking the liquid inside.
   ``This plastic piece is easily broken off the barrel when twisted
or bitten by a child,'' the attorney general's office said. ``This
circular plastic piece, because of its size, can be aspirated by a
child under the age of three and thus presents a choking hazard.''
   After the soft drink is gone, the container can be used as a
water gun.
   Mackie, which admitted no wrongdoing, has agreed to immediately
stop selling or distributing Chilly Bang Bang in New York.
   It also will direct its wholesale customers to pull the product
from their shelves; display a poster about the choking hazard; run
advertisements in local papers; and give refunds to customers who
return the product. Leslie Gersing, a spokesman for the attorney
general's office, said those provisions were not included in the
federal agreement.
   Mackie also must file an affidavit in 180 days detailing its
compliance with the New York agreement.
   The product also was sold in California, Michigan, Mississippi
and Pennsylvania.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
