<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-29 0512</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Drops; Gold Rises</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Precedes LONDON-BC</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar fell sharply in active trading Tuesday
despite favorable government reports on the economy.
   Gold prices rose as a result.
   On the Commodity Exchange in New York, gold bullion for current
delivery closed at $363.60 a troy ounce, up $3.60 from late Monday.
Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late bid for gold of
$362 an ounce, up $3.
   Currency dealers attributed the dollar's selloff in the United
States and abroad largely to sentiment that the U.S. currency had
been overbought. Many traders stocked up on dollars Monday in
anticipation of a favorable revision to the second-quarter gross
national product report, which is the broadest measure of economic
growth.
   The government said Tuesday that the economy grew at a healthy
2.7 percent annual rate in the spring. The GNP revision was far
higher than the previously estimated 1.7 percent rate but also in
line with market expectations.
   ``You buy on rumor and sell on fact,'' said Robert Ryan, a senior
currency trader for Irving Trust Co. in New York. ``What happened
was the market just squared up and dumped.''
   In another positive economic report Tuesday, the government said
sales of new homes shot up 14.4 percent in July, the biggest monthly
gain in almost three years.
   Currency dealers say they are now awaiting data on July factory
orders, August unemployment and the July index of leading
indicators, which are three of several other reports due out this
week.
   In Tokyo, where trading ends before Europe's business day begins,
the dollar fell 0.13 Japanese yen to a closing 144.15 yen. It was
quoted lower in London at 143.90 yen, and in New York at 143.01 yen,
down from 144.52 yen late Monday.
   The dollar declined against the British pound. It cost $1.5845 to
buy one pound in London, up from $1.5635 late Monday in Europe.
Sterling fetched $1.5870 in New York, more than $1.5636 late Monday.
   The financial markets were closed Monday in London for a bank
holiday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Monday,
included: 1.9362 West German marks, down from 1.9638; 1.6704 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6925; 6.5285 French francs, down from 6.6160;
1.1754 Canadian dollars, up from 1.1717; and 1,391.25 Italian lire,
down from 1,406.375.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Monday, included:
1.9375 West German marks, down from 1.9650; 1.6685 Swiss francs,
down from 1.6940; 6.5325 French francs, down from 6.6180; 2.1940
Dutch guilders, down from 2.2130; 1.1724 Canadian dollars, down from
1.1753; and 1,396.00 Italian lire, down from 1,408.00.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid of $364.00 an ounce compared
with late Friday's $360.45. In Zurich, Switzerland, gold closed at
$360.75 an ounce, up from $359.25 late Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold fell $1.29 to close at $360.82 an
ounce.
   Silver prices rose. On New York's Comex, silver for current
delivery rose to $5.091 a troy ounce from $5.090 late Monday. Silver
rose in London to $5.15 an ounce from Friday's $5.13.
</TEXT>
