<FIRST>u f AM-Ardent-Stellar     08-29 0397</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ardent-Stellar,0411</SECOND>
<HEAD>Merger Expected Between Stellar And Japanese-Backed Ardent</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: News conference is scheduled for 1 p.m. EDT Wednesday</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stellar Computer Inc. and its Japanese-backed
rival, Ardent Computer Corp., are expected to announce a merger
Wednesday of two of the top makers of expensive graphics
minisupercomputers, according to sources close to the deal.
   The companies, which normally steer clear of each other, have
called a news conference Wednesday in New York that will be attended
by chief executives of both companies.
   Sources close to the deal said both privately held companies are
losing money and are hoping that by uniting they will be able to
stave off mounting competition from other rivals, particularly
Silicon Graphics Inc.
   Computers made by Ardent and Stellar have list prices of roughly
$100,000 and can be used by only one person at a time, usually a
highly paid scientist or engineer, so they have a limited market.
Sales of each company are about $20 million a year.
   Graphics minisupercomputers are used for jobs that require heavy
calculation and detailed, three-dimensional displays, such as
analyzing the way air flows over turbine blades in jet engines or
the molecular structure of pharmaceuticals.
   Ardent and Stellar are remarkably similar, both founded a month
apart at the end of 1985 and both having about 210 employees. The
biggest difference is that Ardent has the backing of Japan's Kubota
Ltd., a maker of tractors and industrial equipment, which is a more
patient investor than most American venture capitalists.
   Kubota owns about 44 percent of Ardent. It was not clear Tuesday
how much it will own of the combined companies.
   A source familiar with the deal said the combined company
probably would try to save money by merging the two product lines,
combining the chip design used by Ardent with the graphics system
used by Stellar. That could be bad for Stellar's current customers,
because their software would not run on the Ardent chip.
   Stellar is based in Newtown, Mass., and is headed by J. William
Poduska, its founder, chairman and chief executive. He previously
co-founded Prime Computer Inc. and Apollo Computer Inc.
   Ardent Computer Corp., based in Sunnyvale, Calif., has Allen H.
Michels as its president and chief executive. Michels is founder and
former president of Convergent Technologies Inc., which is now part
of Unisys Corp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
