<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 1958EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-SundstrandRetirement     08-29 0264</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Sundstrand Retirement,0273</SECOND>
<HEAD>Sundstrand Chairman Retires But Will Remain on Board</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCKFORD, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Don R. O'Hare, chairman of Sundstrand
Corp.'s board of directors, is retiring as an employee and company
officer, the aerospace contractor announced Tuesday.
   O'Hare, 67, will remain chairman of the board.
   ``In order to assist in the orderly transition of management and
respnsibilities, Mr. O'Hare will act as a consultant to Harry C.
Stonecipher, president and chief executive officer of the company,
for one year beginning October 1989 and will continue as a member of
the board of directors serving as its chairman,'' the company said
in a statement.
   O'Hare started as an engineering and marketing trainee for
Sundstrand in 1950. He rose through the ranks, and was appointed
chairman of the board on Jan. 1.
   His retirement is not related to Sunstrand's legal problems, said
spokesman Claude Vernam.
   ``Absolutely not related at all,'' said Vernam. ``He's 67, which
makes him two years beyond the normal retirement date.''
   Sundstrand, based in this northern Illinois city, pleaded guilty
to federal contract fraud last October and agreed to pay a $115
million fine _ the largest fraud settlement in Defense Department
history. Several managers were subsequently fired.
   The government said Sundstrand overbilled the department for
aircraft parts and obtained contracts by underbidding actual costs
and attempting to recover them through overhead accounts set up for
other purposes.
   On Jan. 26, Sundstrand agreed to pay an additional $62.3 million
to the Pentagon and make cost-saving concessions on future contracts
that one federal official estimated could be worth an additional $34
million.
</TEXT>
