<FILEID>AP-NR-08-29-89 2120EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f BC-DuPont-Emissions     08-29 0169</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Du Pont-Emissions,0174</SECOND>
<HEAD>Du Pont's Air Emissions Down 8 Percent in 1988</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WILMINGTON, Del. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Du Pont Co. reported an 8 percent
reduction in toxic air emissions and a 45 percent drop in toxic
water emissions in 1988 from its more than 80 plants and refineries
located around the country.
   In a statement Tuesday about its report to the U.S. Environmental
Protection Agency on 1988 emissions, the company said the drop
occurred despite a 5 percent increase in production from a year
earlier.
   Land disposal increased 17 percent, Du Pont said. Ninety-eight
percent of land disposal is to deep wells on Du Pont property using
special geologic formations about a mile below the earth's surface.
   Increases in land disposal were for ammonium sulfate,
hydrochloric acid and metal salts, said Bruce Karrh, Du Pont vice
president for safety, health and environmental affairs.
   Du Pont's total waste management program calls for reductions of
process wastes from 1982 to 1990, plus at least the same amount
during the next decade.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
